<HEADLINE> China Planning On Cleaning Up Bohai Bay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 8 (Xinhua) -- China plans to improve the
environmental quality of the Bohai Bay in the north in ten years
and to finish cleaning it in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The Deputy-director of the Environmental Protection
Administration, Zhu Guangyao, told a conference on marine
environmental protection here today that they will focus on land
polluters, major sea areas, and the mouths of river and will have
strict controls on the emission of certain pollutants like
nitrogen and phosphorus.
</P>
<P>
Laizhou, Bohai, and Liaodong bays, the sea area around 13 major
cities, and the mouths of the Liaohe, Haihe and Yellow rivers are
included in the state anti-pollution plan.
</P>
<P>
China plans to make all factories, ships, and other polluters
in the area meet emission standards by the year 2005 to stop the
deterioration of the marine and the terrestrial ecology.
</P>
<P>
They expect to improve the area's environmental quality and
ecosystem by the year 2010 and to clean the sea by the year 2030,
Zhu says.
</P>
<P>
The Bohai Bay has a 77,000-sq km area. Because of rapid
economic growth along the coast, and the narrow bay mouth,
pollution problems have become even more serious. Some 2.8 billion
tons of industrial waste sewage and more than 700,000 tons of
various kinds of pollutants are discharged into it each year,
damaging fishery resources, causing marine disasters, and even
threatening the health of humans.
</P>
<P>
A technical group will be formed for the cleaning project.
</P>
</TEXT>
