<HEADLINE> Four Kidnapped Foreigners Found Killed in Chechnya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The bodies of three Britons and
a New Zealander kidnapped in Chechnya in October were found near
the Russian republic's border, Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov
confirmed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It was believed to be the first killing of foreign hostages in
Chechnya. All other foreigners have been released following
lengthy talks and, possibly, the payment of ransoms.
</P>
<P>
British citizens Peter Kennedy, Darren Hickey and Rudolf
Petschi and New Zealander Stanley Shaw, who were installing a
cellular telephone system under a contract with a privately owned
Chechen phone company, Chechentelekom, were kidnapped on October 3
in Grozny.
</P>
<P>
The bodies were decapitated, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Maskhadov blamed the murders on outside forces vying for
influence over the Caucasus and their henchmen in Chechnya, lured
by the large sums of money paid to them.
</P>
<P>
The breakaway republic has been plagued by abductions in recent
years. Kidnap victims included federal government officials,
ordinary residents and foreigners.
</P>
<P>
Russian Deputy Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo said in
November that some 700 people were being kept hostage in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
Organized criminal groups have distributed profitable
operations, some doing kidnapping, others whisking hostages away
while still others "providing maintenance, medical service and
food", Rushailo said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
