<HEADLINE> AT&AMP;T to Buy Network Business from IBM for $5 Billion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, December 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. communications giant AT&AMP;T
and big computer maker IBM announced on Tuesday that AT&AMP;T will
acquire IBM's Global Network business for 5 billion U.S. dollars
in cash.
</P>
<P>
The move will enhance AT&AMP;T's ability to supply its customers
with high speed data services and Internet access and will
increase its revenue, with an estimated additional 2.5 billion
dollars in the first full year of operation.
</P>
<P>
The network enables users to link computers in different
places of the world to accept orders from customers and to connect
to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The acquisition will enable AT&AMP;T to compete more effectively
with strong rivals for the provision of global managed data
network services, said AT&AMP;T chairman and CEO Michael Armstrong.
</P>
<P>
IBM's network business has one million Internet users and
business customers in many countries.
</P>
<P>
IBM, which will focus on computer services, said this
transaction is not expected to have a significant impact on the
company's 1999 operational results.
</P>
<P>
The two companies expect the acquisition to be completed by
mid-1999, following clearance by U.S. regulators and certain
regulatory authorities abroad.
</P>
<P>
The two also agreed to another deal which allows IBM to manage
AT&AMP;T's computers in long-distance business customer services for 4
billion dollars over 10 years, and allows AT&AMP;T to run the network
enabling IBM customers to transmit data with a 5 billion dollars
revenue over five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
