<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Film Star, Great Singer to Attend U.N. Gala </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Film Star Michael
Douglas and famous singer Luciano Pavarotti are among the
luminaries who will help U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and
United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights, Mary Robinson,
mark the 50th anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human
Rights.
</P>
<P>
Events commemorating the adoption of the Declaration in Paris
on December 10, 1948, as well as the announcement of six
recipients of the United Nations Human Rights Prize, will take
place throughout the day on Thursday at the U.N. headquarters in
New York, U.N. officials said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
December 10 is celebrated annually as the World Human Rights
Day, and the world day this year coincides with the 50th
anniversary of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, the most
comprehensive and widely recognized international standards for
the protection of civil, political, social, cultural and economic
rights.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, diplomats at the U.N. headquarters are expected to
attend the world premiers screening of the United Nations
documentary on the Universal Declaration of Human Rights, "For
everyone, everywhere" -- with rare archival materials, interviews
with surviving participants in the preparation of the Declaration,
contemporary footage shot on four continents.
</P>
<P>
Newly designed "children's passports," with the text of the
Universal Declaration printed inside, will be presented to an
assemblage of children on Thursday afternoon, the officials said,
adding that this new kind of passports will be distributed
internationally.
</P>
<P>
Adopted in the aftermath of World War II, the Declaration was
intended to prevent a repetition of the horrors of the Holocaust
and other atrocities.
</P>
<P>
Beginning with the pronouncement that "all human beings are
born free and equal in dignity and rights," the U.N. document set
out to cover the range of human existence. It has become at once
the most quoted international document of modern times. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lesotho's Election Monitoring Body to Be in Place </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho's Interim
Political Authority (IPA), which will be in charge of
preparations for the mountain kingdom's fresh election within 18
months, will be sworn in on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The swearing-in ceremony for the 24-member body will take
place at the high court in Maseru, capital of Lesotho, at 10 a.m.
Wednesday, South African Press Association reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
It was delayed by the death of leader of the Basotholand
National Party, a major opposition party, Retselisitsoe
Sekhonyana, who was buried over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
South African Safety and Security Minister Sydney Mufamadi is
expected to travel to Maseru on Thursday morning to chair the
inaugural meeting of the IPA.
</P>
<P>
Mufamadi, who has been leading a negotiation team of the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) on Lesotho, will
chair the meeting until members elected a new chairman.
</P>
<P>
South Africa and Botswana sent troops to Lesotho in September
to help quell nationwide riots there, which were sparked by
protests of opposition parties. The opposition parties claimed
the country's May election was rigged in favor of the ruling
Lesotho Congress for Democracy (LCD). 
</P>
</TEXT>
