<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Developing Countries Face Challenge: Zimbabwean </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Developing countries face
numerous constraints that threaten their survival as independent
nations, Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In his wide-ranging speech at the on-going eighth assembly of
the World Council of Churches (WCC) in Harare, Mugabe said one
such constraint was the unequal allocation of resources,
primarily land.
</P>
<P>
A total of 4,000 white commercial farmers in Zimbabwe held
half of the arable land while about 11 million Zimbabweans were
in the other half.
</P>
<P>
It was not unusual to find individuals owning four to six big
farms amounting to several thousands of hectares when black
communal families toil on allotments of not more than five acres
each, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to the president, it was not fair to label the
country unjust when it demanded land reform or accused him of
"larceny, tyranny, brutality and racism" because of the land
issue.
</P>
<P>
Developing countries also face the debt burden, unequal terms
of trade and depressed commodity prices...all these are wrecking
their economies, said Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
Referring to Africa, he said: "We face conflict situations in
Somalia, Guinea Bissau, the Democratic Republic of Congo, Sudan,
Rwanda and Burundi. We have also an inter-state conflict
situation between Ethiopia and Eritrea."
</P>
<P>
He pledged that Zimbabwe will continue to work for peace on
this continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
