<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB Offers Loan to Nepal for Betterment of Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) Tuesday approved a loan of 20 million U.S. dollars to assist
the Nepali government in promoting the socio-economic status and
employment of rural women, the bank said in a press release.
</P>
<P>
The Rural Microfinance Project, for which the loan has been
approved, will provide a revolving line of credit of 16.5 million
dollars to finance viable farm and off-farm economic activities
for the rural population, the majority of them poor women, in some
26 of the 75 districts in Nepal, the bank said.
</P>
<P>
"The project will also support a program for assessing and
identifying local investment opportunities for women, mobilizing
women and improving their skills and capabilities, supporting
their access to markets and providing financial services," it
added.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that under the project, about 270,000 potential
borrowers, mostly women, will receive training on social
awareness, empowerment of women, selection of women's economic
activities, control by women over their financial resources and
basic bookkeeping and accounting.
</P>
<P>
It said that the loan of 20 million dollars is interest-free
and repayable within 40 years including a grace period of 10
years. The loan carries a service charge of one percent per annum.
</P>
<P>
The project, which costs a total of 30.6 million dollars, is
expected to be implemented in early 1999 and completed by December
2004, the ADB said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said that it has been providing some 205 million
dollars assistance to the Nepali government for developing the
rural finance sector since 1970 under various programs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
