<HEADLINE> UK Seeks Truth Behind Hostages Death in Chechenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The United Kingdom government
pledged on Tuesday to find out what had happened to the three
British hostages reported dead in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
"We need to know... what is being done to bring to justice
those who committed such repugnant murders," Foreign Secretary
Robin Cook said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Officials in Chechenya, a breakaway republic in Russia, had
said earlier that the three bodies found by a road near the
Chechen border were those of British hostages.
</P>
<P>
Cook said the British government was still seeking
confirmation. But he admitted at the same time it was almost
certain that they belong to the three British men who were
captured by unknown gunmen on October 3 in the Chechen capital
city of Grozny.
</P>
<P>
The hostages, three Britons and one New Zealander, were working
for a British telecommunications firm when they were captured. The
firm issued a statement on Tuesday, saying that it had been in
contact with the kidnappers and had received confirmation last
week that the hostages were still alive. 
</P>
