<HEADLINE> Surprises Rule Shooting Range at Asiad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
by sportswriter Cao Li
</P>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Surprises and "black horses"
are the themes at the Hua Mark Sports Center shooting range when
unheralded shooters from central Asian nations won the day's two
individual titles.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan's Dina Aspandiyarova took the women's air pistol
gold while Turkmenistan's Igor Pirekeev won the men's free rifle
prone.
</P>
<P>
"I am not satisfied with my result," said Aspandiyarova after
scoring 486.8 points to beat the Asian Games record set by China's
Wang Lina in Beijing in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Chinese shooters carried home the silver and bronze medals,
with Cai Yeqing notching 486.0 points and Ren Jie registering
484.6.
</P>
<P>
The team title went to China, who scored 1,151 to improve on
their own Asian record of 1,138. Kazakhstan was second at 1,148
while South Korea third at 1,133.
</P>
<P>
In men's rifle prone, Pirekeev scored 104.2 points in the final
for a total of 697.2 points to grab his first international title.
</P>
<P>
Pirekeev, an Atlanta Olympian who registered 593 points to top
the qualification here, produced stable performance to lead all
the way to the title in the final.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's Tavarit Majcharcheep won the silver medal with 693.3
points, followed by Japan's bronze medalist Naoki Kurita at 691.1.
</P>
<P>
In the team event, Majcharcheep, Nopparat Yavilaspradit and
Samarn Jongsuk score a total of 1,758 to give the host country
Thailand its second shooting gold following Monday's victory in
women's air rifle.
</P>
<P>
Kyrgyzstan carried home the silver medal with 1,752 points,
only 1 point ahead of China, who won the bronze at 1,751.
</P>
<P>
The clay target men's skeet title was won by Kazakhstan's Sergy
Yakshin, who smashed Games record with 149 hits.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah Al-Rashidi of Kuwait was second while China's Li Xu
third.
</P>
<P>
The team title was won by Kuwait, followed by China and
Kazakhstan at second and third places. 
</P>
</TEXT>
