<HEADLINE> Blair Says Sino-British Relation Getting Much </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair said Tuesday that Britain and China have established a new
relationship not only on economic but also on political level.
</P>
<P>
Blair made the remarks at the conference entitled "China and
Britain: Grasping The Opportunity" organized by China-Britain
Business Council.
</P>
<P>
On his successful visit to China in October, Blair said,
although he was only able to visit Beijing, Shanghai and Hongkong,
he was "tremendously impressed" by the visible evidence of China's
rapid economic development.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the future of bilateral relationship, Blair said:
"Britain and China can both take satisfaction over the successful
handover of Hongkong. We can now build a new relationship
unhindered by the legacy of history."
</P>
<P>
As far as the economic and commercial relations are concerned,
Blair said, the prospects are "limitless". Britain remains by far
the largest European investor in China with over 12 billion U.S.
dollars and contracted investment so far and more than 2,000
British joint ventures.
</P>
<P>
However, he argued: "Britain can and should be doing better
with its exports. These grew by 25 percent in 1997, but have
slowed down this year, and Asia's recession is likely to make
things tougher still in future."
</P>
<P>
Blair expressed the hope that the improved relationship between
Britain and China and the combined efforts of the British
government and business circles can lead to a significant upsurge
in its exports to China.
</P>
<P>
Blair reiterated that Britain's aim is nothing less than to
make it China's number one business partner in Europe for both
trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
"This may be a demanding target, but it is not an impossible
one," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
