<HEADLINE> India's Congress Party Offers Constructive </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- India's biggest opposition,
the Congress, Tuesday offered constructive cooperation with the
central government led by the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) on
issues of vital interests to the country.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the first general body meeting of the Congress Party
in Parliament (CPP), Congress president Sonia Gandhi gave no
indication that her party was eager to take over the central
government.
</P>
<P>
Following spectacular victories of the Congress in recent
assembly elections in four states, there have been speculations on
what the party's victories mean for the political situation at the
national level.
</P>
<P>
"We will continue to offer the government constructive
cooperation on issues of vital interests to the nation but we
stand prepared to discharge our constitutional obligations as and
when the situation requires us to do so," Sonia said.
</P>
<P>
Maintaining that the current political and economic situation
continued to cause extreme worry, she said India was now governed
by "an unstable coalition in which policy making is at a premium
and even minimum consensus on national issues does not exist".
</P>
<P>
"There are deep divisions in the BJP itself which make it
impossible for the ruling coalition to deliver effective
governance," she said, adding that it could only compound miseries
of people who continue to be oppressed by high prices, lack of law
and order and deteriorating civic services.
</P>
<P>
The Congress leader said that there had been no evidence of
what the people expected of the coalition that "a government that
governs and an administration that administers" in the last eight
months since the BJP came to power in March.
</P>
<P>
Instead, Sonia said, it was immature and irresponsible for the
government to blame others for its own shortcoming.
</P>
<P>
There were signs to suggest that the absence of governance, the
confusion and lack of decisiveness of the BJP-led coalition in the
past several months had brought the country close to an economic
crisis like the one in 1991, she said.
</P>
<P>
On the state assembly elections towards the end of last month,
she said it was an "encouraging sign" that Congress' traditional
support base among the poor, the Dalits, adivaisis and the
minorities was returning to the party fold.
</P>
<P>
She asked parliament members of the Congress to remain vigilant
as the current session of Parliament, which began Monday, was
"crucial" with the ruling BJP emerging as a divided house and its
allies speaking in different voices. 
</P>
</TEXT>
