<HEADLINE> U.S. Envy Holbrooke to Visit Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. presidential envoy for
Cyprus, Richard Holbrooke, will visit Greece next Monday as part
of his diplomatic efforts to break the impasse of the Cyprus
problem.
</P>
<P>
Announcing this at a press briefing, Greek government spokesman
Dimitris Reppas on Tuesday described the strong interest showed by
the international community in resolving the Cyprus issue as "a
positive sign." This should move in the framework defined by the
United Nations, he added.
</P>
<P>
Holbrooke will also visit Turkey and Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Turkish Cypriots-controlled
north and the Greek Cypriots-dominated south in 1974 when Turkish
troops invaded and occupied the northern third of the island in
the wake of a failed coup seeking union with Athens.
</P>
<P>
While blaming Turkey and northern Cyprus for being responsible
for the deadlock of the Cyprus problem, both Greece and Cyprus
have recently expressed their disappointment to the U.S. over the
lack of progress towards settlement of the Cyprus issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
