<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0030 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Crisis Blamed for S. Africa's Sluggish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The South African Reserve
Bank Tuesday attributed South Africa's stalled economic growth
this year to the Asian crisis, saying the crisis in Asia led to
speculative attacks on the local financial market which severely
hurt the economy.
</P>
<P>
Although South Africa's macro-economic stability is not in
doubt and the financial system is fundamentally sound, the
country could not escape the spill-over effects of the Asian
crisis, the central bank said in its latest quarterly review.
</P>
<P>
The country's economic growth fell to a negative 2.3 percent
in the third quarter this year, down from the 0.5 percent growth
in the first quarter and 0.3 percent in the second.
</P>
<P>
Some of the reasons why Asia contagion affected monetary and
economic conditions in South Africa were the low domestic savings
ratio, the inability to attract sustained foreign direct
investment and the paucity of international reserves, South
African Press Association quoted the bank as saying.
</P>
<P>
The high ratio of short-term external debt to international
reserves and falling commodity prices also worsened the
situation.
</P>
<P>
The bank said international speculators transmitted the Asian
crisis to South Africa by selling fixed-interest securities in
the local market. The country's financial market has tumbled
since the speculative attacks started in late May this year.
</P>
<P>
"The principal elements that transmitted the crisis to South
Africa were heavy selling of fixed-interest securities by
non-resident portfolio investors which caused an unavoidable rise
of 725 basis points from June to August in bank lending rates,"
it said.
</P>
<P>
Lower business confidence in the face of the global financial
turmoil and shrinking export demand resulted from the recession
in Asia led to an abrupt decline in the real gross domestic
product (GDP) in the third quarter, it said.
</P>
<P>
Although the telecommunications and financial services sectors
recorded positive growth in the third quarter, many other sectors
posted steep decline in output.
</P>
<P>
Production in the manufacturing sector, the biggest employer
in the country, declined sharply as domestic consumer demand for
durable goods declined and the international economy slowed down,
the bank said.
</P>
<P>
Mining output in the third quarter also contracted, partly
because of the weak export demand for commodities, whereas
agricultural output shrank as a result of a much smaller maize
crop, it said.
</P>
<P>
The bank said the year-on-year GDP growth in the first three
quarters of this year was about 0.5 percent, and the growth for
the whole year was likely to be lower than that. The
lower-than-expected growth rate implied a sharp fall in the real
income per capita of South Africans this year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greenland Bank Defends Performance in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Greenland Bank (T)
Ltd, a major foreign bank in Tanzania, defended Tuesday that it
has a sound financial performance despite the fact that its
parent bank in Uganda has run into trouble.
</P>
<P>
Meeting reporters at the bank in the downtown of Dar es
Salaam, Azad Dhomun, the chief executive, reassured that the bank
has sufficient cash to meet customers' demand. "I am so
confident," he said.
</P>
<P>
Dhomun noted that he was surprised at irresponsible media
reports that a panic withdrawing had happened in the bank.
</P>
<P>
Pointing at places outside his office window, he said, if
there was any panic the queue line would have extended hundreds
of meters into the street, because the bank has 10,000 customers.
</P>
<P>
Dhomun said 25 individuals or companies Monday deposited money
at the bank, which showed that they had confidence in its
performance. However, he declined to reveal the total amount of
their deposits. On average, the bank has 25 to 50 depositors a
day, he added.
</P>
<P>
Business in the bank, however, entered a second day with its
hall packed with hundreds of customers eager to withdraw money
from their accounts.
</P>
<P>
"Panic grips Greenland Bank (T) Limited customers in Dar," an
English-language newspaper headlined, saying that by 5:00 p.m. on
Monday more than 290 million Shillings (about 430,000 U.S.
Dollars) had been withdrawn, almost double the average daily
amount of between 150 million to 170 million Shillings.
</P>
<P>
Rashid Shehe, 27, an employee at the Food and Beverage
Department of the Sheraton Hotel, told Xinhua Tuesday that he
came to withdraw money after hearing from media reports and
fellow workers that the Greenland Bank (T) Ltd. may run into
trouble.
</P>
<P>
The management of Greenland Bank in Kampala, Uganda, was on
Sunday taken over by the Ugandan Central Bank, triggering fears
in Dar es Salaam that its subsidiary in Tanzania would suffer the
same fate.
</P>
<P>
The Greenland Bank, the third largest bank in Uganda, also has
subsidiaries in Kenya and Tanzania's Zanzibar isles.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman for the Bank of Tanzania, the central bank and
the overseer of the Greenland Bank (T) Ltd, however, said: "As
far as we know, the bank is in good performance."
</P>
<P>
"They (the customers) have got their money," he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
