<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Here are major economic briefs
from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Arab Economic Unity Council endorsed Monday an
executive program to resume implementation of the rules of the
mini Arab common market within the framework of the Arab economic
unity agreement.
</P>
<P>
The mini common market embraces seven Arab states, namely,
Egypt, Syria, Libya, Jordan, Yemen, Iraq and Mauritania.
</P>
<P>
The endorsement calls for simultaneous implementation by all
members, starting January 1, 2000, of a timetable that will
abolish customs and other related duties in three years time.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) summit starting
here Monday will mainly deal with economic issues, in the light of
the new world changes and globalization
</P>
<P>
Gulf sources said the economic issues to be discussed at the
summit will include the concept of Gulf citizenship and the flow
of labour force among member states.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The number of factories in the Gulf Cooperation
Council states stands at 422 in all productive sectors.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia claims 180 of the factories, followed by the
United Arab Emirates which has 140.
</P>
<P>
As of the rest, 34 are in Bahrain, 32 in Kuwait, 26 in Oman,
and 10 in Qatar.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanon's budget spending in November exceeded
revenues 53 percent, up from the previous month's figure of 40
percent.
</P>
<P>
A finance ministry statement said spending in November
amounted to 491.88 million U.S. dollars while revenues stood at
243 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Expenditure in the first 11 months of 1998 reached 4.65
billion dollars compared with revenues of 2.69 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The average budget deficit in the past 11 months was 41.6
percent just within the government's overall 1998 target of 42
percent, the statement added.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Fransabank, Lebanon's sixth biggest bank in terms of
total assets, has purchased the much-smaller Universal bank, a
move encouraged by the central bank advocating takeovers in the
banking sector.
</P>
<P>
Financial sources estimated the takeover, which has yet to be
approved by the central bank, was worth 10 million
U.S. dollars. The amount would be paid in installments over one
year, they said.
</P>
<P>
Adnan al-Kassar, Chairman of Fransabank, said that the deal
was aimed at expanding the bank's retail and commercial banking
operation.



08/12/98 18:9 GMT

NNNN
02:12 02:12 g # PAB
</P>
