<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli-Palestinian Clashes Continue in West Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Clashes between Palestinian
protesters and Israeli troops in the West Bank continued Tuesday,
but the demonstrations were scaled down compared with Monday.
</P>
<P>
Two Palestinians were hurt when the Israeli soldiers fired
rubber-coated bullets at the Palestinian stone throwers near the
West Bank city of Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a Israeli girl was slightly injured there as the
Palestinian demonstrators hurled stones at the car she was
driving.
</P>
<P>
In the West Bank town of Ram just north of Jerusalem,
Palestinian students of a high school also clashed with Israeli
soldiers. At least two students were injured as the soldiers fired
rubber bullets and tear gas at them.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrations were launched aimed at pressing the Israeli
government to release Palestinian prisoners in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
Under the Wye agreement signed in October between Israel and
the Palestinians, Israel will pull out its troops from another 13
percent of the West Bank and free 750 Palestinian prisoners by the
end January, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Last month, 250 of them were released, but most were criminals,
not political prisoners demanded by the Palestinian side.
</P>
<P>
On Monday, more than 30 Palestinians and several Israeli
soldiers and civilians were wounded in the clashes spreading
throughout the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israel suspended the implementation of the peace accord last
week, vowing that it will not conduct further troops pullout until
the Palestinians make concessions over some issues, such as that
concerning prisoners.
</P>
<P>
Local media said that Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
announcing the suspension was partially to court the hard-liners
in his coalition to rally more support for his government, which
merely enjoys a slim majority in the Knesset (parliament).
</P>
<P>
Israeli security officials inferred that the scale-down in the
demonstrations on Tuesday resulted from measures taken by the
Palestinian National Authority (PNA).
</P>
<P>
The PNA wants to create a peaceful atmosphere ahead of a tour
by U.S. President Bill Clinton to the region, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Clinton will pay a four-day visit to Israel and the Palestinian
self-rule areas as of Saturday to push forward the implementation
of the Wye accord.
</P>
<P>
To prepare for Clinton's visit, U.S. Middle East Peace Envoy
Dennis Ross arrived here Tuesday. He will meet separately with
Netanyahu and the PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat later in the day.
</P>
<P>
In related development, Jewish settlers from Kadim and Ganim
settlements met with Netanyahu Tuesday, pressing for more security.
</P>
<P>
They told Israeli Radio the prime minister promised that steps
will be taken to cement their security. But they noted that they
are not optimistic since Netanyahu had made such promises before
and nothing has been done.
</P>
<P>
Several Jewish settlements, including Kadim and Ganim, have
became isolated enclaves since Israel handed over 2 percent of the
West Bank to the PNA in its first-phase troops withdrawal last
month under the Wye agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
