<HEADLINE> Zim Dollar Devalued by 68 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwean currency unit
has fallen by 68 percent against the greenback since the
beginning of this year, the Foreign Exchange Traders Association
of Zimbabwe (FETAZ) said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
FETAZ Chairman Charles Nyoka told the Zimbabwe News Agency
that the foreign exchange market has been fairly volatile during
the course of the year due to macro-economic instability.
</P>
<P>
Although the market had begun to stabilize a bit this month,
depressed prices of tobacco coupled with poor prices for other
commodities on the world market had resulted in loss of foreign
currency, he noted.
</P>
<P>
On the continued fall of the Zimbabwean Dollar against major
currencies, he said the key factor to this was that the country
did not have enough capacity to meet its foreign currency
requirements.
</P>
<P>
"It's all a question of supply and demand, and we do not have
a strong base that generate foreign earnings except tobacco and
our manufacturing base is not strong," Nyoka added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
