<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Begins Impeachment Defense </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton's conduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair was "misleading,
even maddening" but did not warrant removing him from office, a
White House special counsel said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing in this case justifies this Congress overturning a
national election," Greg Craig told the House of Representatives
Judiciary Committee in the impeachment hearings which started
Tuesday morning. "There are no grounds for impeachment," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Craig promised to present a "powerful case" against impeachment
and urged legislators to draw "a sharp distinction between immoral
conduct and illegal acts."
</P>
<P>
The White House lawyer said that Clinton's testimony in the
Lewinsky case was "evasive, incomplete, misleading, even
maddening, but it was not perjury."
</P>
<P>
He also conveyed the president's "profound and powerful regret
for what he has done."
</P>
<P>
"The president wants everyone to know -- the committee, the
Congress and the country -- that he is genuinely sorry for the
pain and damage that he has caused," Craig said.
</P>
<P>
"The legal case against the president is, in my judgment, a
house of cards," said John Conyers, the committee's ranking
Democratic lawmaker.
</P>
<P>
Committee Chairman Henry Hyde said Monday that his panel had
made a "compelling case" for removing Clinton for office. But
Conyers rejected that notion, saying the evidence "wouldn't
satisfy any court of law and cannot possibly serve as the
evidentiary foundation" for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
The committee's inquiry enters a final, crucial phase this week
with two days of presentations from Whited House witnesses and
attorneys on Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
With the committee expected to vote on three or four articles
of impeachment related to perjury, obstruction of justice and
abuse of power, Clinton's defenders were increasingly turning
their attention to a likely battle in the full House next week.
</P>
<P>
Sources here said that the White House has been given a list of
30 or so Republican lawmakers who officials believe could be
persuaded to oppose impeachment, either on the merits of the case
or on the basis of the political makeup of their districts.
</P>
<P>
The Republican Party holds a 228-207 majority in the expiring
Congress. Only three Democrats are believed ready to support
impeachment, meaning that moderate Republicans hold the
balanceiary of power in determining whether Clintons case goes to
trial in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
If the House votes for impeachment, it is highly unlikely at
this point that a two-thirds majority in the Senate would vote to
convict and remove Clinton from office, the sources added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
