<HEADLINE> Gulf Leaders Hold Closed-Door Sessions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) held their second closed-door working
session here Tuesday to discuss issues on the agenda of their
19th summit.
</P>
<P>
Right after the opening ceremony Monday evening, the leaders
began their first working meeting which was expected to discuss
falling oil prices, joint security and economic cooperation, the
situation in Iraq, relations with Iran and the Middle East
peace process.
</P>
<P>
The GCC leaders will continue their closing session Wednesday
afternoon during which they will issue the final statement on a
number of issues they discussed at the summit, sources close to
the summit said.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that how to curb the collapse of the oil
prices that has left Gulf Arab economies reeling is dominating the
summit which is being held when the crude oil fell to a historic
low of less than 10 U.S. dollars a barrel.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the world's top oil producer and leading power in
the GCC, was expected to call on the GCC states to adopt a united
and strong position on the world market and make their weight felt
in decision-making.
</P>
<P>
It was time to do something about the low oil prices, Saudi
Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz told the heads of state from
bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar and the United Arab Emirates at the
annual summit.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf oil producers, whose economy depends heavily on oil
earnings, have been hit hard by the sharp drop in prices resulting
from oversupply and flagging demand.
</P>
<P>
The six GCC nations produce about 13.5 million barrel of oil
per day and control nearly half of the world's proven oil
reserves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
