<HEADLINE> Schroeder: Bonn Wants to Reduce Its Payment to EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, December 8 (Xinhua) -- At a European policy conference of
the Social democratic Party (SPD) in German Saarbruecken on
Tuesday, the German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder warned Germany
would not go on paying the European Union (EU)'s bills.
</P>
<P>
"More than half of the money Europe throws around is paid by
Germany," said Schroeder, adding that Bonn could no longer bail
out the EU given its huge and continuing capital transfers to
eastern Germany.
</P>
<P>
EU states got by in the past with the motto: "The crisis will
be solved because the Germans will pay," he said, adding: "This
policy has come to an end."
</P>
<P>
Attacking agricultural spending, which devours half of the EU's
budget, Schroeder stressed EU member states should be paying the
bill for their farmers.
</P>
<P>
"Financing in Europe means... iron budget discipline must be
practiced... in the EU," said Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
Taking his toughest tone on Europe since being elected,
Schroeder said Germany would oppose any moves to raise the annual
EU budget over its current level of 98 billion dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
