<HEADLINE> U.N. Says Iraq Resumes Oil Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Iraq had resumed oil
exports last week after the recent approval of the latest phase of
the "oil-for-food" program, U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Eckhard said two ships sailed over the weekend from the Turkish
port of Ceyhan with a million barrels each of Iraq's Kirkuk crude,
and another four ships sailed from the Gulf port of Mina al-Bakr
from Saturday to Monday, eaching carrying an estimated two million
barrels of crude.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has submitted 29 contracts to sell crude under the latest
phase, with 25 approved for a total of 88.5 million barrels.
</P>
<P>
The oil-for-food program allows Iraq to sell up to 5 billion
U.S. dollars worth of oil over 180 days form November 25 to buy
food, medicine and other humanitarian goods for its people.
