<HEADLINE> Fighting Subsides on Comoran Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Fighting on the Comoran
island of Anjouan subsided Tuesday after a militia faction loyal
to politician Chamassi Said Omar seized control of the Capital
Mutsamudu following three days of fighting.
</P>
<P>
The faction took control of Mutsamudu Monday night after
allegedly looting and burning houses and carrying out summary
executions of civilians on the streets, a local report reaching
here said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, between 40 and 60 people had been
killed in machine gun and artillery battles along the narrow
streets of the tiny port capital Mutsamudu's old town.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the South African government announced Tuesday that
a delegation of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) led by
South Africa will begin a three-day fact finding mission to the
Archipelago's main island Grand Comore Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Fighting erupted on the Comoran island of Anjouan last
Saturday after a failed assassination attempt on the island's
self-declared President Foundi Abdallah Ibrahim -- the second in
just over a week. Ibrahim led Anjouan's secession from the Comoro
Islands in August last year.
</P>
<P>
Omar demanded Ibrahim's resignation. His forces took advantage
of a brief cease-fire which held through last Sunday night to
rally reinforcements from rural areas and soldiers willing to
defect from the regular secessionist army. 
</P>
