<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Shocked to Learn Killing of Foreign Hostages in Chechny </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan "was shocked" to hear news reports Tuesday that four
foreign hostages were found decapitated in Chechnya, a region in
southern Russia, where "kidnappings have become common," U.N.
spokesman Fred Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
The four men -- Britons Darren Hickey, Rudolf Petschi and Peter
Kennedy and New Zealander Stanley Shaw -- were captured by unknown
gunmen on October 3 in the Chechen capital, Grozny, where they
were working for Granger Telecom, a British telephone company,
installing 300,000 telephone lines across Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
It was the first time foreign hostages had been murdered since
the end of Chechnya's 1994-1996 war with Russia for independence.
</P>
<P>
Also on Tuesday, Annan met with the family of Vincent Cochetel,
a Frenchman, who headed the office of the United Nations High
Commission for Refugees (UNHCR) in North Ossetia, near Chechnya.
He was abducted about 313 days ago and a UNHCR spokesman said two
weeks ago he is believed to be alive and healthy.
</P>
<P>
However, efforts to obtain his release has yielded no result so
far since January this year when Cochetel was held.
</P>
<P>
Annan told reporters in Paris that he would speak with Russian
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov "as part of his ongoing efforts
and contacts with Russian officials to try to bring Cochetel
home," Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
Chechnya, a region within Russia, is not recognized as
independent by any country since Moscow withdrew its troops in
1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
