<BODY>
<HEADLINE> COMESA Members Urged to Speed up Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Zambian President Frederick
Chiluba Tuesday urged members of the Common Market for Eastern
and Southern Africa (COMESA) to redouble efforts toward the
economic integration of the region.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating the new COMESA Center or COMESA Secretariat
building in Lusaka, Chiluba said all the member states should
continue moving forward and speed up the process of attaining a
free trade area by the year 2000, reported Zambia News Agency
ZANA.
</P>
<P>
The 21-member regional grouping which was established in 1994
to replace the former Preferential Trade Area for Eastern and
Southern Africa (PTA) also aims to achieve a customs union with a
single external tariff by the year 2004.
</P>
<P>
A fragmented market system, said Chiluba, should be done away
with and member countries should work toward a stronger
sub-regional market in order to create investment and jobs.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed COMESA should strive for integration into the
global market by ensuring peace and stability in the region.
</P>
<P>
No economies will grow independently without being integrated
into the world market, Chiluba noted.
</P>
<P>
He, therefore, called on member countries such as Angola,
Uganda, Rwanda, the Democratic Republic of Congo, Ethiopia and
Eritrea which are involved in conflicts to end their hostilities
and engage in more meaningful conflict resolutions.
</P>
<P>
During the inauguration, Zambia presented a check worth
400,000 U.S. Dollars as final payment of its obligations for the
purchase of the COMESA Center, which was centrally situated in
the Zambian capital and acquired from a defunct bank at a total
cost of nine million Dollars.
</P>
<P>
The function was attended by senior government officials,
diplomats and COMESA officials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
