<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania in Grave Food Shortage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Most regions in Tanzania
are faced with severe shortages of food and the government has
sent expert teams to make assessment of the situation.
</P>
<P>
Reports from the Ministry of Agriculture and Cooperatives say
that initial assessment by 15 regions indicates that some 523,247
tons of food are required between this month and next March.
</P>
<P>
The reports said that out of requirement, about 208,000 tons
are to be used for emergency supply and another 315,000 tons for
commercial purposes.
</P>
<P>
By November 30, the Strategic Grain Reserve (SGR) had only
45,557 tons of food, less than 10 percent of the required supply.
</P>
<P>
A senior official with the ministry, however, told reporters
Tuesday that the regions' estimates are too high and that the
actual requirement of food will be known upon completion of the
assessment in two weeks.
</P>
<P>
The official said the expert teams with four members each
drawn from the Food Security Department, the Commission of
Agriculture and Livestock, the Disaster Department in the
minister's office and the Directorate of Meteorology are making
assessment in Lake Zone, Northern and Coastal zones as well as
the central Morogoro Region.
</P>
<P>
He said those were the areas which did not get short rains
this season and are suspected to be facing acute food shortages.
</P>
<P>
The official said that authorities concerned will thereafter
reconcile the assessment made by the regions and the experts and
come up with a situation report which will advise the government
on what should be done.
</P>
<P>
The official said the food security department has approved
distribution of 35,000 tons of food from the SGR for commercial
purposes and that each region has been allocated with a share.
</P>
<P>
Arusha has been allocated with 1,400 tons, Kilimanjaro 1,000
tons, Tanga 1,600 tons, Dodoma and Singida, 1000 tons each,
Tabora 500 tons, Dar es Salaam 6,400 tons and Coast 2,600 tons,
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
