<HEADLINE> International Symposium on Human Rights Held in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 8 (Xinhua) -- An international symposium on
human rights was held here Tuesday under the slogan "The
continuing unjust sanctions are an evident violation to human
rights."
</P>
<P>
Speaking to its opening session, Iraqi Foreign Minister
Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf said "the unjust embargo aims at
diminishing Iraq's civilization history of more than seven
thousand years."
</P>
<P>
"As the international community exerts earnest and faithful
efforts for the welfare of mankind, human rights have become a
weapon in the hands of some countries to achieve their own
interests when they claim these rights through a double standard
policy," Sahhaf stressed.
</P>
<P>
The minister expressed hope that the symposium would shed
more light on the crimes committed against the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations imposed economic sanctions on Iraq
following its 1990 invasion of Kuwait, which touched off the
1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has said the U.N. sanctions is tantamount genocide to the
people of Iraq, citing that more than 1 million Iraqi children
and elderly people have died due to the acute shortages of food
and medicine caused by the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi minister reminded the participants that Iraq was the
first country in the world that set laws and paid attention to
human rights since King Hammurabi 3,000 years ago." The Code of
Hammurabi is believed to be the first written law in the world.
</P>
<P>
Head of the Preparatory Committee of the symposium, Mohammed
al-Doury, expressed hope that participants in the symposium and
the international community should work seriously to lift the
sanctions imposed on Iraq and to stop this crime which contradicts
with the International Declaration of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
More than one hundred Arab and foreign figures from Britain,
France, Spain, Greece, India, Mali, Yemen, Bangladesh, Sudan, and
Jordan attended the symposium which will last three days.
</P>
<P>
The symposium will discuss 25 researches that deal with the
negative influences of economic sanctions on human rights in
the world in general and in Iraq in particular, said the
Iraqi News Agency. 
</P>
</TEXT>
