<HEADLINE> Schroeder, Chirac Call for Binding EU-wide Job Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bonn, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The German Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder and French President Jacques Chirac sent Tuesday
together a letter to Austrian Chancellor Viktor Klima, appealing
this week's European Union (EU) summit in Vienna to approve a job
creation pact which would be mandatory across the 15-nation bloc.
</P>
<P>
Chancellor Klimais will be hosting the December 11 to 12
summit.
</P>
<P>
According to this letter published here today, the leaders of
Germany and France said: "The governments of all member states in
the EU should obligate themselves to binding verifialble targets
regarding employment policy guidelines...".
</P>
<P>
They stressed the jobs-creation would be in the center of the
european policy, and suggested the EU-summit of this weekend
regard the cuts in unemployment as a important subject under
discussion.
</P>
<P>
The letter said stress should be on "cutting youth and
long-term unemployment but also discrimination aimed at women in
the job market".
</P>
<P>
Linked to a jobs pact would be setting common minimum standards
in environmental policy along with progress toward minimum taxes
and entitlements, said the letter.
</P>
<P>
The letter also indicated the EU will seek a new constitutional
congress in a bid to make the key institutional reform decisions
passed over by the 1997 Amsterdam Treaty. These include reducing
the size of the European Commission, shifting to majority voting
instead of the current national veto and re-weighting of votes
from different sized members.  
</P>
</TEXT>
