<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Denies Fresh Recruitment in Army </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The Rwandan government has
been angered by Amnesty International's report alleging that in
August and September it forced men and boys into the army,
Rwandan News Agency (RNA) reported in Kigali Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The allegations are a complete fabrication, lacking point,
truth and substance," the RNA quoted the Rwandan Defense Ministry
as saying in a statement Tuesday, which called the report a
campaign against the government army, the Rwandan Patriotic Army
(RPA).
</P>
<P>
The ministry of defense further claimed that "the RPA has
never had shortage of willing volunteers to join its ranks," and
described RPA as one of the best trained and motivated armies in
the region.
</P>
<P>
"It would therefore be a self-defeating exercise to recruit
men and boys against their will, as this would result in
desertion and serious problems of troops' morale," the statement,
broadcast on both state-run radio and television, stressed.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan ministry of defense argued that it halted
recruitment a few months ago, due to budgetary constraints, and
that it has embarked on trimming down the size of its army. It is
in line with this policy that by the year 2,001 Rwanda will have
demobilized between 22,000 and 25,000 soldiers, from its
estimated 55,000 at present.
</P>
<P>
Since early August, Rwanda is engaged in the Congolese war
where it backs rebels fighting to oust embattled President
Laurent Kabila from power.
</P>
<P>
There had been widespread sayings that because of this war,
the Rwandan army has been coercing men and boys to join its ranks
in a bid to back up the war efforts in Congo (K).
</P>
<P>
One Sunday, Rwandan Vice-President and Minister of Defense,
Major General Paul Kagame, said he will maintain his troops in
Congo as long as security along its borders will remain
threatened by Hutu extremists using Congo as a launching pad for
cross-borders raids on Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
"If we are given cast-iron guarantees by the International
community that our security concerns would be addressed, and
Kabila demonstrated a genuine commitment to address our security
concerns, then we would have no further need to keep our troops
in Congo," Kagame underscored.
</P>
<P>
Kagame accused Kabila of having gorged an alliance with the
forces which committed genocide in Rwanda and which still have
plans to overthrow the regime in Kigali.
</P>
<P>
He advised Kabila and his allies to favor peace talks because
"they cannot defeat the rebels", now controlling about half of
the country's territory, especially in the east and the north.
</P>
<P>
"They also cannot wish away the problems they have created.
They need to sit down and talk to those fighting them," Kagame
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
