<HEADLINE> Aziz: Lift Sanctions or Kick out UNSCOM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Iraq Deputy Prime Minister Tariq
Aziz said here Tuesday that UNSCOM would be banned from working in
his country if the United States and Britain insist on keeping
economic sanctions against Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Aziz told a press conference that a decision on continuing
Baghdad's cooperation with the U.N. Special Commission on Iraq's
disarmament (UNSCOM) will depend on the results of the
comprehensive U.N. review of the Iraqi situation scheduled for
early January.
</P>
<P>
Iraq will make a decision on protecting Iraq's independence and
sovereignty in light of the review, said Aziz, who was here on a
four-day working visit to enlist Moscow's support for an end to
the crippling sanctions imposed by the U.N. following Baghdad's
invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
He warned London and Washington that if they insist on keeping
economic sanctions, they should be ready for the UNSCOM being
banned from working in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"Our patience is not endless," he said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said Washington and London are intent on using their veto
power at the U.N. Security Council to derail the lifting of
economic sanctions against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He accused the UNSCOM of being dishonest and executing the will
of Washington which wants to have the Iraqi leadership replaced
rather than the sanctions lifted.
</P>
<P>
The commission conducts extensive espionage in the interests of
the United States, Britain and Israel, Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz, who arrived here Sunday and held meetings with Russian
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov and Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov,
is scheduled to leave Moscow Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
