<HEADLINE> Ugandan President's Brother Defends Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Ugandan President Yoweri
Museveni's Brother Salim Saleh Tuesday defended his position in
the Uganda Commercial Bank (UCB) saga.
</P>
<P>
Answering questions in Radio Uganda's "Talk Show" program,
Saleh, also former senior presidential advisor on defense and
security, said he bought UCB from a Malaysian company in the
interests of average Ugandans.
</P>
<P>
He said he did not want UCB to be controlled in foreigners'
hands.
</P>
<P>
Although the method of buying the 49 shares of UCB from the
Malaysian company through Greenland Bank is illegal, this move is
well-intentioned, he argued.
</P>
<P>
He also refuted allegations that he is doing business for the
president and said he regretted his resignation Saturday leaving
his brother alone.
</P>
<P>
"I had no other choice," the 38-year-old major general said.
</P>
<P>
When asked if he went against his oath as reported, Saleh said
he did not give any oath at all.
</P>
<P>
Previous reports said Saleh had denied, before parliament
under oath, any involvement in the UCB issue. But under mounting
press pressure, he admitted his purchase of the biggest
commercial bank in the country.
</P>
<P>
The major general said he had many businesses in Uganda, but
declining to give the exact number.
</P>
<P>
There are also some listeners who called to thank Saleh for
his purchase of the bank and encouraged him to continue the
doing.
</P>
<P>
Francis Kene, a member of the parliamentary committee on
privatization, told Xinhua in a telephone interview Tuesday
evening that many people involved in the issue are to be
investigated and that some would be punished for their mistakes.
</P>
