<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia's Foreign
Minister Tuesday said ties between Ethiopia and Sudan will
normalize only after Khartoum hands over to Addis Ababa the
terrorists who tried to kill Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in
1995.
</P>
<P>
According to the Ethiopian News Agency, Seyoum Mesfin made the
remarks in response to questions posed by Ethiopian reporters on
relations between the two countries shortly before his departure
for Nigeria and Ghana.
</P>
<P>
Seyoum described as "far from the truth" reports by the
Sudanese media and some diplomatic sources claiming that
relations between Ethiopia and Sudan are on the mend.
</P>
<P>
The Sudanese media, in particular, are reporting that the two
countries are trying to launch cooperations, "but all these
(reports) are lies," said the Ethiopian minister.
</P>
<P>
Seyoum said relations between the two countries soured after
evidences showed that the Sudanese government was directly
involved in the attempt on the life of president Mubarak here in
Addis Ababa in June 1995.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Khartoum government has given shelter
to the terrorists who tried to assassinate the president.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian foreign minister said Sudan has repeatedly
refused calls on it by, among others, the Organization of African
Unity (OAU) and the United Nations Security Council, to extradite
to Ethiopia the terrorists.
</P>
<P>
He said the Ethio-Sudanese ties will not normalize until
Khartoum extradites the culprits, adding that by refusing to hand
over the terrorists to Ethiopia, Sudan has given precedence to
its ties with terrorists over its relations with the people and
government of Ethiopia.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian foreign minister will convey messages from Prime
Minister Meles Zenawi to the presidents of Nigeria and Ghana,
according to the report. 
</P>
