<P>
LUSAKA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- After two weeks of talks held
here the International Monetary Fund (IMF) has reached an
agreement with Zambia under which donors will release their
promised aid to the latter, a Zambian official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Finance Minister Edith Nawakwi told a news briefing
here that the aid to be released will put her country's economy
back on track.
</P>
<P>
She said Zambia's economy is expected to grow next year if the
second phase of the enhanced structural adjustment facility
(ESAF) is implemented early next year.
</P>
<P>
The Zambian government and the visiting IMF country director
Renoild Van Till held intense discussions on the next phase of
the structural adjustment program of the country, she said.
</P>
<P>
Nawakwi told the press that this year has been difficult for
Zambia's economy following the structural problems it has faced.
</P>
<P>
The major hustle for Zambia has been the slow race of
privatization of the copper mines which the donors advanced as a
precondition for receiving aid, she noted.
</P>
<P>
She expressed her optimism that the mines will be sold off
completely by early next year, a move which has pleased the
donors.
</P>
<P>
Van Till told the briefing that Zambia's economy will begin to
grow next year as inflation which is the current major problem
will be tackled thanks to assistance from IMF and other donors.
</P>
<P>
He said it is important that Zambia becomes a good partner
with the IMF so that the ESAF program expected to be in force
next year takes root.
</P>
<P>
He also said that Zambia's economy has performed poorly this
year for reasons he attributed to the failure of the government
to dispose of the mines and he hoped there will be growth next
year.
</P>
<P>
In May this year donors pledged to give Zambia an aid of 530
million Dollars at the Consultative Group meeting held Paris.
However, the donors have not released the pledged aid while
pressing for a quick completion of the privatization of the
Zambia Consolidated Cooper Mines (ZCCM), which earns more than 80
percent of Zambia's foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
Zambia's two-thirds of government expenditure come from the
donors and the withholding of the aid has reduced inflow of
foreign exchange into the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
