<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Says N. Ireland Peace Process in Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 8 (Xinhua) --- Sinn Fein's chief negotiator
Martin McGuinness said on Tuesday the Northern Ireland peace
process was in "crisis."
</P>
<P>
Emerging talks with Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern in
Dublin, McGuinness said he had no speculation on the IRA's
position on arms decommissioning.
</P>
<P>
He also made plain his determination that a ministry for
equality and a cross-border body dealing with the Irish language
be set up under the new Northern Ireland Assembly.
</P>
<P>
McGuinness was quoted by BBC as saying: "Why should anyone be
afraid of a department of equality? Why should anyone be afraid of
a cross border implementation body into the Irish language?
</P>
<P>
His remarks came as British Prime Minister Tony Blair was
holding a new round of talks to overcome the impasse in
implementing the Northern Ireland Peace Agreement.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman said Blair will meet Ulster Unionist
deputy leader John Taylor later Tuesday and will hold talks with
nationalist Social Democratic and Labor Party (SDLP) deputy leader
Seamus Mallon and McGuinness the following day.
</P>
<P>
There has been a considerable effort in Northern Ireland
recently to try to force an agreement before Thursday, when First
Minister David Trimble and SDLP leader John Hume receive the Nobel
peace prize.
</P>
<P>
The Sinn Fein chief negotiator added: "I think it is vitally
and critically important at a time when there is considerable
demoralization about the non-implementation of this agreement that
the political leaders should get their act together.
</P>
<P>
The present impasse arose when Trimble found he was unable to
go along with the compromise after consulting his party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
