<HEADLINE> European Markets End in Mixed Performances </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- A softer opening in the New York
market sent European bourses to a lower performances Tuesday with
London as an exception owing to hopes of an interest rate cut.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 index ended moderately higher helped by
speculation that the Bank of England may deliver a sizable cut in
interest rates this week.
</P>
<P>
The blue-chip share index finished 39 points or 0.7 percent
higher at 5,615.7.
</P>
<P>
However, many investors were still reluctant to trade and
dealers said the FTSE was still consolidating around the 5,600
level.
</P>
<P>
"People are keeping a pretty tight rein on things ahead of the
euro launch," said one observer. "No one wants to leave themselves
exposed to the unknown implications of the euro."
</P>
<P>
The Frankfurt Xetra Dax index closed down 12.98 points at
4,708.19. Dealers said the hallmark of the session was inactivity
as many investors have already stopped trading in preparation for
the coming of the euro in the New Year.
</P>
<P>
In addition, Tuesday is a holiday in a number of European
countries, further damping trading activity in Germany.
</P>
<P>
Paris stocks ended a sluggish session almost flat Tuesday, amid
unwillingness among investors to take positions ahead of the euro
launch with the Cac 40 closing down 5.8 points at 3,765.41.
</P>
</TEXT>
