<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Talks With Turkey on Kurdish Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Ministry
spokesman Hamid Reza Asefi Tuesday denied that Iran and Turkey had
held talks on a trip of Turkish rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan to
Tehran.
</P>
<P>
The Italian Lastampa daily has reported that Ocalan, leader of
the Turkish Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK), had disclosed that a
Turkish delegation had visited Tehran for his tour there.
</P>
<P>
The PKK rebels have been fighting since 1984 for an independent
Kurdish state in southeastern Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Rejecting the report as baseless, Asefi said that Iran so far
has not held any negotiation regarding Ocalan's trip to Iran and
is not going to do so.
</P>
<P>
"At present, a Turkish delegation is in Tehran to participate in
the two countries' high security commission, which is held every
six months regularly," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"The visit of the Turkish delegation has nothing to do with the
Ocalan's issue," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Ocalan has been detained in Italy since arriving from Moscow on
November 12. Turkey, which considers him a terrorist responsible
for thousands of deaths, has demanded his extradition. But Italy
has refused because he can face death penalty when returning
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Asefi also noted that, just as what Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi said during his recent visit to Italy, Iran is ready to
play a mediatory role to defuse the tension between Turkey and
Italy if the two countries wished to do so. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
