<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PLO Representative Doubts Netanyahu's Sincerity on Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The chief Palestinian
representative on Tuesday expressed his doubt about Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's sincerity in carrying out the peace
process with the Palestinians in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Netanyahu does not view the Palestinians as his partners
in this process and he still vacillates on the issue of wanting to
make peace with the Palestinians," Hassan Abdel Rahman, head of
the Palestine Liberation Organization (PLO) office in Washington,
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes he is more interested in making peace with his own
coalition, rather than with the Palestinians," he added.
</P>
<P>
Rahman, who helped negotiate the Wye agreement between Israel
and the Palestinians in October, said a series of Israel's actions
indicated Israeli insincerity.
</P>
<P>
For example, he said, the Israelis failed to set up committees
to talk with the Palestinians on a Gaza seaport and on safe
passages between the Gaza Strip and the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
The Wye agreement, signed in Washington on October 23, said the
two sides would renew negotiations on the safe passage immediately
and would proceed "without delay" to conclude an agreement on
building the seaport.
</P>
<P>
Another example, and one of the biggest threats to the peace
process, is the Israel's position on political prisoners, Rahman
said.
</P>
<P>
Israel agreed at Wye Mills, Maryland, where the pact was
negotiated, that it would set free 750 prisoners in three batches
of 250. The Palestinians understood that all of them would be
political prisoners, but the first batch of 250 contained 150
common criminals.
</P>
<P>
"This is inconsistent with the agreement and with the spirit
which is supposed to be emerging between the Palestinians and the
Israelis," Rahman said.
</P>
<P>
"Here we were talking about a partnership for peace, about
putting the peace process back on track... and the Israelis are
bargaining, in essence taking hostage those political prisoners,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
But Israel said there was no agreement at Wye on what type of
prisoner Israel would set free. The United States has appeared to
concur, saying the first prisoner release met the commitment which
Israel made in the agreement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
