<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mass Fish Death Triggers Disputes in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, December 9 (Xinhua) -- There has been a mass fish
mortality in the coastal areas between Mogadishu and Warsheikh
district of Middle Shabelle region in southern Somalia since
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Residents of the capital got up early in the morning and found
dead fish everywhere as all the fish markets have been glutted.
</P>
<P>
Despite the super cheap price in the fish markets, strong
rumors circulated that the fish had been poisoned by toxic wastes
from Western nuclear plants and poured into Somalia's unguarded
sea waters. As the rumors increased, the people have gone in
streams to the sea shores to witness what was ostensibly seen as
a mere here-say.
</P>
<P>
The disputed administration of the capital has also sent a
committee consisting of senior officials and sea-life experts. As
the matter became pragmatic, two fish were taken for tests in
Mogadishu's limited laboratories, while extensive interviews were
made with veteran fishermen at Lido's beach in Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
The fishermen have declined the attribution of the dead fish
to toxic wastes poured into the sea since most of the dead fish
belonged only to what's known locally as Kakuna fish type, a fish
species not commonly eaten in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
"The poison could have killed all fish types and other sea
creatures instead of Kakuna or another particular type alone,"
said Ali Mohamed Robleh, one of the seamen at Lido beach.
</P>
<P>
The fishermen said the most probable reason is the dumping of
the unwanted fish types by illegal foreign vessels fishing off
Somalia's coasts.
</P>
<P>
A Somali Seamen Organization based in Mogadishu said foreign
vessels from Japan, Italy, the Republic of Korea, the Philippines
and Thailand are exploiting Somalia's seas using illegal methods
and nets for fishing.
</P>
<P>
"As their nets are quite small, all kinds of fishes are caught
and the unwanted types are later on dumped into the sea," said
Robleh.
</P>
<P>
The organization has called on the international community to
help stop illegal fishing into the Somali waters by foreigners
taking advantage of the lawlessness and lack of central
government, to safeguard the economic exclusive zones of Somalia
in the Indian Ocean and the Red Sea.
</P>
<P>
The illegal fishing conspiracy in Somalia's sea waters seem to
have shifted to southern Somalia after sea pirates in the
northeastern regions increased in number and caught several of
those illegal fishing vessels. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
