<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Records Highlight Asian Games (Day Four) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Three weightlifting world
records were produced in the Asian Games while China was jolted
into action and pulled away in the medal tally with a haul of 12
golds on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
South Korean lifter Kim Hak-Bong won the men's 69kg division
after setting a world record in the clean and jerk.
</P>
<P>
Kim, way behind in the snatch with 145kg, upset favorite Wan
Jianhui of China with a stunning lift of 195kg in his final
attempt at the jerk, which is five kilos over the new world
standard set by the International Weightlifting Federation.
</P>
<P>
In the women's weightlifting, Chinese Chen Yanping snatched a
new world record of 98kg en route to winning the 58kg class, while
Ri Song-Hui from the Democratic People's Republic of Korea set the
clean and jerk world record with a 125kg lift.
</P>
<P>
China and Japan battled out again in the water with the
former scoring a narrow win.
</P>
<P>
China won three of the five golds Wednesday, with Japan
taking the other two to lead 8-6 in the swimming medal table
after 15 events.
</P>
<P>
Chinese swimmer Chen Hua made the most of the absence of world
champion Chen Yan by winning the women's 400m freestyle.
</P>
<P>
Chen Yan, who won the event along with the 400m medley at this
year's world championships in Perth, is ill with a stomach
ailment.
</P>
<P>
Chinese veteran Fu Yong, a bronze medalist in the 1994 Asian
Games, splashed home first in the men's 200m backstroke.
</P>
<P>
China's third swimming gold came from the women's 4x100
freestyle relay, in which the Chinese foursome of Chao Na, Han
Xue, Qian Min and Shan Ying timed 3:45.51.
</P>
<P>
The men's 100m freestyle event belonged to a Japanese twin.
</P>
<P>
Shunsuke Ito came into the world before twin brother Shusuke
and was in front of him again as they scored a 1-2 finish.
</P>
<P>
"I'm really happy to have a 1-2 finish with my brother," the
winning brother said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Tomoko Hagiwara grabbed the women's 100 backstroke,
beating compatriot Mai Nakamura and South Korean Choi Soo-Min.
</P>
<P>
China landed three gold medals in shooting as Xu Dan won the
men's air pistol title after leading his teammates to the team
victory, and Wang Xian snatched the women's sport rifle prone
title.
</P>
<P>
China showed their depth in gymnastics as Huang Xu led
teammate Yang Wei to a 1-2 placing in the men's all-around event.
</P>
<P>
Wang Xiaobo ended China's gold drought in judo as she
overwhelmed Japanese Kimoto Nami in the women's 63kg category
final.
</P>
<P>
China also struck gold in canoeing as Meng Guanliang
triumphed in the men's C-1 1,000m race.
</P>
<P>
China has nailed its No. 1 position in the medal tally with 25
golds, 22 silvers and 18 bronzes.
</P>
<P>
Japan came second with a 16-19-16 record and South Korea was
third with 15-6-12. Kazakhstan placed a distant fourth with a
6-5-9 haul. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
