<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Hopes to Be Self-Sufficient in Corn </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia would achieve
self-sufficiency in corn production by 2001 if the government
sticks to its program to intensify corn planting in dryland, a
senior researcher said.
</P>
<P>
Corn harvests from dryland are less than those from wetland,
head of the Agriculture Ministry's Food Crop and Horticultural
Research Center Sumarno was quoted by Antara News Agency Wednesday
as saying.
</P>
<P>
"At present, Indonesia produces 9 million tons of corn per
annum but still has to import at least one million tons more every
year," Sumarno said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that a hectare of dryland yields only 1.5-2.5 tons of
corn while a hectare of wetland produces 6-6.5 tons of corn.
</P>
<P>
Without tapping the country's dryland for corn production, the
government needs to open 200,000 new hectares of cornfields to
achieve self-sufficiency by 2001, he said.
</P>
<P>
In support of the program to grow more corn in dryland, the
ministry will release new high-yielding varieties of corn, he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
