<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai PM Opens Public Forum on Contentious Bills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai
Wednesday opened a public forum to explain 11 contentious bills to
stimulate the country's ailing economy amid accusations from the
opposition.
</P>
<P>
The forum, broadcast live on radio and television, also
featured Finance Minister Tarin Nimmanahaeminda and other cabinet
members.
</P>
<P>
The opposition members of parliament boycotted the forum,
arguing that the bills, especially those covering investment from
overseas and bankruptcy, would hand over much of the economy to
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
"The government is trying to give more accurate information on
these bills to allow the public to understand them properly,"
Chuan said.
</P>
<P>
Hours before the meeting, Chuan hit back at the criticism that
the bills and the 17.2-billion-dollar International Monetary Fund
(IMF) rescue package granted too much control of the economy to
foreigners.
</P>
<P>
People should not "engage in unfounded allegations, sensational
allegations, for example, in charging that we in the government
want to sell off the country", Chuan said.
</P>
<P>
"Those charges are certainly unfounded," Tarin told the forum.
He said Thailand still faced an economic battle. "All these bills
are important factors for economic rehabilitation but it doesn't
mean that by passing the bills we will eradicate all the
problems," he said.
</P>
<P>
A number of high-profile senators, who are opposed to the bills
and have substantial business interests, have warned that the
measures could force them to hand over the control of their firms
to foreigners. 
</P>
</TEXT>
