<HEADLINE> IOC President Calls for Respect of Human Rights in Sports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- President of the International
Olympic Committee (IOC) Juan Antonio Samaranch called on
Wednesday for respect of human rights in sports in a message
marking the 50th anniversary of the Universal Declaration of
Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
"The practice of sport is a human right," the IOC chief said.
"Every individual must have the possibility of practising sport
in accordance with his or her needs."
</P>
<P>
He said that the fundamental principles of the Olympic Charter
reflect the ideals and rights defended in the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights, adopted on December 10, 1948 at the
Palais de Chaillot in Paris.
</P>
<P>
"The desire to create a culture of democracy, justice,
peace,solidarity and respect for fundamental and universal
ethical principles has been omnipresent in the activities
undertaken by the IOC since its creation in 1894," Samaranch said.
</P>
<P>
"At a time when the wind of democracy is blowing across the
continents, it is vital that we call attention to the importance
of developing policies that advocate education for all, health
for all,peace for all, sport for all and respect for all human
rights for all," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Samaranch stated that the Olympic Movement will continue to
work toward the well-being and intellectual and physical
development of humankind, and to defend human rights,
particularly the rights of children, young people and women.
