<HEADLINE> Islamic Council for Peace in Afghanistan Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Islamic Council of the
People of Afghanistan was launched here Wednesday with the avowed
purpose of freeing the Afghan people from the fire of "cruel civil
war" and restoring peace in the country.
</P>
<P>
Announcing the launching of the council, Afghan religious
scholar Motasim Billah Mazhabi, president of the council, said
that the organization is not hostile to any faction, including the
Taliban, as its purpose is to secure unity and national
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
"The Taliban are also from the Afghan nation and we are not
hostile to any faction, we do not reject anyone as we are for
unity," he said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
Mazhabi, who claimed the backing of Afghan scholars and
intellectuals and the masses as well, called for talks to resolve
the differences between various factions.
</P>
<P>
Replying to a question about the council's stand on self-exiled
Saudi Osama bin Laden's stay in Afghanistan, he said the council
"will not accept him if he is actually found involved in terrorist
activities."
</P>
<P>
Mazhabi stressed his opposition to "narrow vision" of the Islam
religion, saying "we are Muslims and Islam is not a narrow-vision
religion, the label of fundamentalism is an allegation and a
conspiracy to declare Afghans terrorists."
</P>
<P>
The charter of the council, made available to reporters, vows
to eliminate all differences and discrimination and secure social
justice in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
While asserting the council's opposition to terrorism, he
condemned terrorism all over the world.
</P>
<P>
On the foreign front, Mazhabi lauded Pakistan's role for the
restoration of peace in the war-battered country.
</P>
<P>
"I will hold talks during my stay in Pakistan with the
leadership of Pakistan because it is very sincere to play an
effective role for peace in Afghanistan," he said.
</P>
<P>
On foreign interference in Afghanistan, he said peace in the
country can only be effective if the external interference is
stopped and the supply of arms to various factions is curtailed.
</P>
<P>
He also announced plans to hold rallies all over the world for
the cause of peace in Afghanistan, disclosing that first such
rally will be brought out in Islamabad in January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
