<HEADLINE> Gulf Arabs Pledge to Extend Oil Output Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Abu Dhabi, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of the Gulf
Cooperation Council (GCC) Wednesday ended their 19th summit with
a pledge to extend existing oil output cuts until the end of
1999.
</P>
<P>
The pledge was made in a joint communique issued at the end of
the three-day summit of the GCC which groups Bahrain, Kuwait,
Qatar, Oman, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates (UAE).
</P>
<P>
The falling oil prices, which has had a negative impact
on the GCC economies, top the issues highlighted in the final
communique.
</P>
<P>
The leaders "urged other oil producers to take similar measures
in order to achieve stability in the market in the benefit of both
producing and consuming countries as well as for the safety and
stability of the world economy."
</P>
<P>
The communique said that if pledges on output cuts were
honored, the GCC member states would be ready to enter into proper
 arrangements with other oil exporting countries in order to bring
stability to the oil market.
</P>
<P>
"The council asserted the importance of oil producers to
abide by productions cuts they had pledged in June 1998 to
stabilize the oil market. Based on this, the Higher Council
agreed to extend work with production cuts pledged by its
states until the end of 1999," the communique said.
</P>
<P>
How to curb the falling oil prices that have left Gulf Arab
economies reeling dominated the summit held at a time when the
crude oil hit a historic low of less than 10 U.S. dollars per
barrel.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf oil producers, whose economies depends heavily on
oil earnings, have been hit hard by the sharp drop in prices
resulting from oversupply and flagging demand.
</P>
<P>
On internal economic aspects, a GCC long-term comprehensive
development strategy for the years 2000-2025 aimed at total
regional economic integration was one of the main points in the
comminique. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
