<HEADLINE> 53 Killed in Bus-Tanker Collision in India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 9 (Xinhua) -- At least 53 people were
killed in one of the worst road accidents Wednesday when a
over-crowded bus collided head-on with an oil tanker in Bihar,
northeast India, the Press Trust of India (PTI) reported.
</P>
<P>
The bus carrying supporters of the Rashtriya Janata Dal, or the
National People's Party, was returning from a rally in Patna,
capital of Bihar, when the tragedy occurred in Bhojpur district
of the state, PTI said.
</P>
<P>
While the district magistrate said the accident claimed at
least 53 lives, eyewitness said the toll would not be less than 75
as the bus was so over-crowded.
</P>
<P>
A PTI correspondent reported from the spot that five people,
who were standing near the bus door, could be rescued with 70
percent burns.
</P>
<P>
Eyewitness said under the impact of the collision, the tanker
split into two and a blaze engulfed the vehicles immediately.
</P>
<P>
The blaze could only be put out by 15:30 local time, nine hours
after the tragedy occurred at 06:30, PTI said.
</P>
<P>
The driver of the bus and the helper of the oil tanker, who
survived, said that people were seen traveling even on the
roof-top of the bus which had a seating capacity of 55.
</P>
<P>
A local police officer said five others suffered serious
injuries in the mishap which was followed by an explosion.
</P>
</TEXT>
