<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Universal Declaration of Human Rights: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 9 (Xinhua) -- December 10, the World Human
Rights Day, will be marking the 50th anniversary of the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights. The Declaration was one of the first
major achievements of the United Nations, and after half a century it
remains a powerful instrument which continues to exert an enormous
effect on people's lives worldwide.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time in history that a document considered to
have universal value was adopted by an international organization. It
was also the first time that human rights and fundamental freedoms
were set forth in such detail. There was broad-based international
support for the Declaration when it was adopted.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. document represented "a world milestone in the long
struggle for human rights," said a U.N. General Assembly
representative from France.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of the Universal Declaration stems in large part from
the strong desire for peace in the aftermath of the World War II.
Although the 58 Member States which formed the United Nations at that
time varied in their ideologies, political systems and religious and
cultural backgrounds and had different patterns of socio-economic
development, the Universal Declaration of Human Rights represented a
common statement of goals and aspirations -- a vision of the world as
the international community would want it to become.
</P>
<P>
Since 1948, the Universal Declaration has been translated into
more than 200 languages and remains one of the best known and most
often cited human rights documents in the world.
</P>
<P>
Over the years, the Declaration has been used in the defense and
advancement of people's rights. Its principles have been enshrined in
and continue to inspire national legislation and the constitutions of
many newly independent states.
</P>
<P>
This year marks the 50th anniversary of this "Magna Carta for all
humanity." The theme of the 50th anniversary -- "All Human Rights for
All" -- highlights the universality, the indivisibility and the
interrelationship of all human rights.
</P>
<P>
It reinforces the idea that human rights -- civil, cultural,
economic, political and social -- should be taken in their totality
and not disassociated from one another.
</P>
<P>
PUBLIC AWARENESS CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
The 50th anniversary is a time to promote public awareness of the
meaning of the Universal Declaration and its relevance to our daily
lives. Providing information about human rights in the languages
understood by peoples everywhere is one aspect of a global public
campaign.
</P>
<P>
Falling during the Decade of Human Rights Education (1995 -
2004), the anniversary also provides another focus for education and
action. In addition to the 200 language versions already available,
a number of other local language translations are to be released for
the 50th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
The 50th anniversary of the Universal Declaration is an opportunity
for people worldwide to commemorate the adoption of the landmark
document. It also represents an opportunity to mobilize all strata
of society in a reinvigorated and broad-based human rights movement.
</P>
<P>
The involvement of civil society and non-governmental
organizations in fighting for an demanding recognition of basic
rights has played a central role in the advancement and promotion of
human rights around the world.
</P>
<P>
National committees have already been set up in many countries,
with the aim of undertaking activities to mark the upcoming
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS AND HUMAN RIGHTS
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the recommendations made at the 1993 World
Conference on Human Rights for increased coordination within the U.N.
system, Kofi Annan, the U.N. secretary-general, said, "I will be a
champion of human rights and will ensure that human rights are fully
integrated in the action of the Organization of all other domains."
</P>
<P>
Human rights, indeed, cut across all the work of the United
Nations, from peacekeeping, child rights, health and development to
the rights of indigenous peoples to education, social development
and the eradication of poverty.
</P>
<P>
Consultations have already taken place among all agencies and
programs of the United Nations, leading to strategies and campaigns
being devised.
</P>
<P>
CHALLENGES OF OUR ERA
</P>
<P>
Since the inception of the United Nations, the promotion and
protection of human rights have been at its very core. Reference to
the promotion of and respect for human rights was made in Article 1
of the U.N. Charter and in the establishment of a commission for the
promotion of human rights, mentioned in Article 68 of the Charter.
</P>
<P>
During the past 50 years, the United Nations has created a wide
range of mechanisms for monitoring human rights violations.
Conventional mechanisms (treaty bodies) and extra-conventional
mechanisms (U.N. special rapporteurs, representatives, experts and
working groups) have been established in order to monitor compliance
of state parties with the various human rights abuse.
</P>
<P>
Challenges still lie ahead, despite many accomplishments in the
field of human rights. Many in the international community believe
the human rights, democracy and development are interwined.
Unless human rights are respected, the maintenance of
international peace and security and the promotion of economic and
social development cannot be achieved.
</P>
<P>
The world is still plagued with incidents of ethnic hatred and
acts of genocide. People are still victims of xenophobic attitudes,
are subjected to discrimination because of religion or gender and
suffer from exclusion.
</P>
<P>
Around the world, millions of people are still denied food,
shelter, access to medical care, education and work, and too many live
in extreme poverty. Their inherent humanity and dignity are not
recognized.
</P>
<P>
What's even worse, some Western countries, with an excuse of the
alleged protection of human rights, have repeatedly interfered in
internal affairs of the developing world. Therefore, the future of
human rights lies in our hands. We must act all in one to guard
against such human rights preachment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0088 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
