<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, India Fail to Reach Agreement on Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh and India failed to
reach agreement Wednesday after two days of talks on trade issues
between the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
While Indian trade officials said that their market was open to
Bangladeshi exports, local businessmen here argued that the real
situation was quite different.
</P>
<P>
Tariff and non-tariff barriers, countervailing duties,
quantitative restrictions and canalization were some of the major
obstacles to increasing exports to India, they said.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with visiting Indian Commerce Secretary P.P.
Prahbu Thursday, President of the Federation of Bangladeshi
Chambers of Commerce and Industries (FBCCI) Abdul Mintoo claimed
that Bangladeshi exporters were not finding the Indian markets
accessible because of the barriers.
</P>
<P>
Flooding of local markets by Indian goods against a very poor
export of Bangladeshi items to India had widened the trade
imbalance between the two countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, Bangladesh imported goods
worth 937.69 million U.S. dollars from India against its exports
of only 65.58 million dollars during the 1997-98 fiscal year
ending June 30.
</P>
<P>
The figures showed an imbalance of 872 million dollars against
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
"Such a huge imbalance is not in the interest of sound trading
relationship and we fear that the situation may fast become
untenable," Mintoo told the Indian officials.
</P>
<P>
Referring to India's tariff cut and withdrawal of quantitative
restrictions on 2,000 items from export from SAARC (South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation) nations, the FBCCI chief
said, "These do not apply to Bangladesh in most cases."
</P>
<P>
He insisted that much remained for India to do in eliminating
non-tariff barriers for Bangladeshi products.
</P>
<P>
The Indian commerce secretary said that his country slashed
tariff under SAPTA (South Asian Preferential Trading Arrangement)
negotiations by 50 percent across the board for goods coming from
SAARC countries, and in many cases, tariff concession was 60
percent.
</P>
<P>
"The maximum tariff concession under the SAPTA was given by
India," Prahbu said. "Access to Indian market is not the issue
today."
</P>
<P>
On trade imbalance, he said Indian exports to Bangladesh were
rising because it was offering goods at a competitive price. "It's
not true that we are deliberately trying to import less and export
more."
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh mainly exports raw hides, leather, vegetable fat and
textile goods to India, and imports textile items, vegetable
products, mineral products, base metals, vehicles and consumer
items from India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0091 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
