<HEADLINE> Taiwan Affairs Office Warns A Few Divisive Forces To Stop Actions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A spokesman for the Communist
Party of China (CPC) Central Committee's Taiwan Work Office and
the State Council's Taiwan Affairs Office today warned a handful
of people in Taiwan to stop playing with fire in their attempts to
split the country.
</P>
<P>
"We have noted that a few of the Taiwan authorities have made
threatening remarks about separating Taiwan from the motherland by
holding a so-called referendum on the reunification issue and we
have also noticed that a few extreme separatists in favor
of 'Taiwan-Independence' in the city of Tainan recently held a
referendum on reunification and other issues," the spokesman said,
adding that the Taiwan Authorities have not taken effective steps
to stop this.
</P>
<P>
These is a dangerous example of "playing with fire" and a vain
attempt to use a referendum to stop the reunification of the
motherland and create "Taiwan independence," he said, "We firmly
oppose this and are issuing this stern warning to these divisive
forces."
</P>
<P>
There is only one China and Taiwan is an inalienable part of
it. This is the common understanding of Taiwan compatriots and all
other Chinese, and recognized by the international community, the
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that China's sovereignty and territorial
integrity are inseparable. That sovereignty includes Taiwan, the
Penghu, Chinmen and Matsu islands and these belong to all
Chinese, Taiwan compatriots included, and the reunification of the
motherland is the sacred historical mission of all Chinese people,
Taiwan compatriots included.
</P>
<P>
What Taiwan's divisive forces are doing is illegal, invalid,
and a futile attempt to oppose the reunification of China and to
change Taiwan's status as a part of China through a referendum, he
said.
</P>
<P>
These activities not only go against the will of the people on
both sides of the straits and seriously undermine the stability
and development of cross-straits relations, but will endanger the
safety of Taiwan compatriots as well as the peace and stability of
the Asia-Pacific Region, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We hope Taiwanese compatriots can tell the true nature of what
this divisiveness is supposedly doing in the name of democracy and
that with their patriotic tradition they will steadfastly guard
state sovereignty and territorial integrity and contribute to the
growth of cross-straits relations and push for the peaceful
reunification of the motherland," the spokesman concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
