<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Rejects Invitation for European Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Turkey has rejected the
invitation of the European Union (EU) to European Conference,
Foreign Ministry Deputy Spokesman Sermet Aracanli said here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"We won't participate in the European Conference because we
think the character and frame of this invitation is not
appropriate." Aracanli said at a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said Turkey is opposed to the formation of the
European Conference from the very beginning, and to the EU stance
toward Turkey's request of a full EU membership.
</P>
<P>
Last December, the EU decided in Luxembourg to reject Turkey as
a candidate for the EU membership.
</P>
<P>
"The EU summit decision, on certain point, was unfair,
sometimes biased and sometimes with the connotation of double
standards. Sometimes it was based on exaggerated allegations,"
Turkish Foreign Minister Ismail Cem said.
</P>
<P>
The EU last year decided to invite Poland, Hungary, the Czech
Republic, Estonia, Slovenia and Cyprus to start accession talks
early this year.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria, Latvia, Lithuania, Romania and Slovakia were put on a
slower negotiating track by the 15-nation union, leaving Turkey, a
34-year applicant, completely in the cold. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
