<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh Marks Human Rights Declaration Anniversary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi leaders Wednesday
issued separate messages to mark the 50th anniversary of the
adoption of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights by the
United Nations, which falls on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
President Shahabuddin Ahmed said in his message that Bangladesh
aspires and strives to promote the global cause of freedom and
fulfill its obligations to create a more peaceful, tolerant,
secure and prosperous world for the succeeding generations.
</P>
<P>
The people of Bangladesh join the rest of the international
community to re-dedicate themselves to the universal goal of
protecting and upholding the fundamental freedom and basic human
rights, he stated.
</P>
<P>
He said that the achievements of international institutions,
states and the embryonic civil society in laying down precise
human rights norms and standards are commendable.
</P>
<P>
But there remains much for translating the declaration into
reality, he observed.
</P>
<P>
In her message, Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina called upon the
international community to come together on an integrated approach
 to the question of human rights so that every man, woman and
child can live in peace with fullest dignity and enjoy all their
freedom.
</P>
<P>
She reiterated Bangladesh's deep commitment and unequivocal
support to the principles and purposes of the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
"We remind ourselves that we had fought our liberation war of
independence for realization of the fundamental rights and freedom
for our people," she said.
</P>
<P>
It is therefore an occasion "for us to take a renewed pledge
that the sacred ideals and goals set forth in the declaration are
translated into reality for every citizen of Bangladesh," and to
strive to secure those for the whole of mankind, she added.
</P>
</TEXT>
