<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Sweeps All-around Titles in Asiad Gymnastics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Defending champion China
captured both the men's and women's all-around titles in the
gymnastics competition of the Asian Games here on Wednesday,
sweeping all the four gold medals on offer so far in the teams'
and all-around contests.
</P>
<P>
The 19-year-old Liu Yuan crowned as the all-around queen with a
total of 38.787 points by leading all the way through uneven bars,
beam, floor exercises and vault.
</P>
<P>
Irina Yevdokimova took the silver with 37.912 while Japan's
Risa Sugawara picked up the bronze in 37.300.
</P>
<P>
"I'm so happy because this is my first all-around title in
major international event," said Liu Xuan, the Chinese captain who
once considered her retirement after the 1996 Olympic Games.
</P>
<P>
"So I really want to say thanks to my coach Lu Shanzhen because
it was him to encourage me to continue my carrer," said Liu, also
winner of the World Cup tournament early this year.
</P>
<P>
Liu single-handedly brought home the gold for China as her two
teammates, world floor champion Kui Yuanyuan and young talent Ling
Jie, both made big mistakes on their starting apparatuses and were
out of the gold contention after the first rotation.
</P>
<P>
"I saw their performances and I knew it was time for me to
stand out as the captain to do my duty," said Liu, whose flewless
display gave her an unbeatable 1.025 points lead after three
rotations.
</P>
<P>
"Liu Xuan is the only girl over 19 in our team," said Chinese
women's coach Lu Shanzhen, "She really save our team from an
empty-handed day with all her excellent performances. And I think
she has the potential to compete in next year's World
Championships or even the 2000 Olympics."
</P>
<P>
"I don't know if I can still compete in 2000, but what I know
is that my desire to compete with all the world best gymnasts is
still there. That means even harder work after the Asian Games for
me," said Liu, who started gymnastics training at an age of five
in her hometown Hunan province.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the afternoon, Huang Xu surged ahead with a stable
performence on his last apparatus of the pommel horse to take the
men's top personal honor in 57.825 points.
</P>
<P>
China's Yang wei picked up the silver in 57.600 and Japan's
Tsukiahara brought the bronze with 57.375.
</P>
<P>
The 19-year-old Huang Xu became the fourth Chinese gymnast to
win the men's all-around which China has been dominated since the
1978 Asian Game.
</P>
<P>
Huang, a member of China's 1997 world champion team,
established his lead from the first rotation where he started on
the rings and led all the way through four rotations before his
leading place was taken over by one-year younger Yang Wei after
five apparatuses.
</P>
<P>
Huang was 0.025 points behind Yang when he jumped on the pommel
horse. He received a good enough 9.575 points from a stable and
nearly flawless display to retain the lead to capture the Asiad
men's top honor.
</P>
<P>
Japan's Naoya Tsukahara, the bronze medalist in last year's
World Championship, followed closely the Chinese teenagers but
could not take over the lead with his low points of 9.350 and
9.400 on the horizontal bar and the floor.
</P>
<P>
China's has won both the men's and women's teams titles in
previous two-day competitions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
