<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Era For China's Rural Democracy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Organic Law on Village
Committees that took effect in early November is the result of 10
years of experimenting with the law and it means a new historic
period for China's rural democracy, according to Cao Zhi,
vice-chairman of the National People's Congress Standing Committee.
</P>
<P>
The system of self-government created by villagers is now a
part of the country's legal system," Cao told a government forum
to promote on the law, and asked people to understand the
political significance of the law and the spirit of the Communist
Party's rural policies when implementing the law.
</P>
<P>
First of all, he said, the democratic elections of village
heads must be in strict accordance with the law, which is the key
to democratic policy making, self-government, and supervision.
</P>
<P>
Anyone who violates this and halts elections with violence or
other unfair means must be dealt with in accordance with the law,
Cao said.
</P>
<P>
Second, Cao acknowledged that, affairs that concern villagers'
interests must be made public.
</P>
<P>
What they worry most about is financial affairs, fees collected
by the town government and by village officials, profits,
collectively-owned businesses, the distribution of disaster relief
and aid in some places, and funds raised by villagers, Cao said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
