<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 1/5 Households in Asia Receive Cable &AMP; Satellite TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, December 9 (Xinhua) -- An estimated one in five
households in Asia subscribed to cable or satellite services in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Singapore Minister for Information and the Arts and Second
Minister for Trade and Industry George Yeo made the announcement
Wednesday at the opening ceremony of the Cable &AMP; Satellite Asia
'98 and the Cable &AMP; Satellite Broadcasting Association of Asia
(CASBAA) Conference '98.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the ceremony, CASBAA President S.K. Fung
confirmed that there are 90 million homes in Asia receiving cable
&AMP; satellite television and the number is expected to augment to
200 million homes, about 36 percent of households, by the year
2005.
</P>
<P>
George Yeo said that the cable and satellite industries in Asia
have grown tremendously in the past years although this has been
moderated by the current economic downturn.
</P>
<P>
Taking China for example, George Yeo said around 700 million
households in China are receiving cable services and this number
is expected to reach 100 million by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The cable penetration rate in major Chinese cities like
Guangzhou, Beijing and Shanghai is between 80 percent and 90
percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
He also said Singapore's Service of Cable Vision (SCV) would
have cabled 82 percent of all homes by the end of this year while
the current penetration rate for cable TV is about 17 percent of
all homes.
</P>
<P>
When SCV completes the wiring-up of the whole island by the end
of next year, George Yeo said, over 900,000 Singapore households
will have direct access not only to cable TV but to a whole range
of broadband services from fast Internet to electronic banking.
</P>
<P>
George Yeo said great demand offers tremendous opportunities
for the growth of the cable and satellite broadcasting industry
and digital technology, the convergence of broadcast and
communication, and the rapidly changing social, political and
economic landscape in Asia present huge challenges to the
industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Hold International Agriculture Exposition '99 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese Ministry of
Agriculture will hold the China International Agricultural
Expo '99 in Beijing from September 23 to 28, 1999, Vice-minister
of Agriculture Wan Baorui said today, as part of the 50th
anniversary of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
It will be a showcase of China's agricultural and rural
economic developments of the past 50 years, especially since
the reforms and opening-up began two decades ago. It will also
encourage exchanges and cooperation with other countries in
agriculture.
</P>
<P>
He says that the Asian financial crisis and the devastating
summer floods have had an impacts on China's economy, and
especially on agriculture, so the central government allocated
another 35 billion yuan (4.2 billion US dollars) this year for
agriculture, for seed breeding, poverty relief, irrigation, and
ecological protection projects.
</P>
<P>
He said that China's 860 million rural people are a vast market
with big potential and the Chinese government will further open up
the domestic market, improve the investment environment, and
create more favorable conditions for overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
China had evolved 7,300 agricultural projects with contracts
worth 14 billion U.S. dollars of overseas investment in the past
20 years. China's agricultural produce in 1997 was worth 24.7
billion U.S. dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
