<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Upholds Palestinian Rights to Declare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, December 9 (Xinhua)-- Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) Chairman Yasser Arafat said Wednesday that Israel has no
right to stop the Palestinians from declaring an independent
state.
</P>
<P>
"They are telling us that we should not mention the
word 'state', but I told them we have said that word and have
declared it," Arafat was quoted by Israel Radio as telling
members of his Fatah movement in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian leader also said that the date is drawing near
when Jerusalem becomes the capital of a future Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Observers noted that Arafat did not say, as before, that he
will unilaterally declare a state on May 4, 1999, when the interim
period stipulated by the Oslo accords terminates..
</P>
<P>
Israel and the Palestinians have been engaged in a war of words in
the last few days over several issues concerning the
implementation of the Wye accord signed on October 23.
</P>
<P>
Israel threatened last week that it will not carry out the
second stage of redeployment stipulated in the accord, scheduled
next week, if the Palestinians fail to meet some conditions,
including a public pledge by Arafat that he will not unilaterally
declare Palestinian statehood.
</P>
<P>
Also on Wednesday, the Palestinians staged a general strike in
the West Bank to mark the 11th anniversary of the beginning of the
Intifada, the Palestinian uprising against Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Ahmed Yassin, spiritual leader of the Islamic
Resistance Movement (Hamas), joined in the protest Wednesday by
starting a hunger strike at his home in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
Several clashes broke out Wednesday in the West Bank and the
Arab East Jerusalem as Palestinian demonstrations aimed at
pressing Israel to release Palestinian prisoners continued but
scaled down.
</P>
<P>
At least one Israeli woman was injured by stones thrown by
Palestinian protesters, Israel Radio reported. Israeli soldiers
kept Israeli cars from driving on certain roads in the West Bank
to avoid possible attacks.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians, demanding the release of political prisoners,
are angry over Israel's inclusion of 150 common criminals in the
first group of 250 Palestinian prisoners freed in November
according to the new land-for-peace interim deal.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian officials said Israel had made a verbal promise
during the talks in the United States that all 750 prisoners to be
released will be political detainees, those who took part in
anti-Israel activities.
</P>
<P>
But Israel insisted that it had never agreed to release those
with "blood on their hands" or members of militant groups like
Hamas. Washington urged the two sides to resolve their difference
through negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The disputes, however, have sparked several days of protests
and clashes in the West Bank and Gaza strip, which were called by
Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon as a "new intifada," during
which scores of people have been wounded.
</P>
<P>
The prisoner issue is highly emotional because it touches
nearly all Palestinian families. Almost every family has had a
member or relative arrested at some point since 1967, when Israel
seized the West Bank, Gaza and East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reports said Yassin was also protesting against
the PNA over their treatment of him and other Hamas members.
</P>
<P>
Yassin has been put under a house arrest and hundreds of Hamas
activists have been detained by the PNA since the signing of the
Israeli-Palestinian peace deal, under which the Palestinians are
obligated to crack down militant groups in exchange for Israeli
withdrawal from 13 percent of the West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
