<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Following are the major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- The White House largely dropped its attack-the-accuser
impeachment strategy Tuesday to offer its most comprehensive
rebuttal yet to the case against U.S. President Bill Clinton,
declaring that he should not be thrown out of office even though
his extramarital affair was "sinful" and his sworn testimony
"maddening."
</P>
<P>
-- Scientists in Japan have cloned several calves from a single
adult cow, the third species of mammal to be genetically
duplicated after sheep and mice, and the most commercially
important animal to be cloned to date.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- A power failure blacked out San Francisco in the U.S. during
the morning rush hour Tuesday and lasted for more than six hours.
Officials said a construction crew's error was responsible.
</P>
<P>
-- The U.S. National Security Adviser, Samuel R. Berger, openly
appealed for Arab support in the government's campaign to oust
Iraqi President Saddam Hussein.
</P>
<P>
The Wall Street Journal:
</P>
<P>
-- Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu said he was
unlikely to go ahead with an Israeli troop withdrawal from the
West Bank next week despite a scheduled visit by President
Clinton. 
</P>
