<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Three Games Records Fall as China Upstages Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Three Asian Games' records were
broken here on Wednesday when the Chinese swimmers upstaged their
Japanese rivals 3-2 in the gold hunt.
</P>
<P>
The 16-year-old teenager Chen Hua had a morale-boosting start
for China when she won the women's 400m freestyle in four minutes
and 12.31 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Her winning time also beat the former games mark of 4:13.55,
set by her Compatriot Yan Ming in Beijing eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
Scachiko Yamada won the silver in 4:14.53, with Tsai Shu-Min
third in 4:15.66.
</P>
<P>
"I caught a fever before the match and I haven't expected to
win," Chen said. "I just wanted to do my best."
</P>
<P>
"The withdrawal of Chen Yan put a lot of pressure upon me,
perhaps this helps me much in the match."
</P>
<P>
The gold of the following event went to Japan when 22-year-old
Shunsuke Ito clocked 51.29 to win the men's 100m freestyle,
beating China's Zhao Lifeng into the third place.
</P>
<P>
Shunsuke's younger twin brother Shusuke Ito was second in
52.07. Zhao came in third in 52.21.
</P>
<P>
"I'm extremely happy to win the gold for Japan," said Shunsuke.
</P>
<P>
But Shusuke was as pleased. He quipped: "I'm always second to
my elder brother. I'm determined to beat him next time."
</P>
<P>
It was Tomoko Hagiwara who stole the limelight on Wednesday
when she beat favored Mai Nakamura to win the women's 100m
backstroke.
</P>
<P>
The 18-year-old Japanese finished in 1:01.84 for the gold. Team
mate Nakamura, silver medallist in the World Championships in
Perth, Australia in January, had to settle for second in 1:02.11.
Choi Soo-Min of South Korea was third in 1:03.37.
</P>
<P>
"As everybody expected Nakamura to win, I was very surprised
when I found I have won the gold," said Hagiwara. "I just wanted
to do my best, never expect to beat Nakamura."
</P>
<P>
"When I touched home, I looked at the screen to see my time. I
saw I won, " She said. "It's really a surprise."
</P>
<P>
Fu Yong measured up to the pre-match tippings as he clinched
the gold of the men's 200m backstroke in style.
</P>
<P>
The 20-year-old Chinese, whom head coach Zhang Xiong said would
be sure to win in this event, retook the lead from Malaysia's Lim
Keng-Liat in the 100-meter mark and never relinquished it.
</P>
<P>
His winning time of 1:59.30, the fourth best of the year, also
broke the old games record of 2:00.65, which was set by South
Korean Ji Sang-Joon in Hiroshima in 1994. Keng-Liat came in second
in 2:00.94, with Raymond Papa of the Philippines third in 2:01.80.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese swimmers put on the finish winning note by beating
their own games record to win the women's 4x100m freestyle relay
race in 3:45.51. The former mark of 3:46.39 was also set in
Beijing in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Japan finished second in 3:47.65 and Chinese Taipei came in
third in 3:51.48.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xiong was satisfied with his swimmers' performance. "Chen
Hua opened a good start for us, and her win greatly boosted our
morale."
</P>
<P>
"Our Chinese swimmers' performances moved up a step compared to
their medicore show yesterday," he added.
</P>
<P>
China only managed five silvers to Japan's four golds in five
swimming events on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
