<HEADLINE> Japanese WWII Chemical Weapons Still Injuring Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- More than 2,000 Chinese have
been hurt by chemical weapons left behind by Japanese troops from
their invasion in China half a century ago, and some have died as
a result, according to a 400-page report from the Heilongjiang
People's Publishing House, "History of Japan's Chemical War".
</P>
<P>
One of the people who helped prepare it says that the fact that
there are still bombs around affecting city construction work,
government work, classroom order.
</P>
<P>
Japan began its chemical weapons research in 1915 and used the
weapons on a large scale during the invasion of China from
1937-1945. Japanese troops used the weapons in 16 major battles
and in experiments with human beings as live targets.
</P>
<P>
After the end of World War II, many chemical weapons were left
behind and the Chinese government does not know their location or
number, the report says.
</P>
<P>
For the past four decades, chemical weapons have been
discovered in many places. Between 1990 and 1993, people in east
China's Zhejiang province discovered Japanese gas bombs while
draining a canal. In 1991, about 50 gas bombs that were unearthed
on a middle school campus in north China's Hebei province
injuried 20 students.
</P>
<P>
For more than 20 years, Li Chen, a sailor, has lived a painful
existence because of a Japanese bomb. Li and 34 others were
injuried by the bomb while draining a river in Heilongjiang
province in northeastern China in 1974. Li was burned over 90
percent of his body and even today occasionally has problems with
his skin. He says that sometimes he wants to kill himself just to
find relief from the pain.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1990s, the Chinese government has signed agreements
with the Japanese on ways to deal with the problem. But, because
of the silence of officers and soldiers from that time, the
location and number of the bombs remain a mystery.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
