<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wang Xianbo Takes Dramatic Win for China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Wang Xianbo scored a dramatic
win over Japanese Kimoto Nami in the women's 63 kilograms judo
category at the Asian Games here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Wang, Olympic bronze medalist in 1996, dominated the less known
Kimoto from the start and looked sure to win.
</P>
<P>
But at the ringing of bell, Kimoto, cheered by a boisterous
crowd on the stand, used all her strength to throw the 22-year-old
Chinese onto the mat.
</P>
<P>
The referee immediately ruled Kimoto the winner. The Japanese
fans, coaches and athletes roared but all the Chinese were angered.
</P>
<P>
Wang's coach Wu Weifeng jumped to the mat and questioned the three
judges, while Wang appeared shocked, knees down with the head in
her hands.
</P>
<P>
"I only regret I should never slacken off in the final
seconds," the tearful Wang said. "But I heard the bell. I thought
the match had ended."
</P>
<P>
The Chinese officials submitted their protest to the
arbitration panel, which changed the original ruling and gave the
gold medal to Wang after 10 minutes of discussion.
</P>
<P>
"The gold medal should belong to me," Wang choked. "From the
start to the end, I was holding an andvantage."
</P>
<P>
Now it was the turn of Kimoto to cry. Her parents, who had been
sitting on the stand to cheer her, came up to console her. The
Japanese coaches also submitted their protest but the result
remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
"This is a big mistake for the referee. He didn't hear the
bell," Chinese manager Liu Yuqi said.
</P>
<P>
This is the first judo gold for the Chinese after three days
of frustration.
</P>
<P>
South Korean Kim Hwa-Soo and Wu Mei-Ling of Chinese Taipei
finished joint third.
</P>
<P>
South Korea got a gold harvest by grabbing the other three gold
medals.
</P>
<P>
Yoo Sung-Yeon beat 1993 world champion Nakamura Yoshio of Japan
to win the men's 90kg division. Purevsuren D. of Mongolia and
Nurodov Kamol of Uzbekistan came joint third.
</P>
<P>
The women's 70kg class gold was captured by Lim Jung-Sook, who
ousted Amao Miki in the final.
</P>
<P>
The bronze went to Song Jianfeng of China and Chen Chiu-Ping of
Chinese Taipei.
</P>
<P>
Cho In-Chul beat DPR Korea's Kwak Ok-Chol to win the men's 82kg
gold, with Kazem Sarikhani of Iran and Ruslan Seilkhanov of Kazakhstan
placing joint third. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
