<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Urges NATO to Act With U.N. Mandate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Igor
Ivanov on Wednesday warned the North Atlantic Treaty Organization
(NATO) to resort to force only with the mandate of the United
Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov was stressing the necessity of using international law
as the basis for the alliance's new strategic concept at the
NATO-Russia Permanent Joint Council in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
"The use of force should be based on the United Nations
Security Council resolutions and any (NATO) decision to use force
has to be taken within the framework of the United Nations Charter
Article Seven," said Ivanov, who was participating in the council
for the first time as foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said that he made clear to NATO Secretary-General Javier
Solana Russia's views on some basic points that would form the new
strategic concept of the western military alliance, but he did not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the NATO strategy should not result in setting
up new divisions in Europe.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov reiterated that Russia is strongly opposed to NATO
enlargement into the former Soviet republics in the Baltic region.
</P>
<P>
He said that Russia's approach to this issue was made well
known before the Madrid summit when NATO invited Poland, Hungary
and the Czech Republic to start accession talks.
</P>
<P>
"Our approach remains the same as before Madrid," said Ivanov.
</P>
<P>
NATO and Russia agreed on Wednesday that necessary steps should
be undertaken to complete the adaptation of the Treaty on
Conventional Forces in Europe (CFE) in accordance with the
declaration issued by the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe in Oslo.
</P>
<P>
In regard to the work of the permanent joint council, Ivanov
said that the council had achieved "quite a lot" in the past year
though neither side was 100 percent satisfied.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the council was only "an institution for
consultation" and neither side had the right to veto.
</P>
<P>
Ivanov said that Russia was still waiting for technical
problems to be redressed before it could confirm readiness to
participate in the aerial verification led by NATO in Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
