<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Population Estimated to Rise to 7.54 Million in Mid-2008 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong's population is
projected to increase from an estimate of 6.68 million in mid-1998
to 7.54 million in mid-2008, Katherine Fok, secretary for health
and welfare, said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This represents an average annual growth rate of around 1.2
percent or an overall increase in population of 863,000 over the
ten-year period, Fok said in a written reply to a question in the
Legislative Council meeting.
</P>
<P>
She said that natural increase accounts for around 28 percent
of the projected population growth while balance of arrivals over
departures accounts for the remaining 72 percent.
</P>
<P>
Fok said that the fertility rate of Hong Kong is already one of
the lowest in the world, having dropped from 1.37 per reproductive
age woman in 1986 to 1.19 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The number of births registered per year has decreased in the
past 10 years from 73,030 (13 per thousand population) in 1988 to
60,379 (9.3 per thousand population) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
This suggested that the concept of family planning is well
accepted by the public, she said.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey done in 1997 showed that the percentage of a
representative sample of 1,511 married women practicing
contraception has risen from 72 percent in 1977 to 86 percent in
1997.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
