<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic briefs
from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
RIYADH -- The total insurance subscriptions in the Saudi market
last year nearly doubled the previous year's figure to reach 5.1 billion
rials (760 million dollars), the "Al Hayat" newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
The National Company of Cooperative Insurance released the
statistics it gathered. The figures justified the growth of
insurance subscriptions in the market to the "distinguished
growth" in the car and medical insurances in 1997.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, subscriptions in all other insurance branches
had declined.
</P>
<P>
Insurance market sources attributed the insurance decline to
static insurance awareness in Saudi Arabia, on the one hand, and
to the concentration of promotion efforts and attention on the
part of government departments on car and medical insurances, on
the other other.
</P>
<P>
DOHA -- Secretary General of the Doha-based Gulf Industrial
Investment Organization Abdul Rahman Al Jifri has called for the
establishment of large non-Gulf industries capable of confronting
the anticipated heated competition by giant companies.
</P>
<P>
Jifri on Tuesday inaugurated the second forum of industrial
investment companies in the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) states,
held the Doha Sheraton hotel. It was attended by senior officials
of Gulf industrial companies.
</P>
<P>
Jifri stated that industrial investments in the GCC states
increased from 28.5 billion dollars in 1988 to 80 billion dollars
in 1998, at an annual rate of 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
He added that the number of industrial establishments in the
GCC states grew from 4,692 in 1988 to over 7,359 in 1998, outside
the petroleum sector. Likewise, the work force created by these
industries has increased in volume, from 253,000 workers to over
567,000 workers in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Jifri pointed out that total foreign investments in joint
industrial ventures in the GCC states by the end of 1998 would
reach 16 billion dollars, whereas local investments in these
projects stood at 23 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
DOHA -- The Gulf helicopter company, a Qatari joint stock
company with a paid capital of 66 million Qatari rials (about 18
million dollars) has been established, it was announced in Qatar.
</P>
<P>
The Qatari general petroleum establishment undertook the
formation of the new company which had originally been under the
Qatar Airways.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordan's budget deficit for 1998 has been so far 2.3
percentage points higher than the government's prediction, the
semi-official Jordan Times quoted an unnamed official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The deficit now accounts for 9.3 percent of the gross domestic
product while the government's prediction a few weeks ago was
just 7 percent, the official added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
