<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chicken Pox Vaccine Gets Approval in Canada </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A vaccine for the highly
contagious chicken pox disease will be available in Canada in
early January.
</P>
<P>
Merck Frosst Canada Inc., which developed the vaccine, said
Tuesday that it has been approved by the health
authorities for use on healthy people over one year old.
</P>
<P>
The vaccine is expected to be about 62 Canadian dollars (40
U.S. dollars) a dose, the company said. The cost of treating the
disease, barring complications, is about 350 Canadian dollars (227
U.S. dollars) per patient.
</P>
<P>
Chicken pox, a member of the herpes family, afflicts 350,000
Canadians a year, said Stanley Read, chief of the infectious
diseases divisions at the Hospital for Sick Children, in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
Though the disease is known as more of an irritant than a
danger, serious complications can arise from the viral infection,
which can sometimes result in death. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
