<HEADLINE> Luxury Cars Doing Well In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The new Mercedes-Benz S-model
went on sale in Beijing Monday for a fast-growing luxury car
market.
</P>
<P>
And, last week, Volvo put its lastest models on the China
market. Other luxury car makers like BMW and General Motors
released their models earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
The president of Mercedes-Benz China Limited. says that
Mercedes sells more than 4,500 cars annually in China and that the
three S-Class models will probably be welcomed by Chinese
consumers.
</P>
<P>
In sharp contrast to crisis-hit Southeast Asia, China's
Mercedes sales have continued to rise since the Daimler-Benz and
Chrysler merger, he says. Their marketing strategy in China is
long-term, he says, and a booming economy will no doubt help sales.
</P>
<P>
Companies and money-making individuals have been replacing
government institutions as luxury car buyers for the past several
years, after the ban on expensive purchase by government officials.
</P>
<P>
Volvo is targeting the individual consumer with a strong need
for self-development and exploration, says Leif Engstrom, Volvo's
chief representative in China. The company launched its S80 model
this June to increase its competitiveness. In the past ten years,
Volvo has gained quite a reputation in China, Engstrom says.
</P>
<P>
Volvo began selling cars for taxis in major Chinese cities in
the mid-1980s and has designated retailers in southern, central,
eastern and northeastern parts of the country. It is looking for
ways to produce cars in China.
</P>
<P>
The Benz S500 currently sells for 2.2 million yuan in China,
more than 10 times the price of sedans produced by joint ventures.
</P>
</TEXT>
