<HEADLINE> Gulf Summit Ends in UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Gulf Leaders on Wednesday
ended their 19th summit with a call for actions to shore up the
falling oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The call was made in a joint communique issued at the end of
the three-day summit of the Gulf Cooperation Council which groups
Bahrain, Kuwait, Qatar, Oman, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab
Emirates.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, the leaders of the six GCC states discussed
ways to prop up oil prices, joint security and economic
cooperation, the situation in Iraq, relations with Iran, the
Middle East peace process and other related issues.
</P>
<P>
How to curb the collapse of the oil prices that has left Gulf
Arab economies reeling dominated the summit which was held when
the crude oil fell to a historic low of less than 10 U.S. dollars
per barrel.
</P>
<P>
Saudi Arabia, the world's top oil producer and leading power in
the GCC, urged its neighbors to adopt a united and strong position
on the world market and make their weight felt in decision-making.
</P>
<P>
It was time to do something about the low oil prices, Saudi
Crown Prince Abdullah Ibn Abdul-Aziz said at the annual summit.
</P>
<P>
The Gulf oil producers, whose economy depends heavily on oil
earnings, have been hit hard by the sharp drop in oil prices
resulting from oversupply and flagging demand. 
</P>
</TEXT>
