<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Jets Stage Mock Raids on Lebanese Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Israeli fighter-bombers
Wednesday buzzed several main cities of Lebanon, including the
capital of Beirut.
</P>
<P>
An Israeli jet flew to Beirut at 9:10 a.m. (0710 GMT) and
crashed the sound barrier in two low-level flights. Sonic booms
shook many parts of the city where windows and doors of buildings
were severely jolted.
</P>
<P>
In the country's third largest city of Sidon, about 40
kilometers south of the capital, a thunderous mock raid at dawn
had forced thousands of residents out of bed to scurry to
basements as the Israeli jets howled overhead for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Similar mock air raids were also staged over south Lebanon's
densely populated market town of Nabatiyeh, the Orient radio
reported.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli violent act is designed as a warning against
Lebanese government and the resistance movement after a wave of
deaths Israeli forces suffered last month, said foreign diplomats
here.
</P>
<P>
Last month, a total of seven Israeli soldiers were killed in
less than 10 days by Hezbollah guerrillas' bomb ambush inside the
Israeli occupied south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah, or Party of God, backed by Iran, is leading a
guerrilla war to oust Israeli forces from south Lebanon where
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in 1985.
</P>
<P>
The mounting casualties have rekindled heated debate in Israel
over whether it is wise to continue military presence in the
Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
However, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and his
government insist that Israeli forces will not pull out from south
Lebanon unless Beirut agrees to guarantee security for Israel's
north. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
