<HEADLINE> Iraq-UNSCOM Dispute Occurs in Surprise Inspection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A dispute occurred Wednesday
when an inspection team of the U.N. Special Commission on
disarming Iraq (UNSCOM) tried to enter one of the ruling Baath
Party headquarters "in a provocative way," said an Iraqi official.
</P>
<P>
Hussam Mohammed Ameen, head of the Iraqi liaison U.N. arms
inspectors, said in a statement carried by the Iraqi News Agency
that at 9 a.m. (0600 GMT) that one of the inspection teams tried,
without prior notice, to enter one of the party headquarters in
Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
Ameen added that a party comrade there asked the inspection
team to write the materials or things that they intended to
inspect, but the team rejected the demand and left the site.
</P>
<P>
"Do UNSCOM elements need to search for materials pertaining to
the process of scrapping weapons of mass destruction in
headquarters of political parties?" Ameen asked.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi official stressed that such provocative and
surprising style practiced by UNSCOM inspection teams was aimed at
fabricating crises and problems.
</P>
<P>
UNSCOM Chairman Richard Butler said in New York Monday that
surprise inspections that would be carried out in this week and
early next week were to test Iraq's promise of full cooperation
with U.N. arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
Butler said that he had renewed work in four areas, namely
access to document, monitoring, interviews and visits to
so-called "capable sites" which might have potential for use for
forbidden purposes.
</P>
<P>
The fifth area was investigation of sites where prohibited
weapons programs might exist, he said.
</P>
<P>
In mid-November, Iraq announced unconditional resumption of
cooperation with U.N. arms inspections it suspended three months
ago. By doing that, Iraq narrowly escaped the U.S.-led air
strikes against it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
