<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, December 9 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela Wednesday wrapped up his two-day visit to Riyadh,
Saudi Arabia where he held talks with King Fahd Ibn Abdul-Aziz on
cementing bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Mandela discussed with the King on Tuesday means of further
boosting the rapidly-developing relations between their two
countries, the Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The two leaders also exchanged views on the prospective
strategic agreements due to be signed soon on establishing a
permanent cooperation partnership between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Mandela had arrived from Abu Dhabi, the United Arab Emirates
where he attended the opening session of the 19th Summit of the
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC). This was Mandela's second visit to
the Gulf kingdom since November, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Mandela's visit also came after South Africa's executive Vice
President Thabo Mbeki visited Saudi Arabia last November, when
Riyadh and Pretoria agreed to develop a strategic partnership.
</P>
<P>
Trade between Saudi Arabia and South Africa has seen rapid
growth in recent years, with its volume reaching 433.6 million
U.S. dollars in 1996, 10 times that of 1994, when the two
countries restored diplomatic relations. 
