<HEADLINE> Dow Corning Increase Presence in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Dow Corning, one of the world's
leading silicon products producers, is taking China as a key to
its development strategy for the 21st century, according to
Richard Hoover, president of the company's Asian operations.
</P>
<P>
He said the company has gone through some difficult times in
its Asian operations for the past two years, and is looking toward
a major expansion in the region in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
Recently, Dow Corning invested several hundred million yuan in
the Songjiang Silicon Manufacturing Factory in Shanghai. It has
also opened a representative office in Chengdu in southwest
China's Sichuan Province.
</P>
<P>
At present, the company's products enjoy a remarkable share of
the market in textiles, construction, automobiles, rubber,
plastics and other manufacturing industries. Corning accounts for
over 90 percent of the sealing rubber market in the country's
construction industry.
</P>
<P>
It now has one solely owned company, two representative
offices, and one factory in China.
</P>
<P>
The company's silicon products have become major ingredients in
cosmetics and personal care products in China.
</P>
<P>
A senior technician from Procter and Gamble (P&AMP;G) said their
new shampoo uses Dow Corning silicon products to achieve better
moisturizing and protecting effects.
</P>
<P>
A P&AMP;G official noted that in the past, Dow Corning focused on
large customers and refused to accept small orders.
</P>
<P>
However, the company has apparently strengthened its services
for small- and medium-sized customers. It invited representatives
from more than 100 Chinese enterprises to a Beijing workshop
meeting with the theme of "serving customers in a changing Asian
market."
</P>
<P>
At the workshop meeting, Corning announced that it will offer
training and education programs to its customers' employees in
China. It also sponsors several doctoral-candidate graduate
students at the Chinese Academy of Sciences and other Chinese
universities.
</P>
<P>
"We will take providing extraordinary service to our customers
in China, and in the rest of Asia, as a new key focus to enhance
our competitive edge," Hoover said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
