<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK's Water Meets World Health Organization Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A Hong Kong official said
here Wednesday that the average level of free chlorine residue of
Hong Kong's potable water complies with the World Health
Organization's (WHO) Guidelines for Drinking Water Quality (1993).
</P>
<P>
WHO required that the level should not exceed 5 mg per liter of
water while Hong Kong's level was about 1 mg, said Kwong Hon-sang,
Secretary for Works, in a written reply to a question in the
Legislative Council meeting.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the level of trichloromethane in Hong
Kong's drinking water caused minimal health risk to human beings.
Trichloromethane is a substance formed when chlorine reacts with
other impurities in raw water.
</P>
<P>
"Records of the Water Supplies Department show that a
trichloromethane level below 50 micrograms per liter of water has
been maintained for many years," he said.
</P>
<P>
The requirement of WHO's guidelines is not to exceed 200
micrograms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
