<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Human Rights Protected by Basic Law in HK: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) of China said
here Wednesday that human rights are protected by the
constitutional document of Basic Law in the SAR.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong has a long tradition of respecting and safeguarding
human rights, Tung said in a written statement Wednesday, the day
prior to the 50th Anniversary of the Universal Declaration of
Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
The rights proclaimed in the declaration have been given legal
substance through the International Covenant of Civil and
Political Rights and the International Covenant on Economic,
Social, and Cultural Rights, both of which have applied to Hong
Kong for more than 20 years and are entrenched in the Basic Law,
Tung noted in the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement will be included in a special publication to mark
the occasion, to be distributed by the Home Affairs Bureau of the
SAR to the public Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Together, the declaration and the two covenants comprise the
International Bill of Rights, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
The declaration was born into a world that had barely emerged
from the Second World War - a war in which there had been more
fatalities than in any human conflict before or since, a war that
had spawned new depths of inhumanity, he said.
</P>
<P>
In 1948, the world desperately needed an affirmation of right
values and a reassurance that simple human decency still
prevailed: a covenant among the nations proclaiming their common
goal to do better by the peoples of the earth, he added.
</P>
<P>
"We salute the noble and laudable aims of those who formulated
the Universal Declaration," the chief executive said.
</P>
<P>
"We, in Hong Kong, are indeed fortunate to live in a society
where human rights - founded on the bedrock of the rule of law -
are woven into the very fabric of our lives," Tung noted.
</P>
<P>
However, the chief executive reminded people that every right
entails, as its natural concomitant, a corresponding duty.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong remains a robust and lively community where people
have no hesitation in speaking their minds, Tung said.
</P>
<P>
"We will do everything to protect and preserve these rights,"
he stressed.
</P>
<P>
"But we should also be mindful of the vision of those who
drafted the Universal Declaration, that we also owe a duty to the
community which nurtures and forms us, and without which our lives
would be without substance," Tung concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
