<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Successfully Test Launches New ICBM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Russian strategic missile
force has successfully test launched a new Topol-M
intercontinental ballistic missile from the Plesetsk launching
center in northern Russia, Interfax reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The launch reaffirmed the main flight and technical
parameters of the missile, which are unique to the Topol-M, and
completed "a key stage in developing the missile complex of the
21st century", the force's press service said.
</P>
<P>
This was the sixth test launch of the Topol-M missile.
</P>
<P>
Russia is counting on the Topol-M missile to equip its
strategic missile force for the next century as most of its
ballistic missiles currently in service have outlived their
service life.
</P>
<P>
Anatoly Perminov, chief of the strategic missile force's
general staff, said late November that 58 percent of the missiles
have outlived their service life.
</P>
<P>
"The service life of almost 70 percent of space probes, 90
percent of ground services and one third of launch systems is also
over," Perminov said.
</P>
<P>
The first regiment equipped with 10 new Topol-M missiles in
Tatishchevo will come on duty this year, force commander
Colonel-General Vladimir Yakovlev said.
</P>
<P>
First Deputy Prime Minister Yuri Maslyukov, who oversees the
country's military industry complex, said last Friday the
strategic missile force would acquire 10 more Topol-M missiles
next year. By the year 2000, Russia plans to have 40 Topol-M
missiles in service. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
