<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0150 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Economic Conference (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The conference called for attention to be paid to four major
issues for improving economic activities in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Firstly, while ensuring the continuation of an appropriately
paced economic growth, efforts should be focused on making the
best use of the existing economic structure while at the same time
improving the quality and efficiency of growth overall.
</P>
<P>
It is accepted that fairly fast growth can generate more jobs,
increase revenues, improve the living standards of people. It may
also contribute to solving problems arising from the current
reforms.
</P>
<P>
Taking into account the prevailing conditions of a socialist
market economy, the speed of economic development should be
measured and set against agreed forecasts and should be market-led
rather than imposed in a mandatory manner. It should also be based
on reality, be well coordinated and highly efficient.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, to improve domestic demand and expand the domestic
market will be a basic policy platform within a long-term economic
strategy.
</P>
<P>
While continuing to increase the central government's
investment, more measures will be taken to encourage the
investment portfolio of enterprises, collectives and individuals.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, further efforts will be made to expand urban and
rural markets and nurture new consumer hot spots to stimulate even
more consumption.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, active fiscal and monetary policies will be
implemented with the aim of encouraging and domestic demand and
expand domestic market. A key task is to make sure that increased
investment funds will be used for infrastructure construction in
an efficient way.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, efforts will be introduced to assist the improvement
of tax collection.
</P>
<P>
Fourthly, the conference declared that close attention should
be paid to guaranteeing social and political stability, while
deepening the reforms and promoting economic development.
</P>
<P>
All Party members, especially leading Party officials at
different levels, should take economic work as the central issue
and firmly push forward the reform and opening drive, while
sticking to the Four Cardinal Principles.
</P>
<P>
The timing and extent of reform measures must always be well
thought out in accordance with the capacity of the public and with
due considerations on coordination between various
measures. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops First Window-Cleaning Robot </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Technology widely used on
aircraft propellors has been adapted by Chinese engineers to
develop a special robot for cleaning the outside windows of
skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
"It is expected to do away with human cleaners who have to hang
precariously on the outside of tall buildings and should greatly
increase efficiency," said Zhang Qixian, a professor with the
Robot Institute of Beijing University of Aeronautics and
Astronautics, who is also a member of the Chinese Academy of
Engineering.
</P>
<P>
"Technically it was difficult to develop such a robot. Foreign
engineers have tried by using suction pads but they restricted the
robots movements," explained Doctor Tang Shiming, one of the main
inventors of the new window-cleaning robot.
</P>
<P>
"We use a ducted fan, which works like a propeller, to produce
thrust at the direction of the wall which makes the robot adhere
to the structure," said Tang, adding that "with the help of four
wheels and a cable hoist, the robot can move horizontally and
vertically."
</P>
<P>
"Experiments have proved that it can also handle obstacles like
window frames," he said.
</P>
<P>
Although the robot does not resemble a human -- it is a cuboid,
0.78 meters long, 0.53 meters wide and 0.25 meters high and
weighing 10 kilograms -- it can imitate a human's way of cleaning
windows.
</P>
<P>
In further experiments it demonstrated that it can clean an
area of 10 square meters every minute, nearly 10 times faster than
a human.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang Qixian, the robot is still in the
experimental stage and now his engineering experts plan to equip
it with a remote control system and waste detergent recycling
device.
</P>
<P>
Apart from windows in skyscrapers, the robot can also clean
marble walls and ceramic tiles, Mr Zhang revealed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: Chinese Economy Expected To Enjoy Further Improvement (1) By Chen Xin </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- All major economic indicators
show that China's economy is likely to maintain its current
momentum next year provided the world economic situation doesn't
deteriorate further.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese economy has enjoyed an accelerated pace of
development since the middle of the year, thanks to the central
government's series of overall economic control measures to offset
the negative influences of the Southeast Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
The major economic indicators, especially fixed assets
investment and industrial output, have all bounced back up from
their previous low ebb. With the increase in demand, industrial
output nationwide has picked up in recent months.
</P>
<P>
As the year draws to a close, Chinese economic pundits are
examining and commenting on the country's year long performance.
Mainstream economists are already projecting that this year's
economic growth rate will fall within the range of 7.5 percent to
eight percent.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of the year the growth rate stood at seven
percent, only one percent short of the set target.
</P>
<P>
Fan Jianping, an expert from the State Development Planning
Commission's macro economic research institute, sounded a most
positive note about the economy's performance, which has seen it
stand firm against the huge pressures exerted in the export sector
as a result of the continuing Asian financial crisis. It also took
a hammering due to the severe floodings across the country this
summer.
</P>
<P>
Mr Fan said that China has made flexible adjustments to its
monetary and fiscal policies since the beginning of the year, when
the adverse influences of the world's economic problems were
gathering like storm clouds on the country's borders.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the central bank has lowered interest rates three
times within the year, an extreme rarity in the past, adding that
the government has also adopted more drastic fiscal measures since
the middle of the year.
</P>
<P>
In view of poor domestic demand and a shrinking monetary
supply, the Chinese government issued 100 billion yuan in
long-term treasury bonds, along with a number of banks which
provided a further 100 billion yuan in loans, which are earmarked
for the expansion and construction of infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
"These measures have worked tangible miracles on the economy,"
Fan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review - Chinese Economy Expected To Enjoy Further Improvement (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"The upturn in the Chinese economy in the second half of the
year is a result of the flexible interaction of policies to
increase domestic demand and counter the negative effects of the
current difficult world economic and financial situation," he
said. "That situation will continue to dominate next
year's economy." he added.
</P>
<P>
Economic experts agree that the country's measures to ignite
domestic demand have yet to make an impact on the coming year but
they are confident of the positive effects.
</P>
<P>
In addition, they said, this year's severe floodings can also
be actually interpreted as good tidings for the national economy's
speedy growth because the rebuilding of homes and resumption of
production have created enormous demand for materials and services.
</P>
<P>
Predictions by the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences indicate
that the growth rate for investment will likely remain above 15
percent, which contributes at least three to five percentage
points to the GDP growth rate.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, increased consumer demand will add about four to
four and a half percentage points, taking into account the effect
of increased investment next year. The academy pointed out that
changes in consumer demand lag behind by more than a year those
affecting investment in China.
</P>
<P>
And these calculations do not yet include the effects of the
central banks' interest rate reduction three days ago.
</P>
<P>
Economic experts believe that although it is difficult to
accurately assess the effects of the latest interest rate drop, it
is safe to assume that more ordinary people will divert their
savings into investments and consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
They play down the role of exports in propelling forward the
national economy, and declare that the country's import and export
levels will even out or end up in a slight surplus next year.
</P>
<P>
A cautious optimism on next year's national economic
performance therefore prevails within the ranks of most Chinese
economists.
</P>
<P>
They remain alert, though, to the influences of the Asian
financial crisis and possible changes in the economies of major
western industrial nations, because they can exert unpredictable
influences on China, especially as the world economy becomes more
integrated.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
