<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Party Threatens to Pull out Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A major Nigerian political
party, the All People's Party (APP), has threatened to pull out
the transition to civil rule program if foul plays in the
just-concluded local government elections were not redressed.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a party meeting in capital Abuja Tuesday, APP
Chairman Mahmud Waziri said that the election last Saturday is a
sham and that the party has lost total confidence in the
Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC) of Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
"APP must reconsider its participation in the on-going
transition program if we can no longer be accommodated in the
system," he was quoted by Wednesday's New Nigerian newspaper as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Waziri said that many APP candidates are now in hospitals
because of gunshots they received from security agents and thugs
employed by the People's Democratic Party (PDP), which emerged as
the winner of the elections.
</P>
<P>
"All known electoral guidelines were openly flouted, with
members of the APP harassed and brutalized by agents of
government masquerading as security chiefs," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to results so far released by the INEC, the PDP won
over 400 local council chairmanship seats, out of a total of 774,
the APP secured about 160 seats and another party, the Alliance
for Democracy, bagged about 95 seats.
</P>
<P>
The rest of the six provisionally registered parties won only
one or two seats each, and are almost sure to be scrapped by the
INEC according to guidelines released earlier.
</P>
<P>
The INEC is expected to address a press conference on the
election in Abuja Wednesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
