<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Economic Conference Held in Beijing (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- China has made major economic
progress throughout 1998, delegates to a special conference held
in Beijing this week were told by President Jiang Zemin in his
keynote speech.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also analyzed the current economic situation and raised
general requirements for next year's economic work.
</P>
<P>
During the three day conference, which was attended by other
top leaders including Li Peng, Zhu Rongji, Li Ruihuan, Hu Jintao,
Wei Jianxing and Li Lanqing, Premier Zhu outlined the government's
plans for continued economic growth in 1999.
</P>
<P>
The conference pointed out that China has also enhanced its
image and status worldwide because of the positive manner in which
it has dealt with the effects of the current financial turmoil in
Asia, which has badly impacted on the world's economy.
</P>
<P>
The meeting revealed that China had been praised for the fast
and efficient way it tackled the summer floods which devastated
large areas of the country.
</P>
<P>
The conference, staged from December 7-9, was a joint event
between the Central Committee of the Communist Party of China
(CPC) and the State Council.
</P>
<P>
Under the direction of the CPC Central Committee led by
President Jiang Zemin, China has maintained the fast pace of
economic growth, kept the yuan stable and continued a series of
vital reform programs. Linked to social stability and the ongoing
improvement in the standard of living, the conference emphasized
that the overall economic situation is sound.
</P>
<P>
Throughout 1998, China has made crucial yet orderly strides in
economic restructuring, in line with the laid down schedule. It
also achieved considerable progress within some admittedly
difficult sectors such as introducing necessary reforms to make
more efficient the grain circulation system, state-owned
enterprises and the financial sector.
</P>
<P>
The restructuring of the housing system and introduction of a
medical insurance system have also been initiated.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, plans to ban the army, police, other law-enforcement
departments and Party and government institutions from operating
in the business sector have moved full steam ahead. And the
institutional restructuring of the State Council has also
proceeded smoothly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
