<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Y2K Bug to Cost S. African Property Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The millennium bug
computer threat could cost South African property sector more
than 100 million Rand (16 million U.S. Dollars), the Business Day
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Gavin Douglas-Hamilton, a Y2K consultant, as
saying that the commercial and industrial property sectors may
have been caught unawares.
</P>
<P>
People tended to think of the "bug", the inability of some
computers to read the change of date to the new century, as some
thing which affected only computer systems, said the consultant.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Douglas-Hamilton said, date-dependent data was
embedded in any number of products or systems.
</P>
<P>
He said there were potential problems for building access
control systems, escalators, elevators, air-conditioning systems,
fire and security systems.
</P>
<P>
Property companies needed to take action to ensure that their
buildings were year 2000 compliant, instead of waiting for the
first working day in January 2000 to see what problems occurred,
he said.
</P>
<P>
South African Communications Minister Jay Naidoo, who is in
charge of the government's Y2K compliance program, also said
early this week that South African business was expected to spend
about 20 billion Rand (3.3 billion Dollars) on compliance,
compared with costs of 400 billion Rand (66 billion Dollars) in
Britain.
</P>
<P>
The South African government set up Y2K operations center and
national assistance service last month. A free hot-line to deal
with the millennium bug is also open to the public. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
