<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia Considers Free Primary Education </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government is
studying the possibilities of compulsory and free education of
primary school children under an investment program set to kick
off next year.
</P>
<P>
Zambian Education Minister Godfrey Miyanda said this on the
occasion at which the country office of United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) released a report on the state of children in the
world.
</P>
<P>
The Times of Zambia Wednesday quoted Miyanda as saying that
once finalized, the investment program for the country's basic
education sector would increase enrollment to 1.3 million in the
year 2002 from 980,000 at present.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that his ministry would research
into the possibility of making the first nine years of education
compulsory and define a mechanism for the government to pay for
the poor.
</P>
<P>
According to UNICEF country representative Peter McDermott,
about 130 million children at primary school age worldwide are
not attending school. And About 73 million of them at the ages
between six and 11 years are girls.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that in Zambia with a population of 9.5
million, 600,000 children are not attending school. 
</P>
</TEXT>
