<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholar Urges Correct Appraisal of U.N. Human Rights Declaration (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese human rights expert
today said that a correct knowledge and appraisal of the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights is conducive to wisely prophesying the
future trend of world human rights movement and promoting its
healthy development.
</P>
<P>
Despite its unique and noteworthy role in the world history of
human rights protection, the Declaration is by no means an
independent document, said Dong Yunhu, Deputy Secretary-General of
the China Society for Human Rights Studies.
</P>
<P>
Instead, he said, it should be regarded as component part of
the whole U.N. documents on human rights. Therefore, in order to
correctly understand and evaluate the Declaration, one should
study it as a section of the U.N. document on human rights, while
paying enough attention to the development process of human rights
theory and practice.
</P>
<P>
To link the Declaration with the U.N. Charter is necessary for
better understanding the historical document. This is because, on
the one hand, it is actually an instrument for specifying and
interpreting the human rights provisions of the U.N. Charter, and
on the other hand, it was worked out on the basis of, and
according to the principles made by the Charter, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Declaration requires that no U.N. principles should be
violated, while realizing the human rights enumerated by the
Declaration. While the U.N. Charter adopts human rights protection
to be one of the U.N. principles, it articulates that the way by
which the principle or goal is reached should be promotion of
international cooperation in accordance with the principle of
sovereign equality and no interference in other's internal
affairs, said Dong, also a professor of the Central Party School
of the Chinese Communist Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
