<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholar Urges Correct Appraisal of U.N. Human Rights Declaration (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
This means that to realize and protect the human rights
enumerated by the Declaration, nations and people should cooperate
and abide by the principles of sovereign equality and
non-interference in other's internal affairs, he said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, any approach to separate the Declaration from the
U.N. Charter, or create antagonism and interfere with other's
internal affairs by making use of the human rights listed in the
Declaration, should be regarded as violation of the basic spirit
and principle of the Declaration, Dong said.
</P>
<P>
To study the Declaration, one should also scrutinize every
major progress of the U.N. in protection of human rights in the
past 50 years. Since the Declaration was approved in 1948,
tremendous achievements have been made in maintaining and
protecting human rights by the international community, he said.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 100 countries have shaken off the yoke of colonialism,
resulting in a complete collapse of the colonial system existing
for centuries. This has enabled more nations and peoples to
maintain and safeguard their basic human rights, he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the United Nations, promoted by Third World
countries and other progressive forces in the world, worked out
and ratified a series of covenants, declarations, protocols and
resolutions relating to human rights protection, which brought
about some new principles and concepts on human rights, he said.
</P>
<P>
The important U.N. documents in this regard include the
International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights and the
Optional Protocol passed by the U.N. General Assembly in 1966,
Proclamation of Teheran passed by International Human Rights
Convention in 1968, the Declaration on the New Concept about Human
Rights passed by the U.N. General Assembly in 1977, the
Declaration of the Right to Development passed by the United
Nations in 1986 and the Vienna Declaration and Working Program
passed by the World Human Rights Convention in 1993, Dong said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scholar Urges Correct Appraisal of U.N. Human Rights Declaration (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is due to these U.N. documents and joint actions that the
content and concept about human rights have been enriched and
developed to a great extent. They are also the instruments by
which the international community may explore the methods and ways
for protection of human rights and fundamental freedoms more
effectively and substantially, he said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, their realistic importance to guiding the progress
and development of international human rights cause is
indisputable. "In conclusion, we must study the Declaration by
linking it with other U.N. human rights documents," Dong said.
</P>
<P>
We should not just rest on the interpretation of human rights
by the Declaration and pay no attention to development of concepts
in the several decades afterwards. It is even worse to
discriminate against the recently-evolved concept of human rights
or purposely separate the new elements from those traditional ones
provided by the Declaration just based on pragmatic approach, or
political or ideological prejudice, he said.
</P>
<P>
The past 50 years since the Declaration was passed has seen
fundamental changes of the international relations, which featured
emergence of the Third World countries and the emergence and
decline of the Cold War, he said.
</P>
<P>
These have enormously changed the world, while exerting
influence on the development of the global human rights
cause. When the Declaration was being passed, the United Nations
consisted merely of 56 member states. But now 185 countries have
joined, Dong said.
</P>
<P>
At present, both the connotation and extension of the human
rights content have gone far beyond that defined by the
Declaration. Now the problems facing the international human
rights cause are extremely different from those 50 years ago, he
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
