<HEADLINE> First Human Rights Declaration Called Milestone (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese human-rights scholar
said today that the first international declaration of human
rights is an important milestone and has made an indelible
contribution to human rights progress.
</P>
<P>
The Universal Declaration of Human Rights, the first
international document specially devoted to the cause and adopted
by the United Nations 50 years ago, reflected the common demand
and will of people throughout the world to eradicate fascism,
eliminate the cause of war and protect basic human rights, said
Dong Yunhu, deputy secretary-general of the China Society for
Human Rights Studies.
</P>
<P>
It expresses everyone's desire for world peace, democracy and
justice, he said.
</P>
<P>
During World War II, the world was shocked by the German,
Japanese and Italian fascists who willfully trampled on basic
human rights and brutally killed millions of human beings.
</P>
<P>
After the war, the people of the world jointly expressed their
demand that fascism be eradicated and basic human rights protected.
</P>
<P>
As soon as the United Nations was founded in 1945, it wrote
into the Charter of the United Nations the principle of "universal
respect for, and observance of human rights and fundamental
freedoms for all without distinction as to race, sex, language, or
religion," said Dong, also a professor of the Party School
of the Chinese Communist Party Central Committee.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. General Assembly ratified the Universal Declaration of
Human Rights on December 10, 1948, which is regarded as a
comprehensive and authoritative interpretation of the human rights
provisions contained in the Charter of the United Nations, he said.
</P>
<P>
The dclaration was also the direct result of the worldwide
anti-fascist war. Thus, its historic importance to human progress
is evident, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Human Rights Declaration Called Milestone (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The declaration was the first genuine human rights declaration
commonly accepted and affirmed by the international community and
not only by some people or some nations. In this document was
embedded a unique significance in the history of worldwide human
rights protection, Dong said.
</P>
<P>
As all may know, it was the Western capitalists who first
created the protection of human rights and fundamental freedoms by
means of issuing "declarations of human rights," he said.
</P>
<P>
The American Declaration of Independence and the French
Declaration of the Rights of Man and the Citizen are such
documents, which elaborated several inalienable human rights, Dong
said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, all these declarations share one thing in
common: they represented the social standards of one country and
were enunciated by the ruling class of the country during a period
dominated by egoistic Western ideology.
</P>
<P>
Thus, the so-called "human rights" declared in these documents
were not actually applicable to every country in the world, but
only to Western countries. Therefore, they by no means set out
genuine universal human rights, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Declaration was worked out in the wake of two
disastrous world wars in quick succession, and a number of
socialist countries and newly independent nations were emerging as
active voices on the international stage, resulting in fundamental
changes in international relations, he said.
</P>
<P>
As a genuine international document on human rights, the
declaration was drafted through negotiations and in accordance to
the principle of equal sovereignty by an international community
made up of nations with different social systems, cultural
traditions and levels of economic development, Dong said.
</P>
<P>
It was meant to proclaim a common standard of achievement for
all peoples and all nations. Hence, the "human rights" advocated
and elaborated in this document are in principle universal and
applicable to every country in the world, the professor
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Human Rights Declaration Called Milestone (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Declaration requires that each state undertake to respect
the rights recognized in the Declaration without distinction, he
said.
</P>
<P>
This eventually led to the abandonment of the traditional
concept of human rights based merely on Western values, and
brought the issue into a broad international domain, Dong said.
</P>
<P>
Objectively, the progress of human-rights protection encouraged
the Third World countries and colonies in their fight against
imperialism, colonialism, hegemonism and racism, and consequently
ushered in a new era in which the oppressed nations and peoples could
strive for their human rights, he said.
</P>
<P>
The basic human rights listed in the Declaration go beyond the
traditional Western concept. For example, the subject of human
rights was broadened according to the Declaration, he said.
</P>
<P>
When the issue of human rights was first put forward in the
West, both the American Declaration of Independence and the French
Declaration of the Rights of Man and the Citizen used the term
"rights of man." This defined human rights as literally solely a
male preserve and, in addition, limited the enjoyment of human
rights to wealthy, white males, both legally and in practice, Dong
said.
</P>
<P>
It is the U.N. Declaration that uses the term "human rights" to
make these rights universal, and recognizes human rights as
applying to human beings "without distinction of any kind, such as
race, color, sex, language, religion, political or other opinion,
national or social origin, property, birth or other status," as
the Declaration states in Article 2, he said.
</P>
<P>
This enables the concept of human rights to genuinely represent
the common value that everyone is born equal. In addition, the
Declaration was the first international human-rights document to
recognize people's economic, social and cultural rights, apart
from the civil and political rights as defined in traditional
Western understanding, he said.
</P>
<P>
This opened a new avenue for working people throughout the world
to strive for and maintain their natural and alienable rights, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
