<HEADLINE> Chinese Divers Not Perfect, Says Team Leader </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese divers left much to be
kdesired in the Asian Games, though they looked set to bag the
other two golds, said team leader Xue Li here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Though we have the possibility to make a sweep of all the four
diving golds at stake, our divers' performances are not
impeccable, sometimes even flawed," said Xue. "If we want to
regain our supremacy in the world, we have to work hard after
going home."
</P>
<P>
Zhu Yilin and Cai Yuyan, both from China, prevailed repectively
in the preliminaries of men's platform and women's springboard on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zhu amassed 700.140 points heading into the finals, as Cai got
a leading 188.610 points.
</P>
<P>
Divers from other countries were not to contend for gold
medalas for they were not in the same level against the two
Chinese, a judge, who asked for anonymity, said.
</P>
<P>
Guo Jingjing proved too good for her rivals in the women's
3-meter springboard event while Tian Liang outclassed his
opponents in the men's 10m platform battle on Tuesday, bringing
China the first two diving golds.
</P>
<P>
"Our divers seem to have put these two golds under safe lock,"
said Xue. "But this means nothing to us, for most of other Asian
countries lag behind the rest of the world in diving and we
Chinese divers mainly compete agaist ourselves in the games."
</P>
<P>
"But in the world major competitions such as the Olympics or
the World Championships, there will be a galaxy of high-echelon
divers. Even a small error can cost you the gold when you compete
against them," she added.
</P>
<P>
Chinese divers captured three golds in the 1996 Olympics. But
the winning form seemed to betray them in 1998 when they were
denied golds in the Olympics, the World Championships and the
Goodwill Games. 
</P>
</TEXT>
