<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Human Rights Declaration Called Milestone (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Declaration, as the first international human rights
document, sets forth the basic contents of human rights and common
goals that all the people in the world should strive together to
realize. Thus, it serves as a source from which people of later
generations can draw inspiration in human-rights theory and
practice, and it lays a foundation upon which the world cause of
human-rights protection can develop, Dong said.
</P>
<P>
It is inevitable that the Declaration is not flawless. For
example, even though the document contains economic, social and
cultural rights, it evidently attaches much more importance to
civil and political rights than it does to economic, social and
cultural rights, he said.
</P>
<P>
The entire text of the document speaks about individual human
rights, but none of the paragraphs are devoted to collective human
rights, and it seems that it did not intend to do so. Even though
it mentions the social obligations of an individual, it fails to
pay enough attention to individual obligations and
responsibilities, as it should, so as to secure a balance between
rights and obligations, he said.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the value of the Declaration is still obvious,
despite deficiencies. It was the first international document to
systematically list the human rights and fundamental freedom that
should be recognized by the international community and realized
by every nation and people, thereby building up a benchmark
according to which people of later generations may further the
study of human rights theory and practice, Dong said.
</P>
<P>
After World War II, national liberation movements were launched,
and a great number of newly independent countries emerged to voice
their views on the international political stage, he said.
</P>
<P>
Given this situation, efforts to protect international human
rights, based on the Declaration, became closely related to the
just cause of fighting against imperialism, colonialism,
hegemonism and racism, he said.
</P>
<P>
As a result, some collective human rights such as the right to
national self-determination, development and equality of
nationality and race were added. Affirmation of collective human
rights reflects an evolution from the concepts originally spelled
out in the Declaration, Dong said.
</P>
<P>
It now goes beyond the Western human-rights concept based on
individualism. This development, obviously, promotes the
international movement of human rights protection advancing in the
direction of the interests of the majority of the world's people,
he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0188 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cause of Human Rights Faces Progress and Challenges (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese human-rights scholar
said today that the international cause of human rights faces a
good opportunity to development as well as challenges.
</P>
<P>
The trend of multi-polar international relations and
international cooperation creates a good opportunity for the cause
of human rights to develop, said Dong Yunhu, deputy
secretary-general of the China Society for Human Rights Studies.
</P>
<P>
However, most developing countries are facing problems such as
poverty, food shortages and widespread malnutrition. These not
only hinder human progress and world development, but also pose
the most serious challenges to the development of the human rights
cause, he said.
</P>
<P>
The relationship between the universal and the particular in
the concept of human rights must be correctly dealt with, Dong
said.
</P>
<P>
The values, ideas and goals of human rights protection are
universal. Everyone's right to all human rights is a common human
goal, he said.
</P>
<P>
But in reality, no country may proclaim that it has completely
reached this goal. Nevertheless, the universal principle of human
rights protection is realized in different countries through
various efforts, he said.
</P>
<P>
Various countries take different approaches to human rights
protection, and have different timetables because of their
different histories, cultural traditions, sense of values,
religions, economic development, and social and political systems,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, every country should respect the universal
principles of human rights protection, while the special
approaches of different countries in realizing human rights should
also be fully respected, Dong said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cause of Human Rights Faces Progress and Challenges (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
All human rights should be regarded in a comprehensive and
balanced manner, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is necessary to have comprehensive and complete knowledge of
the U.N. human rights documents so as to give civil and political
rights equal status with economic, social and cultural rights, and
individual rights with collective rights, he added.
</P>
<P>
For historical reasons, developing countries give priority to
people's economic, social and cultural rights, the rights
closely related to their subsistence and development, he said.
</P>
<P>
This should be well understood by the international community
in order to guarantee that the world effort for human-rights
protection is non-discriminatory and non-differentiated, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is also necessary to balance rights and obligations, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Everyone has the right to demand that other people and the
state and society respect his or her human rights. At the same
time, everyone is obliged to respect the human rights of others,
as well as the interests of the state and society, he said.
</P>
<P>
"While celebrating the 50th anniversary of the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights, we should remember and reemphasize
the inseparable relationship between rights and obligations," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Third World countries' experiences of, and contributions to,
the development of human rights protection should be given full
attention, he said.
</P>
<P>
Accounting for three-fourths of the world's population, the
Third World countries' human rights demands and views deserve
great attention, and their experiences in human rights protection
according to their actual conditions should be highly esteemed, he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
