<HEADLINE> Falling Commodity Prices Drive Australian Dollar Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Tunneling commodity prices
caused the Australian dollar to churn lower Wednesday, but the
local currency closed off two-month lows recorded during the
session.
</P>
<P>
During the local session the Australian dollar reached a low of
61.00 U.S. cents, a level not recorded since October 8 this year.
</P>
<P>
After the early afternoon dip the Australian dollar recovered
some ground to finish at 61.43 U.S. cents from 61.85 late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Bankers Trust's Geoff Bowmer said the fall in commodity prices
was responsible for the tumble in the Australian dollar.
</P>
<P>
"Once you had seen the CRB (Commodity Research Bureau Index)
move you knew that the Aussie was going to be softer," Bowmer
said.
</P>
<P>
"And it was going to be vulnerable to the downside in that
environment."
</P>
<P>
Bowmer said technical selling on the break of 61.20 U.S. cents
added to the Australian dollar's woes.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar lost ground against all major currencies
offshore Tuesday night and here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar was buying 72.96 Japanese yen from 74.35
and 1.0240 German marks from 1.0386. 
</P>
</TEXT>
