<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World's First Huminid Fossil Remains Found in S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, November 9 (Xinhua) -- Researchers at South
Africa's Witwatersrand University (Wits) have found the world's
first-ever entire ape-man skull and its skeleton, the university
announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The almost complete remains of one of humanity's early
ancestors was discovered by Ron Clarke of the Wits
Paleo-Anthropology Research Group at Sterkfontein, some 40
kilometers northwest of Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
The fossil, which is believed to be 3.22 to 3.58 million years
old, is considered the most important South African
archaeological and anthropological discovery since 1924 when the
Taung skull was unearthed.
</P>
<P>
Clarke said at a news conference that the fossil was "the most
dramatic discovery ever made" because of its entirety.
</P>
<P>
Past finds of Australopithecus have been either a partial
skull or a partial skeleton, but never both of the same creature.
</P>
<P>
Clarke believed that the skeleton was well preserved because
the creature fell 15 meters down into a shaft and died there.
</P>
<P>
For the first time paleontologists will know what kind of
skull goes with what kind of limbs for one species of ape man and
how they moved around more than three million years ago.
</P>
<P>
The discovery is full of world "firsts": the skull is
complete with both its lower and upper jaws, even its teeth are
in contact - and the skull is with its skeleton.
</P>
<P>
It is also the first time that such a complete ancient tibia
with fibula (lower leg) has been found - or such a complete
ape-man foot, and radius (outer forearm).
</P>
<P>
The fossil will answer many of the questions concerning human
evolution that continue to mystify scientists, said a Wits news
release.
</P>
<P>
Owing to the fact that the skull and some bones are still
embedded in the rock, it is impossible to say anything about its
exact taxonomic status or whether it is male or female, said
Clarke.
</P>
<P>
But analysis of its foot bones indicates that it was an
upright walker but was still a tree climber.
</P>
<P>
Clarke, who has been working at Sterkfontein for the past
seven years, made the discovery by following his uncanny
"paleo-detective" instincts after his initial finding in 1994 of
four fossil foot bones.
</P>
<P>
More findings in 1997 led him to assume that there must be a
whole skeleton at Sterkfontein.
</P>
<P>
South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki and Environmental
Affairs and Tourism Minister, Pallo Jordan, were present at the
news briefing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
