<HEADLINE> China's Wang Xian Wins Women's Sport Rifle Prone Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Shooting powerhouse China took
three of the four gold medals at stake at the Asian Games here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Shaking off a luckwarm performance at the previous two days,
China claimed both the team and the individual titles in the men's
air pistol in addition to Wang Xian's gold in the women's sport
rifle prone.
</P>
<P>
The only gold that eluded China was that of the team event in
the women's sport rifle prone, which was claimed by Japan with a
very narrow margin.
</P>
<P>
"We had competed to our normal standard today," said Chinese
coach Zhang Heng. "Although we lost one rifle team title, the
pistol shooters performed superbly in the final."
</P>
<P>
Chinese marksmen Xu Dan and Tan Zongliang had a one-two finish
in the air pistol event, with Xu producing a remarkable 103.0
points in the final to bring the total score to a winning 685.0.
</P>
<P>
Tan, who scored 102.0 points in the final for a total of 683.6,
grabbed the silver while Kazakhstan's Vladimir Guchsha won the
bronze.
</P>
<P>
"It was also the victory for the whole Chinese team," said
29-year-old National Games champion Xu, who is from the
northeastern city of Changchun.
</P>
<P>
In the team event, world championship gold medalist China,
formed by Xu, Tan plus world champion Wang Yifu, produced a
record-breaking 1,742 points to improve the previous Asian Games
record by one point.
</P>
<P>
Japan won the silver with 1,723, two points ahead of bronze
medalist South Korea.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, world championships runner-up Wang Xian scored 589
points for her gold, followed by Japanese Yoko Minamoto and Noriko
Ojima at second and third places.
</P>
<P>
"I was unsatisfied with my results here," said Wang. "But I
know now I have seen my form improved."
</P>
<P>
Japan beat China to second place for the team title, where the
countries scored the same total of 1,754.
</P>
<P>
Japan was ruled the winner as the trio of Minamoto, Ojima and
Mari Onoe registered better points in the last twenty shots in
this 60-shot non-Olympic event.
</P>
<P>
China won the silver while Thailand was third at 1,745.
</P>
<P>
"We did not expect a gold medal," said Japan's Minamoto, a
31-year-old veteran making a comeback after two years of absence
from international competition.
</P>
<P>
"I was also surprised that I had won the individual silver,"
she added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
