<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Weaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Losses on Wall Street weighed
on the Australian share market Wednesday, with resource stocks
continuing to be sold down because of weaker commodity prices.
</P>
<P>
The benchmark all ordinaries index closed 21.7 points weaker at
2,750 points off a high of 2,771.7 and a low of 2,745.7 points.
</P>
<P>
The banking sector lent some support to the market, but a slip
by telecommunications companies Optus and Telstra added to the
selling pressure.
</P>
<P>
The all industrials index slipped 30.3 points to 4,926.4 while
the resources sector fell 16.4 points or 1.7 percent to 972.9
points.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday night falls in commodity prices, with both nickel and
copper falling to 12-year lows in London, saw locally exposed
stocks weaken during the day.
</P>
<P>
BHP lost 24 cents, Rio Tinto fell 25 cents, WMC was 19 cents
weaker, Comalco came off five cents while Woodside was 15.3 cents
lower.
</P>
<P>
Despite the general weakness in the overall market, the banking
sector stayed in positive territory with the index 13.3 points
firmer at 6,319.4.
</P>
<P>
GIO Australia was the top traded stock rising 13 cents on a
turnover of 18.22 million shares, after AMP announced it would
lift its bid for the company to 5.35 Australian dollars in cash or
one AMP share for every four GIO shares.
</P>
<P>
Among the bank sector stocks, National Australia Bank rose 27.1
cents and Westpac climbed 15 cents. However CBA was 26.5 cents
softer and ANZ slipped 11 cents. Among other industrials, News
Corp was down 20 cents and its preferred scrip was 35.3 cents
softer.
</P>
<P>
The gold index ended 4.1 points firmer at 1,120.1. Gold bullion
was down 1.20 at 293.40 U.S. dollars per ounce.
</P>
<P>
National turnover was 430.59 million shares worth 1.55 billion
Australian dollars (950.15 million U.S. dollars), with falls
outpacing rises 632 to 505 and with 451 stocks steady. 
</P>
