<BODY>
<HEADLINE> People's Daily Editorial on Central Economic Conference </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The People's Daily, China's
leading newspaper, published an editorial today on the Central
Conference on Economic Work which was held in Beijing from
December 7-9.
</P>
<P>
The conference summed up the country's economic work in 1998,
analysed the current international and domestic situation, and
outlined the requirements for next year's economic work.
</P>
<P>
The editorial, titled "Being Determined and Pressing Forward
Despite Difficulties to Win New Victories in Reform and
Construction," hails the conference as important for pushing
forward the current reform and opening and the country's
socialist modernization drive.
</P>
<P>
The editorial praises the CPC Central Committee for its timely
and correct decision to tackle the difficult situation caused by
the financial turmoil in Asia and the devastating summer floods
through stimulating domestic demand and utilizing macroeconomic
means to achieve steady economic growth.
</P>
<P>
It attributes the remarkable achievements China has made in
1998 to the foundation laid by the 20-year-old reform and opening
drive, the timely and correct policy of the CPC Central Committee,
and the hard efforts made by the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
Next year will be of special importance to the current reform and
opening and modernization drive and the history of the Party and
the nation, the editorial says, adding that economic work in 1999
will be of great importance as well.
</P>
<P>
In order to achieve sustained, speedy and healthy economic
development, the conference put forward some general requirements
for 1999. It called for enlarged domestic demand, stabilized and
reinforced agriculture, restructured state enterprises, increased
exports, and minimized financial risks.
</P>
<P>
The editorial urged recognition of both the favorable and
negative sides of the current international and domestical
situation, and a deeper understand of central economic policies.
</P>
<P>
It also called for relying on the masses in order to bring
their enthusiasm and creativity into full play and urged leading
officials at all levels to be concerned with the life of the
masses, especially factory layoffs in cities and people living in
disaster-stricken and poverty areas. The leaders should remain
forthright, go deep into the grassroot units, and work with the
masses, it stresses.
</P>
<P>
The Party's leadership in the area of economic work should be
strengthened and improved, the editorial said, noting that China
is carrying out its socialist modernization drive while the world
is tending toward multi-polarization and economic globalization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
