<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB to Provide 800M Dollars to Pakistan in 6 Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank
(ADB) Wednesday indicated fresh commitments of 800 million U.S.
dollars for Pakistan during the next six months ending June 1999.
</P>
<P>
Among the total commitment of 800 million dollars by ADB, 400
million dollars could be immediately made available, Director of
Programs Department (West) of ADB Van der Linden told a press
conference here.
</P>
<P>
Linden, who is here as the head of a three-member ADB
delegation, said that the 800 million dollars would be available
under three major loans including loans for power sector, trade
and export promotion and industrial development and loan for the
capital market reforms, besides certain smaller projects.
</P>
<P>
Expressing strong hope for Pakistan reaching an agreement with
the International Monetary Fund (IMF) next month, Linden said, the
fresh commitments, however, will be subjected to the approval of
the program.
</P>
<P>
He said there was no fresh commitment during the first six
months of the current fiscal year (July 1-June 30), although the
disbursement for the ongoing projects continued unfettered.
</P>
<P>
ADB Resident Director M. F.W. Zijsvelt said on the occasion
that the disbursement by November 30 had totaled 487 million
dollars, exceeding the target of 454 million dollars for the
calendar year 1998.
</P>
<P>
Besides the three major loans, Linden said, the future lending
for other small projects loans will include the Women Health
Program, the Malakand Rural Development Project, the non-formal
education for women and the irrigation projects.
</P>
<P>
The ADB is also providing 80 million dollars for Pakistan's
judicial reforms, for which the negotiations between the ADB and
the Pakistani government is continuing.
</P>
<P>
The ADB director said that the purpose of his recent visit was
to assess the ongoing program funded by the ADB and discuss the
future lendings.
</P>
<P>
"We also want to review the post-sanctions economic situation
and meet the new economic team of the government spearheaded by
Finance Minister Ishaq Dar," he said.
</P>
<P>
Stating that the current economic situation in Pakistan is
serious, Linden said, the present government initiated very
important measures to restore confidence in the country's economy.
</P>
<P>
"The bank will, in its moderate role, address the problems
arising as a result of social imbalances created by the
sanctions," he said.
</P>
<P>
The ADB director said, though currently Pakistan's major
concern is on short-term issues, the ADB would continue to focus
on the long-term development strategies like the 2010 program for
the sustainable transformation of the entire economic and social
fabric.
</P>
<P>
To a question about the bank's lending for different important
projects identified by the government, including agriculture and
industrial master plans, good governance and civil services
reforms, he said, the negotiations are in the preliminary stage.
</P>
<P>
The problem relating to restructuring of the civil service is
very difficult and needs a strong political commitment, the
project is in the pipeline but the bank needs to ensure that the
ground for such funding is there, he added.
</P>
<P>
Linden hoped that sanctions imposed against Pakistan will be
lifted soon. However, he said, it is a political decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Government Pushes for Cathay-PAL Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada said here Wednesday that his administration is trying its
best to convince Hong Kong-based Cathay Pacific Airways to buy
into the financially-troubled Philippine Airlines (PAL).
</P>
<P>
In an interview with reporters, Estrada said that he remains
hopeful that both sides could strike an agreement soon.
</P>
<P>
"Well, we're trying our best to settle an agreement," he said.
</P>
<P>
Asked whether a settlement can be hammered out soon, Estrada
said: "You know, this is a negotiation, you cannot set the time
when they will agree. Maybe they will not agree, maybe they will
agree."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Finance Secretary Edgardo Espiritu said Cathay feels
concerned about the constitutional restrictions for foreign
investors.
</P>
<P>
While Cathay wants to manage PAL's day-to-day operations, it is
wary of the constitutional provision limiting foreign investors to
own a maximum of 40 percent of any local company, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that Cathay appears amenable to honoring PAL
management's proposal to preserve the jobs of PAL employees, which
the employees approved overwhelmingly in a referendum last
September.
</P>
<P>
PAL has been incurring losses in most of the past 15 years. It
posted a loss of 8.08 billion pesos (200 million U.S. dollars) in
its fiscal year ending March 31, 1998, the biggest loss so far in
its 57-year history.
</P>
<P>
The airline temporarily shut down operations in September due
to a protracted labor conflict and huge financial losses.
</P>
<P>
But it resumed operations in early October after President
Estrada persuaded PAL's biggest labor union to accept the
management's offer of a 20 percent equity in exchange for a
10-year freeze on strikes and labor bargaining. 
</P>
</TEXT>
