<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Soeharto Questioned Over Alleged Corrupt Practices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian former president
Soeharto was asked 43 questions on his alleged corrupt, collusive
and nepotistic practices during his rule, spokesman of the
Attorney General's Office Barman Jahir told reporters here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Of the 43 questions, 16 were about the foundations he once
led, 18 about the national car (project), and nine about other
issues that have damaged the economy," Barman said after four
hours of questioning of the former president at Jakarta's Higher
Prosecutor's Office in South Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
The investigating team is led by Junior Attorney General for
Special Crimes Anton Suyatna.
</P>
<P>
Barman said that during the questioning, which started at 07:20
a.m. local time and ended at 11:30 a.m., Soeharto explained how
the foundations were set up, their aims, their financial
mechanisms, and their deposits.
</P>
<P>
On November 25, Soeharto handed over to the government the
funds from seven charity foundations he chaired, a total of about
4 trillion rupiah (530 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Barman said Soeharto also told about the chronology of the
issuance of Presidential Decree No. 42/1996 on the Timor national
car project.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, a company controlled by Soeharto's youngest
son Hutomo "Tommy" Mandala Putra was given huge tax exemptions and
a multi-million-U.S.-dollar soft loan from a consortium of 16
banks, including state banks, to produce the Timor national car.
The project had caused the country losses of 1.55 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Barman told reporters that the former president has funds
deposited at the state Bank Bumi Daya, Bank Negara Indonesia and
Bank Tabungan Negara as well as in some private banks, including
Bank Central Asia and Bank Muamalat.
</P>
<P>
"All of Soeharto's testimonies will be evaluated. The attorney
general will decide whether there are irregularities in them or
not," Barman said.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from the questioning, Soeharto told reporters that he
has given all his explanations to the attorney general.
</P>
<P>
"As a citizen who has to abide by the law, I would be ready to
come every time I am needed by the prosecutor's office," he said
in a soft voice.
</P>
<P>
He said he considers Indonesia as a country based on the law
where everybody stands equal before the law.
</P>
<P>
"I have answered all questions and this is still an
investigating process," he added.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was forced to step down on May 21 amid the country's
worst political and economic crisis in decades. He is accused of
corruption and abuse of power during his 32 years in power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
