<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Senate Approves Motion Calling for IMF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Dewan Negara
(Senate) Wednesday passed a motion calling on IMF Managing
Director Michel Camdessus to resign for failing to take suitable
measures to tackle Asia's economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The house approved the motion after a two-day debate, with all
the senators who spoke supporting it, the Malaysian national news
agency Bernama reported.
</P>
<P>
The IMF (International Monetary Fund)'s failure to help
overcome the economic crisis in Asian countries was prompted by
its policy of giving priority to Western banking institutions, a
senator said during the debate Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Senator Mohd Zuki Kamaluddin said this was clear from the
conditions imposed by the IMF on these countries requiring them to
use loans approved by the agency to first settle foreign bank
debts.
</P>
<P>
Due to the IMF's refusal to compromise on such loan conditions,
borrowing nations like Thailand, Indonesia and South Korea found
it hard to revive their economies, he said.
</P>
<P>
The senator called for IMF to be restructured and for the
agency to ensure that measures taken were in line with the global
economic development.
</P>
<P>
Senator Tee Thiong Hock said Camdessus as the managing director
of a large financial body should have played an important role in
restoring the economies of affected countries.
</P>
<P>
"According to the principles of management, if a manager failed
to carry out his duties he should be fired," Tee said.
</P>
<P>
Senator Abdul Majid Baba said Malaysia had proven that it did
not require IMF's assistance to recover from the economic
slowdown.
</P>
<P>
Senator Christina Tibok Vanhouten said Malaysians should be
proud of the government's decision not to borrow from the agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
