<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets South African Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier Qian
Qichen met with Mathole Motshekga, premier of South Africa's
Gauteng Province, and his party here today.
</P>
<P>
Motshekga is here to sign an agreement on the establishment of
friendly ties between his province and Beijing municipality.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, the two sides will work in
cooperation in the fields of economy, science, trade, culture and
other activities.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, Qian said that the agreement signed in
Beijing three day ago will serve to promote cooperation in a
variety of areas between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
Motshekga told Qian that the signing is a concrete achievement
in the growth of bilateral relations and that China is the number
one friend of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
During Motshekga's stay here, he met with local officials and
visited several communities. He said he believes that exchanges
between the youths and women of the two countries play a very
important role in promoting communication on a people-to-people
basis.
</P>
<P>
He also expressed the hope that both South Africa and China
will continue their efforts in related areas.
</P>
<P>
Qian called this a good idea, saying that although China and
South Africa forged diplomatic ties no more than one year ago, the
people of the two countries enjoy a long-standing friendship.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government will continue to promote the traditional
friendship between the two peoples," he added.
</P>
<P>
South African ambassador to China, Chris Dlamini, who attended
today's meeting, told Xinhua that he hopes that exchanges between
the two peoples and local governments will be further
increased. The coming year will be even better than this year for
the growth of Sino-South African relations, he added.  
</P>
