<HEADLINE> Sending Fewer Greeting Cards to Protect Trees, Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Four national non-governmental
organizations have asked everyone to send fewer New Year's cards
this year, beginning with Christmas, as a way to help protect the
environment.
</P>
<P>
In a written proposal to all Chinese citizens, the China
Environmental Protection Fund, the Communist Youth League of
China, the All-China Federation of Trade Unions, and the All-China
Women's Federation, said that China has serious ecological
problems and everyone should try their best to preserve natural
resources.
</P>
<P>
Fully one-third of China is suffering from soil erosion and
more than a quarter of the country's area has desertification
problems which are swallowing the equivalent of a county each
year, and a Beijing city every eight years.
</P>
<P>
"The serious floods in China last summer were warnings from
nature," the proposal said.
</P>
<P>
China consumes huge volumes of greeting cards every year,
especially around Christmas and New Year. A survey revealed that
Beijingers alone sent over 30 million greetings cards during 1997,
using up over 10,000 ten-year-old trees.
</P>
<P>
The production of these cards also produced more than 9,000
tons of waste water and consumed more than 300,000 kwh of
electricity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
