<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lack of Firemen Leads to Fire Tragedy in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The reason behind the recent
tragedy of fire that killed 28 at an orphanage in Manila is the
lack of personnel in the Bureau of Fire Protection, a senior
Philippine official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ronaldo Puno, Undersecretary of Interior and Local Governments,
admitted that the country as a whole faces a problem like this,
disclosing that the ratio is one fireman for every 2,000
residents.
</P>
<P>
Puno admitted the Bureau of Fire Protection also has a problem
of availability of supplies and equipment. At present, there are
only 227 fire trucks nationwide, but only 94 are functioning,
while 18 are used in special cases.
</P>
<P>
A Manila orphanage was razed by fire last Thursday in which 23
infants and five adults were killed.
</P>
<P>
Puno added that his department is about to transfer the
leadership of the bureau's sub-stations to the local government
units.
</P>
<P>
This would improve the bureau's services as the local
government units are expected to allot a budget for the stations'
maintenance and the personnel's sufficient salary. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
