<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Economic Crises Affect Electronic Equipment Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Asian economic crises
have created downward pressures throughout the "electronic food
chain" causing the industry to consolidate further, an expert said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Asian market conditions have caused decreased global
demand, trade imbalances and severe currency fluctuations in the
otherwise very robust electronics industry, which the world's
systems and infrastructure were totally dependent on, Ron Daniels,
publisher and editor-in-chief of Circuits Assembly and Circuits
Assembly Asia, said Wednesday at the PCB (printed circuit board)
Asia '98 Conference in the northern state of Pulau Pinang.
</P>
<P>
"The enormous consumer pressure has since resulted in the
increasing functionality, complexity, portability and
miniaturization of consumer products, and the performance of such
products being faster, denser and cheaper," he was quoted by the
Malaysian national news agency Bernama as saying.
</P>
<P>
This trend is expected to continue to result in new markets as
technology increases electronic content of capital goods, he said.
</P>
<P>
He however said the world electronic equipment markets would be
far from being saturated due to the demand for new products by the
mobile consumer, leading to a convergence of personal computers,
communication devices, TVs and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
He said it is also possible that this factor is causing
technology migration from technologically advanced labor
countries to cheaper and labor intensive nations.
</P>
<P>
Daniels said research by Electronic Trends Publications from
San Jose, California, showed that the worldwide electronics market
had been projected to grow from estimated 1.020 trillion U.S.
dollars in 1997 to 1.382 trillion U.S. dollars by 2001. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0229 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Primakov: Yeltsin Capable of Serving Out Term </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov has said here that President Boris Yeltsin "can perfectly
perform" his duties and will "work until the end of his term" in
2000.
</P>
<P>
In an interview published by the newspaper Nezavisimaya Gazeta
on Wednesday, Primakov reaffirmed that he does not have
presidential ambitions and will try to be as remote as possible
from the election campaign.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Wednesday, Yeltsin moved out of the Central Clinical
Hospital where he was being treated for pneumonia and arrived at
his Rus country residence, some 100 kilometers outside of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, 67, was hospitalized on November 22 with a temperature
of 38.9 degrees in Celsius and diagnosed to be suffering pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
Poor health has forced Yeltsin to cancel several foreign trips
this year and sparked calls for his resignation and doubts over
his ability to complete his term of office.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said he intended to continue energetic contacts with
all factions in the State Duma, or lower house of parliament,
because "the political impartiality of the government is crucial
to pursuing a more effective policy." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
