<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolian Parliament Approves Narantsatsralt's Nomination </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Great Hural of Mongolia,
or parliament, on Wednesday approved the nomination of Janlaviin
Narantsatsralt as the country's prime minister.
</P>
<P>
With 36 votes for and 21 against, the parliament passed the
nomination, which was submitted by President Nachagyn Bagabandy
after he accepted it earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
The Great Hural's approval has ended a five-month political
deadlock.
</P>
<P>
Narantsatsralt, 41, was nominated by the ruling union -- the
Mongolian National Democratic Party (MNDP) and the Social
Democratic Party -- in a letter to the president on Wednesday, a
presidential spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
As a member of the MNDP, Narantsatsralt graduated from a Moscow
university in 1981 and became the mayor of Ulan Bator in November
1996.
</P>
<P>
The government led by Tsakhya Elbegdorj was dismissed on July
24. It was blamed for worsening the country's banking crisis by
deciding to merge the state-owned Renovation Bank with the private
Golomt Bank.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the president and the parliament had turned down
several nominations made by the ruling union.
</P>
<P>
Under Mongolia's law, the parliament should appoint a new prime
minister within 30 days of the government's dismissal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
