<HEADLINE> Mongolian President Accepts PM Nominee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia President Nachagyn
Bagabandy on Wednesday accepted the nomination of Janlaviin
Narantsatsralt as the country's prime minister.
</P>
<P>
A presidential spokesman said that the ruling union -- the
Mongolian National Democratic Party (MNDP) and the Social
Democratic Party -- nominated the 41-year-old Narantsatsralt, a
member of the MNDP, in a letter to the president on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The president has agreed to the nomination and submitted it to
the Great Hural (parliament) for approval, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Narantsatsralt, who graduated from a Moscow university in 1981,
became the mayor of Ulan Bator in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
The government of Tsakhya Elbegdorj was dismissed on July 24,
being blamed for worsening the country's banking crisis by
deciding to merge the state-owned Renovation Bank with the private
Golomt Bank.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, the president and the parliament had turned down
several nominations made by the ruling union.
</P>
<P>
Under Mongolia's law, the parliament should appoint a new prime
minister within 30 days of the government's dismissal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
