<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Reaffirms Commitment to Deregulating </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
reaffirmed its commitment to deregulating the telecommunications
sector.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the fifth anniversary of the Nigerian
Communications Commission Monday in capital Abuja, Nigeria's
number two leader, Mike Akhigbe said the government will continue
with the deregulation of the sector and the privatization of the
Nigeria Telecommunications Corporation (NITEL), according to
media repots Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Akhigbe, who is Chief of General Staff of the Nigerian armed
forces, said the government will give due consideration to the
request of giving "pioneer status" to the industry so that
operators would be able to enjoy tax relief and import duty
reduction.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that the preparations for the appointment of a
second national carrier has reached the advanced stage, adding
that this is the most effective strategy to achieve sustainable
telecommunications development.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to deregulating the sector, the Nigerian
government has in the last few years granted licenses to about
161 private firms to provide various telecommunications services.
</P>
<P>
Nevertheless, the price of a telephone line in Nigeria is
still one of the highest in the world.
</P>
<P>
A report by the International Telecommunications Union puts
the cost of acquiring a phone line in Nigeria now at 1,300 U.S.
Dollars, which is more than twice the average costs in developed
countries.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria now boasts a telephone line for every 150 citizens.
The government plans to boost the level to a line for every 50
persons by the year 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
