<HEADLINE> WFP Resumes Food Aid to Sudan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. World Food Program
(WFP) said Wednesday it has resumed food aid to tens of thousands
of hungry Sudanese in the Western Upper Nile province since
four-month suspension due to the war.
</P>
<P>
Immediately following a lull in fighting and a guarantee by
the warring factions of security for aid workers, WFP
successfully airdropped 375 tons of food to the area Tuesday,
said the WFP in a news release issued by its regional office here.
</P>
<P>
"The food's arrived just in time," said David Fletcher, the Acting
WFP Representative, "Over the past months thousands of people
have fled without food or belongings. Their own villages have
been burned down and their grain stores looted."
</P>
<P>
WFP and other relief agencies have not had access to people in
the towns of Leer and Mankien in the province since the middle of
July when insecurity there was further aggravated in the continued
fighting between militia factions.
</P>
<P>
Leer, once a hub for food and health services, is now a ghost
town, said the WFP field staff, adding that militia factions have
raided Leer three times since June, looting and burning homes and
destroying schools.
</P>
<P>
WFP aid workers in Leer estimated a total of 24,000 heads of
cattle have been stolen by the fighting forces. Many families
lost their crops and seeds in the raids and have had
little success in producing a harvest for next year.
</P>
<P>
The current ceasefire between the Sudanese government and the
rebel Sudanese People's Liberation Army (SPLA) which covers only
the southern Bahr el Ghazal Province is due to expire on January
15, 1999.
</P>
<P>
"It is extremely difficult and dangerous for aid organizations
to work in areas not governed by the current ceasefire," said
Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that this break in fighting marks the beginning of
continued access to Western Upper Nile," he added.
</P>
<P>
The civil war in Sudan erupted in 1983 when the SPLA restarted
fighting against the Moslem-led Khartoum for a secular state and
more autonomy in the animist and Christian-dominated south.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
