<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus' Economy on Track for Steady Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus' economy, forecast to
grow by 4.7 percent in 1998, remained on course in the first nine
months of the year due to an expansion in tourism and a revival in
domestic demand, the Cyprus Mail newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Activity in the vital construction sector also continued to
pick up in the January-August period, a report by Cypriot Finance
Ministry's Department of Statistics and Research showed.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing remained at last year's levels, while agriculture
showed an improvement after last year's sharp decline, it added.
</P>
<P>
Citing a provisional estimate by the Cyprus Tourism
Organization (CTO), the report said that tourist earnings in the
first six months of 1998 totaled 324.6 million Cyprus pound (about
649.2 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Tourism, netting about 1 billion Cyprus' pound (about 2 billion
dollars) a year, accounts for about 20 percent of the GDP and is
the largest single employer in the island.
</P>
<P>
Inflation fell to 2.5 percent in the first nine months of the
year, one percentage point lower than the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Overall unemployment dropped in the January-August period while
the number of construction-related workers out of job increased,
with 1,556 jobless registered in the sector by the end of August
compared to 1,255 at the same time last year.
</P>
<P>
Manufacturing remained stuck at last year's levels during the
first eight months of the year due to loss of competitiveness as
productivity promotion lags behind real wage increases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
