<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Building Industry Faces Slump: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, December 9 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's building
industry could face a worse year in 1999 than it experienced this
year, said Reg Hurry, Chairman of the property investment
company--Kirchmann Hurry.
</P>
<P>
The outlook is "grim' as the industry has been hit by high
interest rates, the Business Day newspaper Wednesday quoted
Reg Hurry as saying.
</P>
<P>
According statistics released by the department concerned,
about 20,000 jobs have already been lost this year, and a further
25,000 are expected to be lost next year, along with about 400
company liquidations.
</P>
<P>
About 225 projects, amounting to about 1.6 billion Rand (250
million U.S. Dollars), planned for 1998/99 have been put on hold,
and residential projects worth just less than one billion Rand
(160 million Dollars) were postponed, meaning about 55 percent of
total project value has been held back.
</P>
<P>
Investment in non-residential buildings dropped five percent
in real terms to 5.5 billion Rand (nearly one billion Dollars)
during the first two quarters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, residential investment dropped two percent to five
billion Rand (830 million Dollars). The declining trend is
expected to continue for the next six to eight quarters, the
industry sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
