<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia Records Higher Trade Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia recorded a higher
trade surplus in October this year, the 12th consecutive month
since November 1997 when the country managed to record a trade
surplus.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus in October this year amounted to 6.6 billion
ringgit (about 1.736 billion U.S. dollars), up by 0.4 billion
ringgit (about 105.263 million U.S. dollars) compared with the
surplus in September 1998, according to the Statistics Department
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The surplus was in contrast to a deficit of 0.2 billion ringgit
(about 52.631 million U.S. dollars) in the same month last year,
the department said in a statement when releasing the "Malaysian
External Trade statistics" for January-October 1998.
</P>
<P>
The department said the higher trade surplus in October was due
to the effects of an 18.5 percent increase in exports to 25.534
billion ringgit (about 6.719 billion U.S. dollars) against a 12.8
percent decline in imports to 18.912 billion ringgit (about 4.976
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
For the January-October period this year, Malaysia posted a
surplus of 44.5 billion ringgit (about 11.71 billion U.S. dollars)
in contrast to a deficit of 1.7 billion ringgit (about 447.368
million U.S. dollars) in the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
For the January-October period this year, exports grew by a
faster rate of 34.3 percent to 236.9 billion ringgit (about
62.342 billion U.S. dollars) compared with imports which grew 8.0
percent to 192.4 billion ringgit (about 50.631 billion U.S.
dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
