<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Swimming Tickets Price Costly, Thais Complain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The prices of the Asian Games
swimming tickets are too high, some local lookers-on complained
here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The price of a swimming ticket for the morning competition is
200 bahts, and 300 for the afternoon. Children pay 70 bahts for
each ticket, regardless of morning or afternoon.
</P>
<P>
"The price is too high, even before the Asian financial
crisis," said 35-year-old Ma Wen-Cai. "We can hardly afford it. I
think 100 baht per ticket is acceptable."
</P>
<P>
He spent 810 bahts buying five tickets for his wife, himself
and their three daughters.
</P>
<P>
"This is the first time for my family to come to watch the
competitions," said Ma, who just came back from a travel to
Beijing with his family. "Whether we will come to see the matches
again, it depends on if they will slash the price."
</P>
<P>
But some zealous spectators showed no dithers before the high
price tag.
</P>
<P>
"Really it is too costly, but I still will come to see the
matches," said Krerchai Genpanit, a university student. "For this
may be the only time for me in my life to see a big games."
</P>
<P>
Ironically, the swimming pool at the Thammasat University
witnessed sell-out crowds every evening since the swimming
competition started on Monday. The organisers even had to ask the
parents to put their children on their laps to prevent crushes.
</P>
<P>
The notorious Asian financial crisis left thousands of Thais
jobless after it breaking out on July 2nd, last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
