<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Leaves Hospital for Country Residence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
Wednesday morning moved out of the Central Clinical Hospital where
he was being treated for pneumonia and arrived at his country
residence, some 100 kilometers outside of Moscow.
</P>
<P>
Presidential spokesman Dmitry Yakushkin quoted doctors as
saying that the hospital stage of Yeltsin's pneumonia treatment
was over.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin, 67, was hospitalized on November 22 with a
temperature of 38.9 degrees and diagnosed to be suffering
pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
He returned briefly to the Kremlin on Monday, firing Valentin
Yumashev, head of the presidential administration, and named
Nikolai Bordyuzha, secretary of the Russian Security Council, to
replace him.
</P>
<P>
Three of Yumashev's deputies were also dismissed during
Yeltsin's three-hour blitz to the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
Yakushkin said Yeltsin was unhappy with the way the
presidential administration had been handling the fight against
extremism, separatism and corruption, especially during his
two-week absence at a time of deep economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Everything that has been going on recently undermines the
trust in presidential authority and authority in general, and
that is inadmissible," Yakushkin quoted Yeltsin as saying on
Monday. "In the present conditions, power should be concentrated
in one hand."
</P>
<P>
Yakushkin said doctors had advised Yeltsin "to take a
convalescence period" which could be organized at his residence
"with regular check-ups at the hospital."
</P>
<P>
"Doctors are generally satisfied with the president's
condition," Interfax quoted Yakushkin as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
