<HEADLINE> Dos Santos Re-elected As Angolan Ruling Party </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Angolan President Jose Eduardo
dos Santos has been re-elected as the Chairman of the ruling
People's Liberation Movement of Angola (MPLA).
</P>
<P>
At the on-going 4th National Assembly of the MPLA Tuesday
night, 56-year-old Dos Santos, as the sole candidate, was
re-elected chairman of the ruling MPLA.
</P>
<P>
In September 1979, he succeeded Antonio Agostinho Neto as the
MPLA chairman, president of the republic and the chief of the
armed forces. In December 1985 and December 1990, Dos Santos was
elected twice as the party chief.
</P>
<P>
Also at the MPLA national assembly Tuesday night, 97 members
were elected into the new central committee, 90 of them from the
candidates selected by MPLA's provincial organs while seven
others chosen from the local governments.
</P>
<P>
Now the number of the central committee members has increased
to 251 from the previous 179.
</P>
<P>
At the later meetings, 154 central committee members will be
gradually elected.
</P>
<P>
The on-going assembly began last Saturday and is scheduled to
close this Thursday at the 42 anniversary of the founding
of the MPLA.
</P>
<P>
At the national assembly, the current tense situation
and the national reform program will be discussed and some
important decisions will be made.
</P>
<P>
The MPLA was founded on December 10, 1956. It was the main
force in the military struggle for the Angolan independence from
the Portuguese colonialists.
</P>
<P>
The party has been ruling since Angola won its independence in
1975. Now, it has nearly two million members under its banner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
