<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Mineral Resources Exports Rise Slightly: Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Australia's minerals and
energy sector continued to withstand the Asian crisis in the three
months to September, by increasing about one percent, despite weak
demand caused by slower world economic growth.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Bureau of Agricultural and Resource Economics
(ABARE) said Wednesday the country's mineral and energy exports
for the third quarter of this year increased by one percent over
the previous quarter, worth 10.84 billion Australian dollars (6.82
billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
ABARE, the Australian government's chief commodities
forecaster, said export earnings in the minerals and energy sector
rose by 62 million U.S. dollars in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
ABARE Director Brian Fisher said the figures were strong given
the current trading conditions.
</P>
<P>
"This strong performance reflected mixed results for minerals
and energy commodities in difficult trading conditions, with
strong increases in earnings in some commodities offsetting
significant falls in other commodities," he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
But he did not provide figures on the volume of export for
specific markets, which is the job of the Australian Bureau of
Statistics.
</P>
<P>
Asia has been the major market for Australian minerals and
energy. Japan and South Korea, Australia's two largest export
markets, have recorded negative economic growth so far this year.
</P>
<P>
Experts say the devaluation of the Australian currency against
the U.S. dollar means that prices by Australian exporters will be
mostly higher as most exports to Asia are valued in U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The biggest rise in export earnings came for crude oil, up 17
percent to 598 million Australian dollars (360 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Export earnings also rose for iron ore, aluminum, liquefied
natural gas, refined gold, zinc, and gems.
</P>
<P>
"In a majority of cases both export volumes and unit returns
increased," ABARE said.
</P>
<P>
But export earnings fell for iron and steel, nickel, copper,
uranium oxide, petroleum refinery products and lead.
</P>
<P>
"Lower export volumes and unit returns contributed to most of
the falls," it said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
