<HEADLINE> Nigerian Youths Shut Down Shell's Oil Terminal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Protesting youths from the
Ogulagha Community in Nigeria's Delta State have shut down
Shell's Forcados oil export terminal over dispute with Mobil
Producing Nigeria Unlimited.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Nigeria, which exports about two million barrels
of crude oil a day, is losing 400,000 barrels per day of oil
exports from the shut terminal, the Daily Times newspaper
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria's Chief of Naval Staff, Rear Admiral Jibrila Ayinla,
Tuesday announced the plans of the Nigerian navy to establish a
special security force to protect all oil installations in the
country.
</P>
<P>
He said that it became necessary to check the threat to
security by restive youths in the oil producing communities when
he met with the Rivers State Administrator Group Captain Sam
Ewang in Port Harcourt.
</P>
<P>
Shell officials said Tuesday that its workers had been
directed to evacuate the terminal invaded by the protesting
youths Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Delta State Administrator Walter Feghabor implored the
traditional rulers in the community to prevail on the youths to
vacate the terminal immediately, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Olgan Hard, head of Public Affairs Unit of Shell, was quoted
as saying that the community had been negotiating with Mobil over
compensation for its oil spill last year.
</P>
<P>
Mobil was believed to have promised to pay the community 60
million Naira (about 750,000 Dollars) as compensation, but the
community rejected it on the ground that it was inadequate.
</P>
</TEXT>
