<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0264 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Asia Faces Challenge in Educating Children: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, December 9 (Xinhua) -- South Asia and the
Sub-Saharan Africa are the regions facing the greatest challenges
in enrolling all their children in primary school by the year
2000, the United Nations Children's Fund (UNICEF) said in a
report.
</P>
<P>
Net primary enrollment was 68 percent and 57 percent around
1995 respectively in South Asia and Sub-Saharan Africa, compared
with 96 percent for East Asia and Pacific and 92 percent for Latin
America and Caribbean, the U.N. agency said in the State of the
World's Children 1999 available here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The annual report, which focuses on education this year, noted
that though primary enrollment in South Asia has climbed from
under 60 percent in 1970 to nearly 70 percent, over 50 million
children of primary school age are not in school.
</P>
<P>
"About 40 percent of children entering primary school drop out
before reaching grade five, the highest regional rate," the report
noted.
</P>
<P>
It observed that nearly half the population in South Asia lives
in severe poverty, earning less than one U.S. dollar a day. "Child
labor is a persistent problem, a cause and consequence of low
enrollment and high drop-out rates," it said.
</P>
<P>
An additional annual expenditure of 1.6 billion dollars is
needed in South Asia for the next decade to educate all children,
it said.
</P>
<P>
On the constraints facing the region, the report said that
pupil-teacher ratios are high in some countries (greater than 60
to 1 in India), particularly in the early grades.
</P>
<P>
Besides, teacher education and training need upgrading, and
rural schools are often remote and poor in quality, it said.
</P>
<P>
"Nearly two thirds of women in the region are illiterate,
compared with about one third of men," the report said. "The gap
between girls' and boys' primary enrollment rates is over 10
percentage points."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
