<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, December 9 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton's defenders
forcefully pleaded his case before the House of Representatives
Judiciary Committee on Tuesday, saying that the president's
conduct was "misleading, even maddening" but did not warrant
removing him from office.
</P>
<P>
"As surely as we know that what he did was sinful, we also know
it is not impeachable," White House lawyer Gregory Craig told a
committee bristling with skeptical Republicans. Other witnesses,
including former lawmakers who sat in judgment of former President
Richard Nixon a quarter-century ago, argued that Clinton's conduct
in the Monica Lewinsky affair was no Watergate, and thus not
worthy of impeachment. (US-Clinton-Hearings)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesian former president Soeharto began to be
questioned at Jakarta's Higher Prosecutors Office on Wednesday
morning over alleged corruption, collusion and nepotistic
practices during his 32 years in power.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian President B.J. Habibie on Thursday ordered Attorney
General Andi M. Ghalib to speed up the investigation into
Soeharto's alleged ill-gotten wealth. According to a summons send
by Ghalib to Soeharto on December 4, the questioning by the
Attorney General's Office will focus on the funds held by several
foundations that Soeharto chaired and on the tax exemptions
granted to his son's company under the Timor national car program.
(Indonesia-Soeharto)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- Kosovo Albanian negotiators have rejected the
latest U.S. draft accord for the Serbian province, Yugoslav
newspapers reported.
</P>
<P>
The Munja newspaper on Tuesday quoted Kosovo Albanian chief
negotiator Fehmi Agani as saying, "It cannot serve as the basis
for negotiations." Agani said on Monday in Pristina that Kosovo
Albanians would submit their own proposals to resolve the Kosovo
crisis. Another newspaper Vecernje Novosti reported Adem Demaci,
the political representative of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army,
was very angry with the U.S. plan. He told reporters in Pristina
on Tuesday that he asked the U.S. government to dismiss Hill as
U.S. special envoy. (Yugoslavia-Kosovo) 
</P>
</TEXT>
