<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Way to Forecast Hurricanes: Scientist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese scientist say that
calamities such as hurricane Mitch can be forecast.
</P>
<P>
Professor Ren Zhenqiu of the China Academy of Meteorological
Sciences said, "It was the huge rainstorm brought by Mitch
that caused the great disaster in Central America. Such disastrous
weather can be forecast through comprehensive research into the
atmosphere, lithosphere and the the Earth's weather system."
</P>
<P>
The meteorologist found, after researching over 100 cases of
typhoons and rainstorms, that tide-generating force can bring
sudden changes to the speed and route of tropical cyclones and
aggravate rainstorms.
</P>
<P>
Ren also found that the influence of tide-generating force on
weather changes is strictly determined by the distribution of the
force when the earth, another celestial body, and the moon or the
sun are aligned.
</P>
<P>
"The huge rainstorm in Central America on October 30 was
triggered by two tide-generating forces with ready atmospheric
conditions," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hurricane Mitch this year brought the most serious natural
disaster ever to Central America, leaving more than 10,000 people
dead and over 4.5 million residents afflicted. The economic losses
in the region are expected to exceed six billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Ren said that research on tide-generating force has
significance for forecasting disastrous rainstorms. "We
successfully forecast two huge rainstorms brought by a typhoon in
1996 in north China's Hebei Province and south China's Hainan
Province. And the forecast of the big storms this summer in the
Yangtze River Valley was also quite successful."
</P>
<P>
Zhang Xiangong, also a meteorologist with the academy, said
that Ren's latest research is on the frontier of science, and
provides new methods for forecasting extraordinary weather.
</P>
</TEXT>
