<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania Denies Agreement to New War Front </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
against Congo (K)
</P>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM#,December 9 (Xinhua) - Tanzania denied Wednesday the

reports which claimed that it has agreed to open a new war front on

Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
<P>
The Minister for Defense and National Service Edgar Maokola

Majogo said in a news release that Tanzania has been avoiding being

involved in the war in DRC ever since its breakout in early August.
</P>
<P>
"Our intelligence and security reports don't warn us of any such

threats on our fronts... the story looks like a fairy-tale," Majogo

said.
</P>
<P>
The Defence Minister said that Tanzania has been striving to make

sure that all the forces in the mineral rich central African country

sign a cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
Majogo made these remarks in reaction to reports by a newly

established wire news service, the Great Lakes Press, which claimed

that a new battle front will be opened in Tanzania by the Tutsi

dominated Burundian army in the pretext of pursuit for Hutu rebels.
</P>
<P>
"The Burundian army would later be backed by a coalition of Rwanda

and Uganda army," the news agency reported from Nairobi, Kenya.
</P>
<P>
It said that the underlying army of opening new front is to divert

the military muscle of President Kabila.
</P>
<P>
"Such reports are aimed at disturbing the neutral position of

Tanzania," Majogo said. "As far as Tanzania is concerned, it has no

hostility with any of its' neighboring countries."
</P>
<P>
Trying to be neutral in the DRC conflict, Tanzania recalled its

military advisors from DRC almost immediately after the conflict broke

out while other neighboring countries rushed their troops to either

side of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
The war has so far already drawn in Angola, Namibia, Chad, Libya,

Sudan and Zimbabwe on Kabila's side while the Tutsi-led rebels are

backed by Rwanda and Uganda. 
</P>
</TEXT>
