<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibet Talks Its Way Into Modern World </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Modern new words are transforming
the language in China's Tibet Autonomous Region reflecting the
huge changes that have taken place there.
</P>
<P>
Previously seldom heard expressions and words such as
'personal computer' 'taxi', 'boss' and 'hi-fi set' are now in
everyday use.
</P>
<P>
Yi Xi, a sociologist specializing in ethnic affairs with the
Tibet Academy of Social Sciences, believes that fast economic
development and closer contact with other ethnic peoples from all
over China are two of the main reasons.
</P>
<P>
He explained: "Since China introduced reform and opening
policies in 1978, and with increasing numbers of commercial
enterprises moving into the area, a lot of young Tibetans are now
able to study in higher educational institutions throughout China."
</P>
<P>
As a result, Yi noted, most of the newly-introduced expressions
are mainly in the fields of science, technology and service trades.
</P>
<P>
"The now common use of words such
as 'refrigerator','biology', 'cassette tape' and 'aerial' are
evidence of the swift pace of scientific and economic development
while there are also flourishing cultural activities." he added.
</P>
<P>
New words were first introduced into Tibet over 1,300 years ago
during the Tang Dynasty when the Han princess Wencheng married a
Tibetan prince.
</P>
<P>
Today, a group of new words such
as 'manager', 'salesman', 'lawyer', and 'insurance company' have
made the daily conversational style of Tibetans much more up to
date.
</P>
<P>
Although they pronounce most of the words like the Han people
it is also quite common to hear such words in their own particular
dialect. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0279 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire Damages Historical Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Components of China's
oldest stone arch bridge, which were collected in a display hall
in north China's Hebei Province, were partly damaged when the hall
was recently destroyed by fire.
</P>
<P>
The display hall was located beside the Zhaozhou Bridge over
the Xiaohe River in Zhaoxian County, north China's Hebei
Province. The bridge was built more than 1,400 years ago and is
known as the oldest open-spandrel arch bridge in the world.
</P>
<P>
The fire started at 9:30 pm on November 27 and spread quickly
because the exhibition rooms were made of bricks and wood. Soon after,
the building collapsed.
</P>
<P>
According to the curator of the display hall, stone bridge
components, collected after several renovations of the bridge
itself, or salvaged from the Xiaohe River, were damaged, along
with a group of other cultural relics on display.
</P>
<P>
Local firemen spent nearly three hours putting the fire out.
The cause of the blaze was later discovered to be a short circuit
in the building's wiring.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modern Experience of One Member of the Gelao Ethnic Group (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANNING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Editor's Note: This is the
tenth in a series of stories featuring the fast-changing life and
culture of the Zhuang, Yi, Miao, Yao and seven other main ethnic
groups in south China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, which
will mark its 40th founding anniversary on December 11.
</P>
<P>
Fifty-eight-year-old Wei Shaoting, a member of the Gelao ethnic
group, says, "Our ancestors were citizens of the Yelang Kingdom."
</P>
<P>
According to Wei, the Yelang Kingdom was one of the strongest
states in southwest China in ancient times. Later, the kingdom was
split and divided into three tribes. Several hundred of year ago,
some of these tribe members came to present-day Guangxi, fleeing
some calamity, it is believed.
</P>
<P>
This is generally in line with the views of some historians.
However, scholars also believe the Gelao ethnic group was formed
after the non-native people mixed together with the aboriginal
people of Guangxi.
</P>
<P>
"Since then, we Gelao ethnic people have lived deep in the
mountains and have seldom had contact with the outside world,"
said Wei.
</P>
<P>
Legend has it that the people of the Yelang Kingdom were
renowned for conceit and arrogance -- one main reason behind their
failures. But Wei Shaoting, who is now chairman of the Longlin
Multi-National Autonomous County Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), looks more like a
modest and amiable scholar.
</P>
<P>
The Gelao is the smallest ethnic group in Guangxi, with a
population of about 4,000, and Wei is the highest official among
the Gelaos. He was also once the deputy county magistrate of
Longlin.
</P>
<P>
"Previously, neither I nor my people would have thought I could
become a government official, as the Gelaos do not have a strong
ambition to become leaders, and they are also afraid of being
identified as 'people of ludicrous conceit.'" said Wei, "But now,
an increasing number of young Gelao people want to seek government
posts or become civil servants."
</P>
<P>
It is obvious that villages with greater contact with the
outside world will have faster economic growth, Wei believes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gelao Ethnic Group (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Gelao people first got their own school when New China was
founded on October 1, 1949, and Wei was one of the first group
lucky enough to receive a primary and middle school education.
</P>
<P>
Wei joined the air force after attending an aerospace school in
1960 and was assigned to work in the ground crew at an airport in
north China's Hebei Province after he graduated.
</P>
<P>
"I am probably the first Gelao who had the chance to study
aircraft," Wei said.
</P>
<P>
Wei recalled that when he applied to join the air force from a
teachers training school where he was studying, he did not dare
tell his parents for fear of their disapproval. There were 150
applicants form the teachers school and only five of them were
enrolled in the aerospace school.
</P>
<P>
"One benefit of going out into the world is that my vision has
been widened," said Wei. He even broke off a marriage engagement
arranged by his parents in accordance with Gelao customs, to marry
a girl of the Zhuang ethnic group.
</P>
<P>
After leaving his hometown, Wei met many people of other ethnic
groups, which made him time and again consider the question: Why
have other ethnic groups become stronger while the Gelao people
remain backward?
</P>
<P>
He found that the answer was partially because of historical
factors and partly because of the people themselves. Therefore,
when he returned to Longlin after being demobilized from the air
force, he worked in education for quite some time, and later was
promoted to deputy county magistrate of Longlin.
</P>
<P>
According to China's law on regional national autonomy,
leaders of an autonomous county are people chosen from the ethnic
groups.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two decades, the Gelao people have seen a
steady increase of its population, an improvement in the
cultural quality and living standards of the people, and a
growing awareness of the market economy.
</P>
<P>
In everyday life, the Gelao people no longer wear their unique
ethnic costumes, donning them now only for traditional festivals.
But the language and some customs unique to the Gelao are still
practiced.
</P>
<P>
The most important Gelao festivals are the "tree-worshiping"
fest in January according to lunar calendar, and "worshiping
ancestors with the heart of cattle" fest on August 15.
</P>
<P>
"Without the care of the Party and the government, I and my
people might still be living a backward life deep in the
mountains, not to mention that I would not be in a position to
help run the county," Wei said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
