<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Stock Market Index Goes up Marginally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Nairobi Stock Exchange
(NSE) 20-share index edged up 11.14 points or 0.43 percent
Tuesday to close at 2621.38 points.
</P>
<P>
Turnover fell to 7.95 million Shillings (about 132,500 U.S.
Dollars) from 219,000 shares, compared to 16 million Shillings
(some 266,666 Dollars) from 215,000 shares Monday, the East
African Standard newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan Central Bank Treasury Bond issue 1/98 worth 1.55
million Shillings (25,000 Dollars) was dealt at between rates of
103.1 percent and 103.3 percent. Foreign investors sold 1,500
shares of Diamond Trust at 21.75 Shillings.
</P>
<P>
Commercial and services sector moved the highest number of
shares accounting for 35 percent of the day's volume. The sector
traded 77,000 shares.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's trading is in contrast to the favorable second week
running which saw the NSE maintain its upward movement as the
index closed last week at 2595.4.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that it is still difficult to predict the
performance of the stock market as the holiday moods start and
the year comes to a close.
</P>
<P>
However, they said that banks and other financial institutions
that rely heavily on the treasury bill market could find
themselves in a tight spot as the margins and yields in the
market continue to shrink.
</P>
<P>
Chief economist of the central bank, J.P. Kanga, said Tuesday
that the Shilling weakened against the U.S. Dollar and the Pound
Sterling in the week ending Tuesday, with the average exchange
rate for the week against the Dollar falling to 60.94 Shillings
from 59.89 Shillings last week.
</P>
<P>
The Pound Sterling average exchange rate for the week moved to
101.08 Shillings from 98.99 Shillings in the previous week.
</P>
<P>
Kanga said the 91-day treasury bill average rate fell to 14.35
percent in the Monday auction from 15.79 percent in the previous
deals. Commercial banks' average base lending rate fell further
to 26.01 percent from 26.20 percent last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
