<HEADLINE> New Zealand Forecasts Current year's Deficit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand government
is forecasting a financial deficit of 52 million NZ dollars (27
million U.S. dollars) for the current year instead of an earlier
predicted surplus of 100 million NZ dollars (52 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
In its Budget Policy Statement released Wednesday afternoon,
the government announced that the current year's deficit would be
followed by a serious 1.3 billion NZ dollar (676 million U.S.
dollar) deficit in 1999-2000 and one billion NZ dollar (520
million U.S. dollar) deficit in 2000-2001.
</P>
<P>
While releasing the Budget Policy Statement, New Zealand
treasurer Bill Birch said the government is taking a long term
view on the deteriorating state of the public account deficit.
</P>
</TEXT>
