<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thumbs Down for Television Shopping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- More than 70 percent of Chinese
consumers are not interested in shopping by TV, according to a
survey by the China Business Monitoring Center.
</P>
<P>
Within that number as many as 42 percent say they are put off
by the high prices of the goods on sale despite the surge of
advertising at peak broadcast times on many television channels..
</P>
<P>
Over 1,200 people took part in the poll in six major Chinese
cities: Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Xi'an, Chengdu and Wuhan.
</P>
<P>
Although it revealed that 85 percent of those questioned
watched TV advertisements, and are familiar with this convenient
way of shopping, only 18 percent think it is likely to become a
popular method.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, some people are suspicious of the exaggerated claims
made for a lot of products while others say they are simply luxury
items.
</P>
<P>
However, according to the survey it seems that high-income
earners are more enthusiastic about television style retailing
while poorer viewers are content merely to watch the programs.
</P>
<P>
It also highlighted that women and young people in the age group
of 15-24 are the bulk of purchasers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Li Xuemei Confident of Beating Jayasinghe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Chinese top sprinter Li Xuemei
said upon her arrival here on Wednesday that she was confident of
beating Sri Lanka's world silver medalist Susanthika Jayasinghe to
become the fastest woman in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Li, 21, Asian record holder in the 100 and 200m, said she had
been training hard in the past two months and everything goes
right for her.
</P>
<P>
"I have no injury problems now, and it's not as hot as expected
here, " said Li, who arrived at the Bangkok international airport
with the 50-strong Chinese track and field team.
</P>
<P>
Jaysinghe, who got here last Saturday, said that she believed
she can win the two gold medals of the women's 100 and 200m.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan was banned for failing a doping test early this
year but later was allowed to run in the Asian Games, got here
last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Li broke Asia's 100 and 200m record with two stunning
performances of 10.79 and 22.01 seconds in last year's Chinese
National Games in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
She crashed at hometown Chengdu last May in the world fastest
woman race which also drew world sprint queen Marion Jones of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
"I don't mind what Jayasinghe said," Li said. "I have been
ready to beat all the rivals."
</P>
<P>
Admitting that the main rival this time was Jayasinghe, Li's
coach Zhang Rongwei said that other Sri Lankans might emerge as
the unexpected winners.
</P>
<P>
"We are not afraid of Jayasinghe," he said. "We only fear that
other little known runners to cause a surprise."
</P>
<P>
Zhang predicted that Li can run inside 11.20 in the 100m and
22.33 in the 200.
</P>
<P>
"Our goal is to win the gold medal. No one can scare us," Zhang
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
