<HEADLINE> China's Wang Xian Wins Women's Sport Rifle Prone Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 9 (Xinhua) -- World championships runner-up
Wang Xian won China's first individual shooting title at the
Bangkok Asian Games when she scored 589 points in the women's
sport rifle prone event here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Yoko Minamoto and Noriko Ojima carried home the silver
and bronze medals, scoring 586 and 585 points respectively.
</P>
<P>
"I wasn't satisfied with my results here," said 18-year-old
Wang. "But I know my form is improving."
</P>
<P>
Chinese coach Zhang Qiuping said: "Wang really has talents for
the sport. It is also remarkable that she is an all-round
shooter."
</P>
<P>
Japan beat China to second place for the team title, where the
countries scored the same total of 1,754.
</P>
<P>
Japan was adjudged the winner as the trio Yoko Minamoto, Noriko
Ojima and Mari Onoe registered better points in the last 20 shots
in this 60-shot non-Olympic event.
</P>
<P>
China won the silver while Thailand was third at 1,745.
</P>
<P>
"We did not expect a gold medal," said Japan's Minamoto, a
31-year-old veteran making a comeback after two years of absence
from international competition.
</P>
<P>
"I was also surprised that I had won the individual silver," she
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
