<HEADLINE> Greener Beijing Hopes to Win Olympic Games in 2008 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- China's capital city of Beijing
has announced plans to increase its grassy parklands in a bid to
win the Olympic Games in 2008.
</P>
<P>
The city's Greening Committee said today that more than one
million square meters of new grass will be planted every year in
the next few years.
</P>
<P>
And to mark the 50th anniversary of the People's Republic of
China next year, as much as 1.5 million square meters will be
planted, according to a spokesman for the committee.
</P>
<P>
He added: "Most Beijingers are keen to have more green areas
in the city, especially now that they are becoming more
environmentally aware.
</P>
<P>
"In recent times this has become a major topic of interest for
increasing numbers of people."
</P>
<P>
Even in winter, officials intend Beijing to enjoy lush, grass
lawns by planting special ever-green seeds and plants.
</P>
<P>
Gardening experts at Beijing Municipal Administration of
Forestry have developed a strain of grass that can last throughout
most of the year, the spokesman revealed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, at the Lawn Development Center of the Beijing
Municipal Forestry Administration in Beijing's suburb of Daxing
County, 70 hectares of the experimental grass has survived even
two heavy snow falls this winter.
</P>
<P>
"It is as green as it was in the spring," said Zhang Yunchang,
the Center's head who said he hoped that in the near future
Beijingers could enjoy grassy areas all over the city.  
</P>
</TEXT>
