<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economists Urge Service Industry Liberalization (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- China must adopt an
enthusiastic, but nonetheless cautious attitude in its efforts
to liberalize its service sector, including the
telecommunications and financial industries.
</P>
<P>
"China must draw lessons from the financial crisis in Mexico
and the ongoing crisis engulfing Southeast Asia," according to
Professor Liu Guoguang, an adviser to the Chinese Academy of
Social Sciences (CASS).
</P>
<P>
Liu made the remarks during the International Trade Industry
Symposium -- China and the World -- held in Beijing, the Chinese
capital, on December 8-9. The symposium was sponsored by the
U.S.-based Ford Foundation, the Institute of Finance and Trade
under the CASS and the Center for American Studies at Fudan
University.
</P>
<P>
China must fully consider the underdevelopment of its fledgling
service industry and gradually proceed in line with the capacity
of the national economy to withstand strains, according to Liu..
</P>
<P>
He noted that China faces a dilemma in terms of liberalizing
its service industry.
</P>
<P>
Countries negotiating China's membership in the World Trade
Organization (WTO) have urged the nation to immediately open most
areas of its service industry. However, the underdeveloped
industry is burdened with the substantial impact associated with
sudden liberalization, said Liu.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that liberalization will involve challenges,
potential risk and various other adverse factors, but will
nonetheless be highly beneficial to further promoting the nation's
foreign trade and economic development.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the Ministry of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation (MOFTEC) show that the service industry
accounts for close to 30 percent of China's GDP. However, the
industry's 1995 turnover of 44.3 billion US dollars accounted for
a mere 1.8 percent of the international total and only 20 percent
of the country's total trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Juventus Coach to Unveil His Future Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Italy's Juventus coach Marcello
Lippi said he would announce his plan for next season within 10
days in Turin, Italy on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
His five-year contract will expire in June.
</P>
<P>
Lippi is expected to join either Lazio or Inter Milan.
</P>
<P>
Before he decides, he will coach Juventus to take on Norway's
Rosenborg at Wednesday's European Champions League and leader
Fiorentina at Italian Division First League on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Lippi led the team to win two Italian League titles in a row.
However, Juventus, which has been winless since November 1, has
plummeted to fifth place in the league standings this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0317 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economists Urge Service Trade Liberalization (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Liu said China must follow nondiscriminatory principles related
to preferential treatment, by granting equal status to domestic and
foreign enterprises, eliminating disparities between sectors,
ensuring balanced regional development and moderate protective
measures.
</P>
<P>
"China's ability to carry out the nondiscriminatory principle
depends on the nation gaining the same status as WTO members,"
according to Liu.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the government should pay close attention
to opening markets to domestic service enterprises, especially in
terms of improving the international competitiveness of
private companies.
</P>
<P>
Liberalization should be introduced gradually and inland
enterprises should have the same opportunities as their coastal
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
China should take full advantage of the cushion effect
accompanying the grace period, and the government should avoid
adopting protective measures which seriously impact
domestic service enterprises.
</P>
<P>
MOFTEC official Zheng Li noted that China initiated its bid for
memberships in both the WTO and GATT some 12 years ago. Issues
surrounding the service industry, especially the
telecommunications and financial sectors, have gradually emerged
as the main obstacles in the negotiating process.
</P>
<P>
Zheng pointed to the urgent need to do a better study on the
development of various service sectors throughout the world, as
well as related international practices and regulations.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 experts, scholars and officials from China, the
United States, Japan, Australia, Germany and the WTO attended the
symposium. Participants focused on a number of issues, including
the development of China's service industry and related trade
activities, as well as international trade involving
telecommunications, finance, insurance and transportation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0318 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
