<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Int'l Buddhist University Inaugurates in Myanmar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, December 9 (Xinhua) -- An international Buddhist
missionary university, the first permanent center of higher
learning of the Theravada (Little Vehicle) Buddhism in various
languages, grandly inaugurated at the Mahapasana (Great) Cave of
Kaba-aye (World Peace) hill here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Attended at the inaugural ceremony were First Secretary of
Myanmar State Peace and Development Council Lieutenant-General
Khin Nyunt, Deputy Prime Minister Lieutenant-General Tin Hla,
Minister of Religious Affairs Major-General Sein Htwa, Myanmar
chief Buddhist monks, religious leaders, personnel from religious
organizations as well as invited guests from 14 countries --
China, Laos, Cambodia, Vietnam, Malaysia, Singapore, Republic of
Korea, Japan, India, Sri Lanka, Nepal, Russia, Britain and the
United States.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the International Theravada Buddhist
Missionary University (ITBMU) is aimed at promoting the
flourishing of the genuine Theravada Buddhism throughout the
world, and studying and comprehending the canonical texts of the
Buddhism which eventually lead to purification, perpetuation and
propagation of the Buddha teachings in the world.
</P>
<P>
The university will begin with a one-year diploma course with
different language teachings covering English, Chinese, French,
Japanese, German, Hindu and Arabic. The medium of instruction will
be in English.
</P>
<P>
The subjects to be taught in the university cover theory and
practice of Buddhism, Buddhist culture, history, comparative
studies of religions, Pali and Myanmar languages.
</P>
<P>
Foreign monks, nuns and laypersons, who have passed the
matriculation standard, are allowed to join the university, or
they will have to sit for the examinations.
</P>
<P>
Those who complete the initial one-year diploma course are
allowed for further studies for Bachelor, Master and Doctor
degrees of Philosophy in Buddha teaching.
</P>
<P>
As a country with the majority of its population (about 89.4
percent) believing in Buddhism, Myanmar had established Buddhist
scripture learning centers and other monastic education schools
long ago.
</P>
<P>
There are two other state Buddhist universities in the country,
one in Yangon and the other in Mandalay.
</P>
<P>
For nearly a thousand years, Myanmar has kept Theravada
Buddhism pure and intact. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
