<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Revises Windows 98 Due to Y2K Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Officials from the Microsoft
Corporation said Tuesday that the corporation is making a revision
to Windows 98 aimed to fix an error related with the Y2K problem,
the Washington Post reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Windows 98 operating system was released this summer and is
used in most personal computers sold today.
</P>
<P>
Don Jones, a Microsoft product manager in charge of features
related to the Y2K problem, said that none of the problems poses
any risk of data loss or damage to computers. The problems caused
by the millennium bug were found during company tests, and none
were reported by customers.
</P>
<P>
The company will help its customers fix the problems free of
charge on its Windows Update site on the World Wide Web. Users
can also receive a "patch" by ordering a special CD-ROM.
</P>
<P>
The problems include the roll-over of dates, leap-year dates
and phone dialing.
</P>
<P>
The year 2000 glitch can cause computers to read the year 2000
as "1900" because most old computers were programmed to read only
a double-digit date. As a result, affected computers might
transmit flawed information, or crash completely. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
