<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi PM Urges Investors to Set up Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Prime Minister Sheikh
Hasina has called upon the local and foreign investors to set up
industries in the rural areas for balanced development of the
country.
</P>
<P>
She made this call while inaugurating a detergent industry in
the private sector in the country's northwest district of
Manikganj Tuesday, The Independent daily newspaper reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Do not locate your industries in the cities or suburbs only,
build those in the rural areas and become a part of balanced
development at progress," she said.
</P>
<P>
Opportunities have been created following the expansion of
infrastructure network all over the country especially the opening
of the multi-purpose Jamuna Bridge in last June, which has linked
the east and northwest parts of the country, Hasina noted.
</P>
<P>
She assured more facilities to the entrepreneurs who would set
industrial plants mainly agro-based industries in the rural areas.
</P>
<P>
This would create employment opportunities in the rural areas
and reduce the tendency of the people going to urban areas to
great extent, she stressed.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the prime minister urged the investors to remain
vigilant so that environment of their areas were not polluted with
the industrial wastes.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh is an agriculture-based country with more than 80
percent of its 127 million people living in the rural areas, and
among them, over 50 percent people are still living under the
poverty-line. The government has adopted a series of measures to
encourage local and foreign investors to set up industries in the
rural areas in a bid to alleviate poverty there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
