<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Cooperation for Flood Management Needed: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Global warming, deforestation in
the upper riparian regions and human interventions in the natural
functioning of ecosystem are the causes of floods in Bangladesh,
speakers pointed out at a seminar held here Tuesday, a daily
newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Flood management in Bangladesh demands an integrated approach
involving regional cooperation with the co-basin countries like
India, Nepal and Bhutan, as the primary cause of floods in
Bangladesh is the excessive rainfall in basins of three mighty
rivers -- the Ganges, the Brahmaputra and the Meghna, The
Bangladesh Observer quoted the speakers as saying at the seminar
on "Flood 1998 and Management of Floods in Future".
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister A.M.S. Kabria said that short, medium and
long-term solutions to the frequent floods in the country should
be worked out in dealing with different dimensions of floods, and
regional cooperation would require in planning long-term flood
control programs.
</P>
<P>
Mentioning various steps which were taken by the government to
check the flood fury, Kabria said the nation has shown the prowess
as it happened in 1971 during the flood period of 1998 by facing
the century's worst ever natural calamity.
</P>
<P>
Regional cooperation with India, Nepal, Bhutan and China could
be helpful in reducing the severity and duration of floods,
Professor A.K. Azad Chowdhury stressed.
</P>
<P>
This was evident from the fact that the area inundated by major
floods increased gradually from 37,000 square kilometers in 1962
to 89,900 square kilometers in 1988 and one million square
kilometers in 1998, he added.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh was hit by devastating floods from mid-July to
mid-September this year, which affected two-thirds of the country
and over 30 million people, inflicting a preliminary estimated
loss of about 4.3 billion U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
