<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton's Lawyers See Lack of Evidence to Back Impeachment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton's defenders forcefully pleaded his case before the House
of Representatives Judiciary Committee on Tuesday, saying that the
president's conduct was "misleading, even maddening" but did not
warrant removing him from office.
</P>
<P>
"As surely as we know that what he did was sinful, we also know
it is not impeachable," White House lawyer Gregory Craig told a
committee bristling with skeptical Republicans.
</P>
<P>
Other witnesses, including former lawmakers who sat in judgment
of former President Richard Nixon a quarter-century ago, argued
that Clinton's conduct in the Monica Lewinsky affair was no
Watergate, and thus not worthy of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
Even so, Republicans flashed frustration as the session dragged
on for 11 hours. "It has been very disappointing that we've had
very little discussion of the actual facts of the case after over
eight hours of testimony without a break," said Republican
lawmaker Charles Canady. "I think the facts are very troubling."
</P>
<P>
Under the direction of the committee's chairman, Republican
lawmaker Henry Hyde, the Judiciary Committee's staff has begun
drafting articles of impeachment accusing Clinton of perjury,
obstruction of justice and abuse of power. Committee votes are
expected to begin Friday.
</P>
<P>
Republican sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
they felt confident an article of impeachment alleging perjury
would garner support from all 21 committee Republicans, thus
assuring its approval.
</P>
<P>
In a 184-page written rebuttal of the charges released Tuesday
night, the White House argued that contrary to Independent Counsel
Kenneth Starr's claims, the president made no agreement with
Lewinsky to lie under oath and did not attempt to influence the
testimony of presidential secretary Betty Currie. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
