<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Witnesses Rising Sterility Levels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Recent statistics show that the
ratio of sterility in China has jumped by three percent to one in
eight couples over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Today's Beijing Morning Post quoted experts as saying that the
causes of sterility are directly associated with the contemporary
environment and living habits.
</P>
<P>
Heavy smoking and liquor consumption, venereal diseases,
premarital sex and electromagnetic waves from household appliances
and telecommunications equipment are so-called "invisible
killers", factors contributing to a couple's weakening ability to
bear children.
</P>
<P>
Air and water pollution, as well as various diseases have also
been listed as causes of sterility.
</P>
<P>
Modern males produce 50 percent less sperm than their
counterparts living some 200 years ago, according to the report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
