<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Economy Estimated to Grow By 0.8 Percent Next </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Thai economy will grow by
0.8 percent next year and inflation by 5.3 percent, according to
latest estimates from the National Economic and Social Development
Board (NESDB).
</P>
<P>
The figures contrast with those made in Thailand's updated
commitments to the International Monetary Fund of 1 percent growth
and 2.5-3 percent inflation.
</P>
<P>
Wirat Wattanasiritham, the board's secretary-general, was
quoted Wednesday by the Bangkok Post as saying that the NESDB's
forecasts were preliminary and would be reviewed later this month.
</P>
<P>
The forecasts would be as far ahead as 2001 and help the
government plan its budget for 2000. Figures would be submitted to
senior economic ministers on December 28.
</P>
<P>
This year, the economy was expected to contract by 7-8 percent,
according the NESDB. It also predicted inflation of 8.5 percent
this year, while the IMF forecast 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Turning to export value, the NESDB predicted a decline of 6.4
percent this year and 5 percent next year. Imports are forecast to
decline by 35.5 percent this year and 5.6 percent next year.
</P>
<P>
The NESDB forecast a surplus of 13.5 billion U.S. dollars in
the trade balance this year and 14 billion U.S. dollars next year.
It also expected a current account surplus of 16 billion U.S.
dollars this year and 16.3 billion U.S. dollars next year.
</P>
<P>
Wirat claimed the economy would start to recover next year as
Thailand had been able to maintain exports and tourism. This was
mainly because the government had run a budget deficit of 3
percent of gross domestic product instead of 1 percent, freeing
100 billion baht (2.7 billion U.S. dollars) for investment.
</P>
<P>
However, the recovery would be slight as private investment
would improve only marginally. After declining by 45.8 percent
this year, private investment would grow by only 1 percent next
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
