<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Right to Development, A Must in Globalization Age (Part I) By Gu Zhenqiu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- As the world is marking
the 50th anniversary this week of the Universal Declaration of
Human Rights, it should be further stressed once again that the
right to development should remain fundamental in realizing all
other human rights, especially in the current age of
globalization.
</P>
<P>
"The right to development is the measure of the respect of all
other human rights. That should be our aim: a situation in which
all individuals are enabled to maximize their potential, and to
contribute to the evolution of society as a whole," U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan has said.
</P>
<P>
The right to development was first proclaimed as an inalienable
human right by the international community in 1986, following
years of debate. The Declaration on the Right to Development,
adopted that year by the United Nations General Assembly,
represented a new approach to the pursuit of the ideals of the
world body.
</P>
<P>
The Declaration says, "The human person is the central subject
of development and should be the participant and beneficiary of
the right to development." It further states that "The full
realization of civil and political rights without the enjoyment of
economic, social and cultural right is impossible."
</P>
<P>
Although everyone agrees that the goal of development is
economic progress and the creation of conditions to ensure a life
of dignity, debate continues on how to achieve it.
</P>
<P>
This is especially true in today's world of rapid globalization
where levels of official development assistance (ODA) are dropping
and private capital flows are increasing to certain parts of the
world to the exclusion of others.
</P>
<P>
While the globalization of the world economy has provided new
opportunities for development, it has also created new risks.
There is a risk of marginalization of countries, groups and
individuals that are unable to compete, as well as the increased
possibility of economic or financial instability and social
discontent.
</P>
<P>
At the July 1998 session of the U.N. Economic and Social
Council, Alioune Sene, former chairman of the Working Group on the
Right to Development which was set up by the U.N. Commission on
Human Rights in 1981, called for emergency measures to prevent the
exclusion of developing countries, especially least-developed
countries, from the globalization process.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that each country needed to elaborate a policy
of development that was centered around the human rights.
</P>
<P>
U.N. statistics show that the greatest benefits of
globalization have been garnered by a fortunate few. The world's
least developed countries, with 10 percent of the world's people,
have only 0.3 percent of world trade -- half their share of two
decades ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0351 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Right to Development, A Must in Globalization Age (Part II) By Gu Zhenqiu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Further worse, the terms of trade are not favorable. Average
tariffs on industrial country imports from the least-developed
countries are 30 percent higher than the global average.
</P>
<P>
Overall, developing countries lose about 60 billion U.S.
dollars a year from agricultural subsidies and barriers to textile
exports in industrial nations. Also, more than half of all
developing countries have been bypassed by foreign direct
investment.
</P>
<P>
According to U.N. figures, 1.5 billion people must get by on
less than one U.S. dollar a day. In South Asia, half of all
children under 5 are malnourished. Only a third of the people in
sub-Saharan Africa are likely to live past 40.
</P>
<P>
Many believe that the time has come to move from a theoretical
debate to practical measures aimed at the realization of the right
to development. Mary Robinson, the U.N. high commissioner for
human rights, has said, "Human rights bring to the development
discussion a unifying set of standards -- a common references for
setting objectives and assessing the value of action."
</P>
<P>
In this regard, a January 1998 policy document of the U.N.
Development Program (UNDP) was worth a warm welcome. It outlines
plans to integrate human rights into activities aimed at fighting
poverty, promoting the advancement of women, protecting the
environment and developing the capacity for good governance.
</P>
<P>
Through its work, the 185-member United Nations continues to
call the world's attention to the problems, and presents avenues
for answers. As a result, there is an emerging consensus that all
countries and all major international economic and financial
agencies should engage more seriously in efforts to formulate
better policies towards globalization to ensure that the gap
between the rich and poor stops growing.
</P>
<P>
To be more specific, poor countries must first rely on
themselves for development. In other words, they must invest in
human development.
</P>
<P>
However, they, on the other hand, also need special support
from the international community -- through concessional
assistance, debt relief, trade preferences, technical cooperation
and national capacity-building -- if they are to make their way in
the fiercely competitive global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
Peace and development are the main theme of our times. The
global problem needs global solution. Therefore, developed
countries should bear their responsibility to help their
developing counterparts. By doing so, the world can do a lot to
prevent many conflicts related to poverty, discrimination and
exclusion that contine to plague humanity and destroy decades of
development efforts.
</P>
<P>
With the assistance from the developed world, the vicious cycle
of human rights violations that lead to conflicts, which in turn
lead to more violations, can stand more chance to be broken. For
it has been vindicating that without the right to development by
the developing countries, there will be no peace and stability in
the world, which, characterized by greater inter-dependence among
countries, will surely have negative impact on the economic
expansion of the developed world. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0352 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian President Urges Rebels to Resume Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Colombian
President Andres Pastrana on Tuesday called on the largest
guerrilla group in his country to return to the negotiation table.
</P>
<P>
"We hope for a peaceful gesture from the guerrillas," Pastrana
said here on the last day of his official visit to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
"We don't understand why they have not" resumed the talks, he
said, noting that his government had met all the demands set by
the Colombian Revolutionary Armed Forces (FARC) to discuss peace.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana and the leader of the FARC reached an agreement on
July 9 on setting up buffer zones. But in November a dispute
about buffer zones stalled the peace process.
</P>
<P>
Pastrana also condemned Monday's attack by a paramilitary group
on the community of La Guajira, which left between 10 and 20
people dead. Local paramilitary groups are involved in armed
fighting against the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian president praised Mexico for its offer to be a
mediator in the peace talks, adding that the intermediaries would
be chosen through a consensus between the government and the
FARC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
