<HEADLINE> Kosovo Albanian Negotiators Reject U.S. Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Kosovo Albanian negotiators
have rejected the latest U.S. draft accord for the Serbian
province, according to Yugoslav newspapers.
</P>
<P>
The Munja newspaper on Tuesday quoted Kosovo Albanian chief
negotiator Fehmi Agani as saying, "It cannot serve as the basis
for negotiations."
</P>
<P>
Agani said on Monday in Pristina that Kosovo Albanians would
submit their own proposals to resolve the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
"Kosovo Albanians are not refusing to talk, but they will not
take part in talks before they submit their own proposals," Agani
said.
</P>
<P>
Adem Demaci, the political representative of the rebel Kosovo
Liberation Army (KLA), holds the "same position" regarding
U.S. special envoy to the Balkans Christopher Hill's latest peace
plan, he added.
</P>
<P>
Another newspaper Vecernje Novosti reported Demaci was very
angry with the U.S. plan. He told reporters in Pristina on
Tuesday that he asked the U.S. government to dismiss Hill as
U.S. special envoy.
</P>
<P>
Demaci said Hill's plan failed to mention the KLA, nor did it
discuss the future of Kosovo after the three-year transitional
period expires.
</P>
<P>
The Yugoslav news media has not yet revealed the details of the
latest U.S. draft. 
</P>
</TEXT>
