<HEADLINE> Indonesian Former President Soeharto Questioned </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian former president
Soeharto began to be questioned at Jakarta's Higher Prosecutors
Office on Wednesday morning over alleged corruption, collusion and
nepotistic practices during his 32 years in power.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto, accompanied by nine lawyers, arrived at the
Prosecutors Office at 07:20 a.m. local time.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian President B.J. Habibie on Thursday order Attorney
General Andi M. Ghalib to speed up the investigation into
Soeharto's alleged ill-gotten wealth.
</P>
<P>
According to a summons send by Ghalib to Soeharto on December
4, the questioning by the Attorney General's Office will focus on
the funds held by several foundations that Soeharto chaired and on
the tax exemptions granted to his son's company under the Timor
national car program.
</P>
<P>
On November 25, Soeharto handed over to the government the
funds from seven charity foundations he chaired, a total of about
4 trillion rupiah (530 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
A document issued by Ghalib on Monday said that the 1996
presidential decree Soeharto issued to authorize the Timor
national car project was designed solely to promote family
interests.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, a company controlled by Soeharto's youngest
son Hutomo "Tommy" Mandala Putra was given huge tax exemptions and
a multi-million U.S. dollar soft loan from a consortium of 16
banks, including state banks, to produce the Timor national car.
The project had caused the country losses of 1.55 billion U.S.
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Soeharto was forced to step down on May 21 amid the country's
worst political and economic crisis in decades. He is accused of
corruption and abuse of power during his 32 years in power.
</P>
<P>
He said he was ready to face any probe into his wealth as well
as allegations of corrupt, collusive and nepotistic practices.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that he had 22 billion rupiah (3 million U.S.
dollars) deposited in three banks, and that his personal property
includes two houses in Jakarta and five hectares of land.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, key associates of Soeharto were questioned at the
Attorney General's Office.
</P>
<P>
Former industry and trade minister Tunku Ariwibowo was
questioned for more than five hours over the Timor national car
project. Also questioned was Hadiyanto, treasurer of the Dharmais
Foundation, one of the seven foundations handed over to the
government by Soeharto.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Mohamad "Bob" Hasan, Tunky's immediate
successor as minister of industry and trade, would be questioned
on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the Attorney General's Office Barman Zahir said
Hasan, a close friend of Soeharto, would be questioned over
Soeharto's foundations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
