<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0360 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Praises Hong Kong for Continued Trade Openness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Despite the present economic
difficulties, China's Hong Kong has maintained its traditional
openness to both trade and investment and has not taken any
measures directly affecting imports or foreign investment, the
World Trade Organization (WTO) said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In its report on Hong Kong's trade policies and practices, the
WTO underlined two main events which put Hong Kong in the
spotlight since the last trade policy review in 1994.
</P>
<P>
The first is Hong Kong's return to the People's Republic of
China on July 1, 1997, and its designation as a Special
Administrative Region under the "one country, two systems"
framework. The second event is related to the economic crisis in
Southeast Asia, the WTO said after a two-day discussion with its
Trade Policy Review Body.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the first, the report noted that there is "no
indication that Hong Kong's traditional openness to trade and
foreign investment has been affected."
</P>
<P>
In regard to the second, the report found that even in the wake
of the crisis, "The government does not appear to have attempted
to influence the long-term structural evolution of Hong Kong's
economy."
</P>
<P>
The Asian economic crisis which began in Thailand in July 1997
and then spread to other countries in Southeast Asia, seriously
impaired Hong Kong's economic performance and caused a dramatic
slowdown in economic activity, according to the WTO.
</P>
<P>
"Real GDP is expected to decline by four percent in 1998
compared to robust growth of 5.3 percent in 1997," said the WTO.
</P>
<P>
"Authorities in Hong Kong believe that competition is best
nurtured and sustained by allowing the free play of market forces
and keeping intervention to a minimum," the report said.
</P>
<P>
It noted that the Hong Kong government has recently established
a body to handle complaints about anti-competitive private
practices while certain sectors, particularly telecommunications
and legal services, have been subjected to increased competition.
Hong Kong is also studying the possibility of increasing
competition in the energy sector.
</P>
<P>
In its conclusions, the WTO report predicted that Hong Kong's
trade deficit is expected to narrow considerably in 1998,
suggesting that domestic product and factor markets may be
adjusting to reverse Hong Kong's recent decline in export
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
"The recent fall in the value of the U.S. dollar, especially
relative to the Japanese yen, and cuts in U.S. interest rates,
will also help improve Hong Kong's growth prospects," it said.
</P>
<P>
"This, together with its traditional adherence to a free and
open market system, should facilitate Hong Kong's emergence from
the current economic crisis and contribute to a resumption of its
strong economic performance," the report concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0361 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
