<HEADLINE> Venezuelan Stocks Soar After Chavez's No-devaluation Decision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- After Venezuelan president-elect
Hugo Chavez's announcement of not devaluing the currency or
imposing exchange controls, stock index of Caracas market on
Tuesday closed at a historic high of 4,757.78 points.
</P>
<P>
The Caracas stock exchange index recovered 835.50 points, or
21.39 percent, over last Friday's close, reflecting investors'
confidence toward Chavez.
</P>
<P>
"The president-elect's first steps have been positive and have
given back confidence to the country," an official stock exchange
statement said.
</P>
<P>
Chavez declared that he would favor and guarantee foreign
investments, slash the budget deficit, and respect all
international commitments.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of Venezuelan currency, the Bolivar, against
the U.S. dollar also rose to 571.50 Bolivars against one dollar
over Friday's 576.50.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts said the financial enthusiasm could end up
soon due to expectation of currency devaluation under intense
pressure and possibility of a new banking crisis.
</P>
<P>
The economy is also expected to shrink one percent after
growing more than five percent in 1997, with the budget deficit
reaching 3.5 billion dollars this year and possibly five billion
dollars next year.
</P>
<P>
Chavez has vowed to increase minimum wages and revamp health
and education systems. He said the money will come from
eliminating corruption and collecting more taxes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
