<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia's Private Banks Expected to Fall to 50 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian President B.J.
Habibie has said the number of private banks is expected to fall
to 50 from the current 150 as a result of the ongoing
recapitalization program.
</P>
<P>
"Currently there are about 150 banks and most of them need
recapitalization which will cost a lot of money. I have told
bankers these must be consolidated to become 50 banks," Habibie
said when opening the Indonesian Chamber of Commerce and Industry
Congress here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian government recently launched a banking
recapitalization program in a bid to revive the country's ailing
banking sector.
</P>
<P>
Bank recapitalization is one of the four measures in the
government's bank restructuring program. The others are cleaning
up bad credits, the liquidation of insolvent banks, merging state
banks and recovery of liquidity support.
</P>
<P>
All commercial banks are required to have a minimum capital
adequacy ratio of 4 percent by the end of this year, 8 percent by
the end of 1999, and 10 percent by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
Capital adequacy ratio is the ratio between equity capital and
risk-weighted assets.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, the government will provide 80 percent of
the required funding, while the remainder has to be provided by
the banks' owners. In return, the government will get a non-voting
equity stake in the banks.
</P>
<P>
Banks whose capital ratios are below minus 25 percent were
given one month from the end of September to inject fresh capital
in order to qualify for the government recapitalization program.
</P>
<P>
The government is expected to close some banks that don't meet
the required standards while others are set to be merged.
</P>
<P>
The president also said he expects the country's inflation will
slow to between 35 and 40 percent in the current fiscal year
ending in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Inflation in the fiscal year 1998-99 is expected to be around
35-40 percent, in 1999-2000 around 10-20 percent and if we are
consistent with our policy, we hope in the year 2001, inflation
will be below 10 percent", he was quoted by national newspapers
Tuesday as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
