<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pioneer Back as New Village Leader by Popular Choice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, December 9 (Xinhua) -- Yan Hongchang, who was one of 18
farmers to begin China's rural reforms 20 years, made a come-back
when he was elected to office in the village of Xiaogang's first
democratic elections recently.
</P>
<P>
The 48-year-old farmer got 137 of the 258 votes cast, beating
out his only competitor, 29-year-old Wu Guangde, as the new
chairman of the villagers' committee.
</P>
<P>
"I must live up to my fellow villagers' trust," Yan said after
winning the elections, "I hope all the villagers will support and
supervise me."
</P>
<P>
In late 1978, Yan and 17 other farmers signed an agreement to
secretly carved some People's Commune-owned farmlands up into
smaller plots for each family in Xiaogang to manage on their own,
an act that was regarded capitalistic at the time, one that could
conceivably result in a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
In the "counterrevolutionary" document, which is now on display
at Beijing's Museum of the Chinese Revolution, the 18 men swore
that if any one of them was persecuted by the authorities for this
act of putting their lives on the line, his children would be
supported by the rest of the signatories until the age of 18.
</P>
<P>
Xiaogang is in Anhui Province's Fengyang County, which used to
have thousands of beggars. "We had no choice but to reform at the
time, because starvation would kill us all," Yan recalled. Almost
everyone in the village went begging for some time before 1978,
Yan said.
</P>
<P>
But, the farmers were lucky when it turned out that their bold
move coincided with the CPC's Third Plenary Session of the
Eleventh Central Committee in December 1978, the landmark start of
China's reforms that were the brainchild of Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
In just one year, the pilot reforms of the Xiaogang villagers
turned them from starving beggars into people with food and
clothing. And, farmers in other parts of the country followed
their example the following year and later.
</P>
<P>
As a result, Xiaogang is seen by many as the cradle of China's
rural reforms.
</P>
<P>
For many years, Yan has never stopped his effort to help his
fellow villagers be better-off. He lives with his wife and four
children and last year made a good income from raising ducks.
</P>
<P>
He concluded, "I want to set an example for my fellow villagers
by doing so, and I want to tell them that if you work harder and
get wiser, you may become as rich as others."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0381 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
