<HEADLINE> Indonesian Government Sets up Council For Law, Order </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, December 9 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government on
Tuesday set up a crisis center to deal swiftly and comprehensively
with law, order and security, national newspapers reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
With an official title of the "Council for Security and Law
Enforcement", the center is headed by President B.J. Habibie, with
Defense Minister/Commander of the Armed Forces General Wiranto as
the executive chief (operations), and Justice Minister Muladi as
deputy chief.
</P>
<P>
Minister/State Secretary Akbar Tanjung told reporters that the
center was tasked with controlling and coordinating efforts to
tackle the crisis swiftly and comprehensively.
</P>
<P>
The crisis continues to threaten national stability and law
enforcement, he said.
</P>
<P>
Following the resignation of former president Soeharto on May
21 this year, the country has been plagued by a series of violent
demonstrations and mass riots.
</P>
<P>
The latest riots have taken place in Ketapang, central Jakarta
and in Kupang, capital of East Nusa Tenggara province, have
undertones of religious conflict.
</P>
<P>
Tanjung said the center has 32 members, 22 of whom are cabinet
ministers, while the other include Police chief Roesmanhadi,
Attorney General Andi Ghalib, Chief of the Intelligence
Coordinating Board BAKIN Zacky Makarim, newly elected Chairman of
the Human Rights Commission Komnas HAM Marzuki Darusman and
religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
Marzuki told reporters that the center will function as a forum
to facilitate communication to help build calm within the public.
</P>
</TEXT>
