<HEADLINE> Koloskov Reelected Head of Russian Soccer Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Vyacheslav Koloskov was
reelected president of the Russian Soccer Union on Tuesday,
ending two months of a sometimes nasty race for the position.
</P>
<P>
Koloskov netted 52 votes in secret balloting. His strongest
rival, Russian Soccer League President Nikolai Tolstykh, got only
eight votes.
</P>
<P>
The victory will add five more years to Koloskov's 20-year
reign at the top of Russian soccer.
</P>
<P>
Death threats, corruption and millions of dollars had been the
hot topics for the fierce election for the most enticing position
in Russian sport.
</P>
<P>
The campaign had seen mud fly from the contenders.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Koloskov accused Tolstykh of making death threats
through a third person.
</P>
<P>
Tolstykh denied the accusation but he did blame Koloskov for
the misuse of funds and said last week that millions of dollars
were not put into Russian soccer but hidden abroad, The Moscow
Times reported.
</P>
<P>
Another candidate was Kirsan Ilyumzhinov, president of the
Russian republic of Kalmykia. Ilymzhinov, incumbent president of
the World Chess Federation, guaranteed that Russia would win the
World Cup in 2002 if he was elected. He also offered to spend 6
million dollars to help Russian soccer.
</P>
<P>
Russian soccer is now at an all-time low. It failed to qualify
for the World Cup for the first time in 20 years this year.
</P>
<P>
The national team's recent defeat to tiny Iceland has put its
chance of qualifying for the European championships at almost
zero. 
</P>
</TEXT>
