<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Releases New Defense of Clinton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The White House released a
184-page detailed defense of President Bill Clinton on Tuesday,
saying that his conduct in the Monica Lewinsky matter was sinful
but did not warrant his removal from office.
</P>
<P>
"We believe a careful and fair review of the real record of
this case -- not the political attacks but the real record --
cannot justify the impeachment of the president," Clinton's
lawyers wrote in the document.
</P>
<P>
"We rely on the judgment of the House... to separate fact from
myth, the record from the rhetoric, and the sinful from the
impeachable," the document said.
</P>
<P>
The White House submitted the document to the House of
Representatives Judiciary Committee, which is holding hearings on
whether to impeach Clinton for his efforts to conceal his affair
with former White House intern Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
It was the third time Clinton's lawyers released documents to
counter Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr's allegations that
Clinton committed perjury, obstruction of justice and abuse of
power in trying to cover up the affair.
</P>
<P>
The document specifically denied those three allegations and
argued that Starr was biased in conducting his investigation.
</P>
<P>
The document argued that Clinton's conduct did not meet the
standard of "high crimes and misdemeanors" set for impeachment in
the Constitution. It also argued that impeachment was intended
only for political offenses against the state, not for private
wrongdoing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
