<HEADLINE> Judge McDonald Fails to Get U.N. Into Rebuking Belgrade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The president of the
U.N. International Criminal Tribunal for Former Yugoslavia, Judge
Gabrielle Kirk McDonald, Tuesday failed to get a Security Council
statement rebuking Belgrade for what she said its failure to
extradite three suspects accused of the 1991 massacre of 260
civilians in the Croatian city of Vukovar.
</P>
<P>
Judge McDoald's failure came after the Russian permanent
representative to the United Nations, Sergei Lavrov, prevented the
15-member Security Council from again rebuking the Federal
Republic of Yugoslavia on the issue of Vukovar.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council was prepared to issue a press statement,
but Lavrov refused to agree on the council's proposed action,
diplomats here said.
</P>
<P>
McDonald Tuesday briefed the Security Council on what she
described as Belgrade's non-compliance with relevant U.N.
resolutions and international obligations.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement read by her spokeswoman to the press
here, McDonald was falbbergasted that not only did Belgrade refuse
to extradite the three but had now asked the international
tribunal for its record, so it could conduct its own
investigation.
</P>
<P>
"Thus not only is (Belgrade) failing to abide by the explicit
requirements of Security Council resolutions, it is taking action
in direct contravention," she said.
</P>
<P>
At issue are three suspects, Mile Mrksic, Miroslav Radic and
Veselin Slijvancanin, indicted by the Hague-based tribunal in
November 1995 for their involvement in the killing of 260 people,
many of whom were said to be unarmed men forcibly removed from a
Vukovar hospital at the start of the Balkan war in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
