<HEADLINE> U.S., DPRK Extend Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The United States and the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) have agreed to extend
their talks on a U.S. demand for access to a DPRK underground
working site, the State Department said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. side alleged that the site could be part of a renewed
weapons program.
</P>
<P>
The two sides will meet again Thursday in New York, where the
talks started last Friday, State Department spokesman James Foley
told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Asked if there was any progress in the talks held in Washington
Monday and Tuesday, Foley said, "I have nothing to report on the
meeting, either positively or negatively. It's not something that
we do -- report on an ongoing negotiation."
</P>
<P>
The United States has said its aim attending the talks is to
secure access to the building site at the village of Kumchang-ri,
where the United States alleged there was an underground building
site that could be connected with a revived nuclear program.
</P>
<P>
The DPRK has denied that the building work was nuclear-related
and has asked the United States to promise 300 million dollars in
compensation if a search proved negative, which, however, was
rejected by Washington.
</P>
<P>
The talks coincided with a trip to Asia by President Bill
Clinton's newly appointed coordinator of policy toward the DPRK,
former Defense Secretary William Perry.
</P>
<P>
Perry was traveling "strictly in listening mode" to collect
information for his policy review, Foley told the reporters at a
briefing.
</P>
<P>
Foley said the United States had no plans for the moment to
ease any of its sanctions against the DPRK.
</P>
<P>
"If we were to see changes in North Korean attitudes on other
issues on concern including the missile area where we have
separate talks, we would be willing to look at an improved
relationship between the United States and North Korea in which
those kinds of issues, including sanctions, would be on the
table," he said.
</P>
<P>
"But we don't have plans to take any further steps on easing
sanctions at this time," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
