<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earth at Its Warmest in Past 12 Centuries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- U.S. climate scientist said
that the warming of the Earth in this century is without precedent
in at least 1200 years and this cannot be fully explained by any
known combination of natural forces, the Washington Post reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
A new research, presented at the American Geophysical Union in
San Francisco Monday, suggests that this century's warmer
temperatures are appearing more anomalous as scientists improve
their understanding of climate change in the past. Not only the
20th century produced the hottest years on record, but the
magnitude of change appears to be without parallel since at least
800 A.D.
</P>
<P>
The average temperature at the Earth's surface has risen about
1 degree Fahrenheit since 1880s, with many of the century's
warmest years occurring in the past decade. Scientists predict
1998 will surpass 1997 as the warmest year since record-keeping
began.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the meeting, Jonathan Overpeck, head of the
paleoclimatology program for the U.S. National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration, said that climate change as far back
as the Holy Roman Empire is strengthening the argument that humans
are partly responsible for the rising temperatures.
</P>
<P>
"Twentieth century global warming is a reality and should be
taken seriously," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0404 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Scientists Back Human Embryo Cloning </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, December 8 (Xinhua) -- British scientists advised
Tuesday that the British government should allow the cloning of
human embryos for research into new treatments that could
transform medicine into the next century.
</P>
<P>
The joint report, from the British Human Genetics Advisory
Commission (HGAC) and the Human Fertilization and Embryology
Authority (HFEA), is seen as a major vote of support for
development of human cells to replace those damaged by disease.
</P>
<P>
The joint HGAC/HFEA Cloning Working Group report advised that
while cloning of grown human beings should remain outlawed,
early-stage embryos are a legitimate subject for research, and the
rigid rules should be relaxed in this case.
</P>
<P>
The British government should introduce legislation explicitly
banning human reproductive cloning, which would effectively
separate the issue of reproductive cloning from cloning as part of
the search for new therapies, the report said.
</P>
<P>
It recommended that British Health Secretary Frank Dobson
should consider changing the regulations so that the HFEA can
issue licenses for the "development of therapeutic treatments for
diseased or damaged tissues or organs."
</P>
<P>
The recommendation followed new development by American
scientists who have succeeded in isolating and growing cultures of
human embryonic stem cells, the undeveloped parents of all the
tissues in the body.
</P>
<P>
It is hoped that this could ultimately lead to the growth of
replacement tissue in laboratories, which would avoid all the
usual transplant problems of rejection.
</P>
<P>
Scientists forecast a day when brain cells are harvested to
replace those lost through degenerative disorders such as
Parkinson's and Alzheimer's disease, and muscle tissue and perhaps
even whole organs are grown from scratch.
</P>
<P>
But the key to such breakthroughs is cloning copies of
early-stage embryos from which stem cells can be taken.
</P>
<P>
However, critics have said that the move would be ill-advised,
and have suggested that the motivation may be more to prevent
Britain from falling behind the United States in research
techniques than for genuine advancement of human welfare. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0405 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 21:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Says U.S. Late to Remove It From Drug List </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, December 8 (Xinhua) -- Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal
Kharrazi said on Tuesday that the United States was extremely
late in removing Tehran from a U.S. list of Main drug-producing
countries.
</P>
<P>
"No country can deny the significant role of the Islamic
Republic of Iran in campaign against narcotics," Kharrazi was
quoted by the official news agency IRNA as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said that Iran has been waging a war against drug
traffickers and so far 2,350 Iranian anti-drug fighters have been
killed.
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. has been very late in admitting this reality,"
Kharrazi said.
</P>
<P>
The U. S. announced on Monday that it has removed Iran and
Malaysia from the list of countries considered to be major drug
producers or transit nations.
</P>
<P>
However, local analysts said the U.S. decision did not
mean any change in Washington's hostile attitude towards Tehran.
</P>
<P>
A commentary on Iranian radio Tuesday said the U.S. decision is
meaningless. "whether the name of Iran is included or not included
in the annual list of the American government will not remove
anything or add anything to the reality of Iran's campaign against
international drug trafficking," the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Tehran started its campaign against drug trafficking in 1989
after the Iranian Majlis pass a strict anti-drug law, which
allows death penalty on those caught with more than 30 grams of
heroin or five kilograms of opium.
</P>
<P>
Iran has been used as a transit route by drug traffickers who
had been smuggling drugs from border areas of Afghanistan and
Pakistan into Iran and onto Europe.
</P>
<P>
Iran has confiscated 110 tonnes of various narcotics since
the beginning of this Iranian calendar year (to end March 20,
1999), senior Iranian officials said.
</P>
<P>
During the past years, Tehran has frequently blasted Washington
for keeping it on the list of drug states, ignoring Iran's efforts
in fighting narcotics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0406 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-08 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Finances Industry Upgrading in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, December 8 (Xinhua) -- The European Union (EU) will
grant 250 million ECUs (300 million U.S. dollars) to Egypt to
finance the country's industry upgrading.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by EU representative office in Cairo on
Tuesday said Egypt's program to modernize its industries is one of
the most important projects in its economic liberalization process.
</P>
<P>
The grant was finalized in last month's talks on a partnership
agreement between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The EU also agreed to supply Egypt with a loan of 402 million
ECUs (482.4 million dollars) in the coming three years for the
industry modernization program.
</P>
<P>
The grant is the largest of its kind that the 15-nation
EU has so far extended to Egypt, the Middle East News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The efforts of the Egyptian government to promote industries are
aimed at forming a solid economic basis that can enable Egypt to
play a key role in the proposed Euro-Mediterranean free trade
zone, which is planned to be set up in 2010, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The free trade zone is one of the results achieved in the
conference held in Barcelona, Spain, in 1995, between the EU
members and 12 countries, including Egypt, along the southern and
western coast of the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
The countries participating in the Barcelona process, or
Euro-Med partnership, have pledged join efforts to boost
regional security, economic integration and social development,
the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19981209.0407 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-12-09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NATO Must Be Equipped to Respond: Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, December 8 (Xinhua) -- United States Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright said Tuesday that the Western military
alliance must be better equipped to respond to outside crises as
well.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the NATO foreign ministers council meeting,
Albright said that the threats NATO allies face today and tomorrow
could come from a number of different sources, including from
areas beyond NATO's immediate borders.
</P>
<P>
If the threats are not addressed early and effectively, the
U.S. secretary of state asserted, they could grow into Article V
threats.
</P>
<P>
Article Five of the NATO Washington Treaty gives the alliance
the right for collective self-defense against invasion.
</P>
<P>
NATO foreign ministers gathered here for a final formal
discussion on the formulation of the future strategic concept of
the alliance that is to be unveiled at next April's NATO summit at
heads of state and government level.
</P>
<P>
They agreed that the new strategic concept must be "fully
consistent with the alliance's new security environment" and
should reaffirm the alliance's commitment to collective defense
and the transatlantic link.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued after the council meeting said that the new
strategic concept should render NATO an alliance ready and with a
full range of capabilities to enhance security and stability for
countries in the Euro-Atlantic area in the next century and to
implement non-Article V crisis response operations outside the
NATO geographical area.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. secretary of state described the new strategic concept
as an updated one that has to find the right balance between
affirming the centrality of Article V collective defense missions
and ensuring that the fundamental tasks of the alliance are
intimately related to the broader defense of the allies' common
interests.
</P>
<P>
"Common sense tells us that it is sometimes better to deal with
instability when it is still at arm's length than to wait until it
is at the doorstep," Albright added.
</P>
<P>
Some European allies, led by France, are opposed to the United
States' stance concerning non-Article V missions. They argue that
the military missions outside the NATO geographical area should be
enshrined by United Nations mandates.
</P>
<P>
The United States and its European allies had opposing views
when they prepared for the crisis-management mission in Kosovo.
The United States said that NATO did not need a U.N. mandate to
act whereas several of its European allies argued that NATO
missions outside its traditional geographical area had to be based
on a legality in the form of United Nations mandates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
