<HEADLINE> Xinhua Mideast News Summary at 21:30 GMT, December 8 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN -- Iran and Iraq on Tuesday swapped the remains of 121
Iranian and 213 Iraqi soldiers killed in the 1980-1988 war, Tehran
radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The exchange took place at the border point of Shalamcheh,
Iran's southwestern province of Khuzestan, the report said.
(BC-Iran-Iraq-Remains Swap)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan has informed Iran
that the United Arab Emirates (UAE) is ready to resume talks with
it over the three disputed islands in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
After meeting with UAE President Sheikh Zayed Bin Sultan
Al-Nahyan in Abu Dhabi, Annan talked with Iranian Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi on phone Monday night to inform him of the
emirates' readiness.
(BC-Iran-UAE-Talks)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Clashes between Palestinian protesters and Israeli
troops in the West Bank continued Tuesday, but the demonstrations
were scaled down compared with Monday.
</P>
<P>
Two Palestinians were hurt when the Israeli soldiers fired
rubber-coated bullets at the Palestinian stone throwers near the
West Bank city of Bethlehem.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a Israeli girl was slightly injured there as the
Palestinian demonstrators hurled stones at the car she was driving.
BC-Palestine-Demonstrations
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Jamil Al-Hugailan was reelected secretary general
of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) Tuesday at the regional
bloc's 19th summit.
</P>
<P>
Hugailan was first elected chief of GCC in 1995 at the 6th GCC
summit held in Muscat, Oman.
BC-GCC-Secretary General
</P>
<P>
- - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- U.N. arms inspectors started their surprise visits
to some Iraqi sites on Tuesday, confirmed an Iraqi official.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the Iraqi News Agency (INA), Hussam Mohammed
Ameen, head of Iraqi liaison with U.N. arms inspectors, said nine
groups of the U.N. Special Commission (UNSCOM) and the
International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) made surprise visits to
24 Iraqi sites. (BC-Iraq-UNSCOM)


08/12/98 21:36 GMT

NNNN
05:38 05:38 g # PAB
</P>
